ice care. My oldest granddaughter will soon be driving, and I have a new grandchild arriving any day now. When my youngest son calls me as he walks from the subway in New York, I shudder at the cacophony of the urban chaos. When the media reports that a youth suffered “fatal wounds” I whisper a prayer before I read the name. The truth is this: our worlds can change in one phone call.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Yet I don’t want my words here to mar an affirming song and darken it with worry and the &nbsp;‘what-ifs’. I am way too joyous and hopeful for that stance. Rather, I share a philosophy that simply reminds us to stay in the moment, cherish that boy behind the badge; rock that baby a bit longer and smile because, as Carl Sandburg wrote, “A new baby is God’s opinion that the world should go on.”<br>Trust that we never run out of time for kisses and hugs, and when love-filled words are on our lips, we let them go with wild abandon. Love. Now. Say it. Now. Forgive. Now. Savor it. Now.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; “If the angels call tomorrow, there is nothing that we hadn’t said.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; And now….I am going to love you, like I just might lose you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Because there is no better way to say hello or good-bye than with words laced in love.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Lyrics to Live By: Valentine’s Day and Beyond','','inherit','closed','closed','','32-revision-v1','','','2026-03-17 22:59:53','2026-03-17 22:59:53','',32,'https://ajsbsd.net/?p=33',0,'revision','',0),
(34,1,'2016-01-06 23:35:00','2016-01-06 23:35:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am a dreamer. Oh, not in that romantic, weepy, swooning, Coke commercial kind of dreamer way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well…now that I put it in print and re-read it, yeah, I am. But what I am trying to tell you is that I dream every night when I sleep. And I remember the dreams. All bazillion of them. I do believe this is the reason I awaken tired, with crazy hair, and the animals have fled my bed because they can’t take it anymore. If you really know me, this is no big news. You have already heard about my bizarre adventures during my night-night time. I think my sandman is on crack.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I also love to sing. And if I am a bad dreamer, I am even a badder singer. &nbsp;(It’s my blog. My bad grammar. I am not in the classroom at the moment, so get over it).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>How do I know I sing badly? &nbsp;Well, folks let me tell you. When my four children were young, I would sing them lullabies. You know, lyrics from Broadway musicals, church songs, and holiday songs. My little ones would place their hands over their ears and beg, “Mommy, we promise we will go to sleep if you will stop singing.” I got the hint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Which brings me to my bad singing and bad dreams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I dreamt the other night that I was singing in my shower and a scary male person threw open the shower curtain and assaulted me. Suddenly, as dreams go, I was in the courtroom facing my assailant. The judge asked me to tell what happened on that fateful morning. I replied that I was taking a shower and singing. I saw the guy, freaked out, and remembered nothing after that. &nbsp;The judge was peering at me and asked what I had been singing. I innocently responded that I was crooning, ‘I’m Dreaming of a White Christmas’. &nbsp;She then asked me to sing a few measures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well, I’ll be darned. I had hardly gotten to the good part when she slammed down her gavel and bellowed, “CASE DISMISSED!”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What??? I had a bad dream that I sang so bad that the case was dismissed because the attacker had to be subjected to my vocals?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where’s the justice in that?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Maybe tonight I will get a good night’s sleep and just stick to snoring.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s so much safer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','“But Your Honor….I was Just Singing in the Shower!”','','publish','open','open','','but-your-honor-i-was-just-singing-in-the-shower','','','2026-03-17 23:35:35','2026-03-17 23:35:35','',0,'https://ajsbsd.net/?p=34',0,'post','',0),
(35,1,'2026-03-17 23:35:35','2026-03-17 23:35:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am a dreamer. Oh, not in that romantic, weepy, swooning, Coke commercial kind of dreamer way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well…now that I put it in print and re-read it, yeah, I am. But what I am trying to tell you is that I dream every night when I sleep. And I remember the dreams. All bazillion of them. I do believe this is the reason I awaken tired, with crazy hair, and the animals have fled my bed because they can’t take it anymore. If you really know me, this is no big news. You have already heard about my bizarre adventures during my night-night time. I think my sandman is on crack.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I also love to sing. And if I am a bad dreamer, I am even a badder singer. &nbsp;(It’s my blog. My bad grammar. I am not in the classroom at the moment, so get over it).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>How do I know I sing badly? &nbsp;Well, folks let me tell you. When my four children were young, I would sing them lullabies. You know, lyrics from Broadway musicals, church songs, and holiday songs. My little ones would place their hands over their ears and beg, “Mommy, we promise we will go to sleep if you will stop singing.” I got the hint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Which brings me to my bad singing and bad dreams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I dreamt the other night that I was singing in my shower and a scary male person threw open the shower curtain and assaulted me. Suddenly, as dreams go, I was in the courtroom facing my assailant. The judge asked me to tell what happened on that fateful morning. I replied that I was taking a shower and singing. I saw the guy, freaked out, and remembered nothing after that. &nbsp;The judge was peering at me and asked what I had been singing. I innocently responded that I was crooning, ‘I’m Dreaming of a White Christmas’. &nbsp;She then asked me to sing a few measures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well, I’ll be darned. I had hardly gotten to the good part when she slammed down her gavel and bellowed, “CASE DISMISSED!”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What??? I had a bad dream that I sang so bad that the case was dismissed because the attacker had to be subjected to my vocals?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where’s the justice in that?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Maybe tonight I will get a good night’s sleep and just stick to snoring.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s so much safer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','“But Your Honor….I was Just Singing in the Shower!”','','inherit','closed','closed','','34-revision-v1','','','2026-03-17 23:35:35','2026-03-17 23:35:35','',34,'https://ajsbsd.net/?p=35',0,'revision','',0),
(39,1,'2026-05-12 02:41:49','2026-05-12 02:41:49','{\n    \"blogdescription\": {\n        \"value\": \"Everything wonderful starts on paper\",\n        \"type\": \"option\",\n        \"user_id\": 1,\n        \"date_modified_gmt\": \"2026-05-12 02:41:49\"\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','e4be687c-f40f-43f6-948c-2db9ac819fca','','','2026-05-12 02:41:49','2026-05-12 02:41:49','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/2026/05/12/e4be687c-f40f-43f6-948c-2db9ac819fca/',0,'customize_changeset','',0),
(40,1,'2026-05-12 02:49:17','2026-05-12 02:49:17','{\n    \"blogdescription\": {\n        \"value\": \"Everything wonderful starts on paper.\",\n        \"type\": \"option\",\n        \"user_id\": 1,\n        \"date_modified_gmt\": \"2026-05-12 02:49:17\"\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','421cfd25-beaf-42cd-968d-a643959ab6fe','','','2026-05-12 02:49:17','2026-05-12 02:49:17','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/2026/05/12/421cfd25-beaf-42cd-968d-a643959ab6fe/',0,'customize_changeset','',0),
(42,1,'2026-05-16 18:53:02','2026-05-16 18:53:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pat Buchanan did not serve in the military.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While he participated in the Reserve Officers\' Training Corps (ROTC) program during his undergraduate years at Georgetown University, he did not complete it. Upon graduating in 1960, he received a selective service draft notice but was granted a medical exemption by the District of Columbia Draft Board.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was classified as 4-F (unfit for military service) due to reactive arthritis (a form of inflammatory arthritis). He subsequently moved directly into his graduate studies in journalism at Columbia University and began his career in media and politics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Pat Buchanan','','trash','open','open','','pat-buchanan__trashed','','','2026-05-16 20:42:44','2026-05-16 20:42:44','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=42',0,'post','',0),
(43,1,'2026-05-16 18:53:02','2026-05-16 18:53:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pat Buchanan did not serve in the military.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While he participated in the Reserve Officers\' Training Corps (ROTC) program during his undergraduate years at Georgetown University, he did not complete it. Upon graduating in 1960, he received a selective service draft notice but was granted a medical exemption by the District of Columbia Draft Board.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was classified as 4-F (unfit for military service) due to reactive arthritis (a form of inflammatory arthritis). He subsequently moved directly into his graduate studies in journalism at Columbia University and began his career in media and politics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Pat Buchanan','','inherit','closed','closed','','42-revision-v1','','','2026-05-16 18:53:02','2026-05-16 18:53:02','',42,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=43',0,'revision','',0),
(44,1,'2026-05-18 07:41:54','2026-05-18 07:41:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While both Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski were prominent female politicians whose sudden and tragic deaths while in office deeply impacted their respective nations, the circumstances surrounding how they died are entirely different.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is a comparison and contrast of the two events based on the documented facts of their passings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Commonalities (Compare)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Active Public Servants:</strong> Both women were sitting lawmakers actively serving their constituents at the time of their deaths. Jo Cox was a British Labour Party Member of Parliament (MP) representing Batley and Spen, and Jackie Walorski was a Republican U.S. Representative for Indiana\'s 2nd congressional district.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Died While on Duty:</strong> Both died while traveling to or from official community events within their respective districts. Cox was on her way to meet with local residents at a routine constituency surgery in Birstall, West Yorkshire. Walorski was returning from a ribbon-cutting ceremony in Claypool, Indiana.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>National Mourning:</strong> Both tragedies prompted immense grief across the political spectrum in their home countries. Following their deaths, flags were ordered to be flown at half-staff at major government landmarks—including the Palace of Westminster and the U.S. Capitol Building—and political figures from opposing parties publicly united to honor their service.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Differences (Contrast)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><td><strong>Feature</strong></td><td><strong>Jo Cox (UK)</strong></td><td><strong>Jackie Walorski (US)</strong></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Cause of Death</strong></td><td>Intentionally targeted and murdered in an act of domestic terrorism.</td><td>Killed in a multi-vehicle highway traffic accident.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Nature of the Incident</strong></td><td>She was shot and stabbed multiple times outside a local library by an attacker using a modified hunting rifle and a dagger.</td><td>She was a passenger in a Toyota RAV4 that was involved in a head-on collision with a Buick LeSabre.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Perpetrator / Fault</strong></td><td>Her attacker, Thomas Mair, acted out of far-right extremism and white supremacist motives. He was convicted of murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.</td><td>A police investigation determined that the vehicle Walorski was riding in, driven by her staffer, crossed the center line to overtake a truck, causing the crash. No criminal intent was involved.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Additional Casualties</strong></td><td>A 77-year-old bystander was injured while attempting to intervene and save her life.</td><td>Three other people died in the crash: two of Walorski\'s congressional staffers riding with her (Zachery Potts and Emma Thomson) and the driver of the other vehicle (Edith Schmucker).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Year &amp; Location</strong></td><td>June 2016 in Birstall, West Yorkshire, England.</td><td>August 2022 in Elkhart County, Indiana, United States.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_c978974613e3f0b3-39\">In summary, while both losses took the lives of dedicated representatives mid-career, Jo Cox was the victim of a premeditated, ideologically motivated assassination, whereas Jackie Walorski died in a tragic vehicular accident alongside members of her staff.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski','','trash','open','open','','jo-cox-and-jackie-walorski__trashed','','','2026-05-18 14:49:25','2026-05-18 14:49:25','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=44',0,'post','',0),
(45,1,'2026-05-18 07:41:54','2026-05-18 07:41:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While both Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski were prominent female politicians whose sudden and tragic deaths while in office deeply impacted their respective nations, the circumstances surrounding how they died are entirely different.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is a comparison and contrast of the two events based on the documented facts of their passings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Commonalities (Compare)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Active Public Servants:</strong> Both women were sitting lawmakers actively serving their constituents at the time of their deaths. Jo Cox was a British Labour Party Member of Parliament (MP) representing Batley and Spen, and Jackie Walorski was a Republican U.S. Representative for Indiana\'s 2nd congressional district.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Died While on Duty:</strong> Both died while traveling to or from official community events within their respective districts. Cox was on her way to meet with local residents at a routine constituency surgery in Birstall, West Yorkshire. Walorski was returning from a ribbon-cutting ceremony in Claypool, Indiana.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>National Mourning:</strong> Both tragedies prompted immense grief across the political spectrum in their home countries. Following their deaths, flags were ordered to be flown at half-staff at major government landmarks—including the Palace of Westminster and the U.S. Capitol Building—and political figures from opposing parties publicly united to honor their service.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Differences (Contrast)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><td><strong>Feature</strong></td><td><strong>Jo Cox (UK)</strong></td><td><strong>Jackie Walorski (US)</strong></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Cause of Death</strong></td><td>Intentionally targeted and murdered in an act of domestic terrorism.</td><td>Killed in a multi-vehicle highway traffic accident.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Nature of the Incident</strong></td><td>She was shot and stabbed multiple times outside a local library by an attacker using a modified hunting rifle and a dagger.</td><td>She was a passenger in a Toyota RAV4 that was involved in a head-on collision with a Buick LeSabre.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Perpetrator / Fault</strong></td><td>Her attacker, Thomas Mair, acted out of far-right extremism and white supremacist motives. He was convicted of murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.</td><td>A police investigation determined that the vehicle Walorski was riding in, driven by her staffer, crossed the center line to overtake a truck, causing the crash. No criminal intent was involved.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Additional Casualties</strong></td><td>A 77-year-old bystander was injured while attempting to intervene and save her life.</td><td>Three other people died in the crash: two of Walorski\'s congressional staffers riding with her (Zachery Potts and Emma Thomson) and the driver of the other vehicle (Edith Schmucker).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Year &amp; Location</strong></td><td>June 2016 in Birstall, West Yorkshire, England.</td><td>August 2022 in Elkhart County, Indiana, United States.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_c978974613e3f0b3-39\">In summary, while both losses took the lives of dedicated representatives mid-career, Jo Cox was the victim of a premeditated, ideologically motivated assassination, whereas Jackie Walorski died in a tragic vehicular accident alongside members of her staff.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski','','inherit','closed','closed','','44-revision-v1','','','2026-05-18 07:41:54','2026-05-18 07:41:54','',44,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=45',0,'revision','',0),
(46,1,'2026-05-18 07:48:12','2026-05-18 07:48:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrating the <strong>Brexit</strong> and <strong>Trump-Russia</strong> angles into the discussion of Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski reveals a striking contrast in how their respective political eras—and the hyper-polarized geopolitical climates they existed in—defined their lives and legacies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the geopolitical forces surrounding them were similarly chaotic, the connection to these specific angles is deeply intrinsic to the death of Jo Cox, whereas for Jackie Walorski, it was part of the broader political backdrop of her career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Jo Cox and the Brexit Angle: A Direct Catalyst</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The connection between Jo Cox’s murder and Brexit is profound, direct, and universally recognized as a defining moment of modern British political history.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>An Intimate Connection to the Campaign:</strong> Jo Cox was killed on June 16, 2016—exactly one week before the United Kingdom voted in the historic EU Referendum. She was a passionate, highly vocal campaigner for the \"Remain\" camp, advocating for Britain to stay in the European Union. She championed multiculturalism, immigration, and the rights of Syrian refugees.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Ideological Motive:</strong> Her assassin, Thomas Mair, targeted her specifically because of her pro-EU and pro-immigration stances, which far-right nationalists viewed as \"treason.\" During the attack, witnesses heard him shout, <em>\"This is for Britain!\"</em> and <em>\"Keep Britain independent!\"</em> When later asked to state his name in court, he said, <em>\"Death to traitors, freedom for Britain.\"</em></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Nation at a \"Breaking Point\":</strong> Cox’s death occurred at the peak of an incredibly vitriolic referendum campaign. On the very morning she was killed, the pro-Brexit UK Independence Party (UKIP) unveiled their infamous \"Breaking Point\" billboard, showing a massive line of non-white refugees. Following her murder, both the Leave and Remain campaigns suspended activities out of respect. Her assassination stands as a tragic monument to how political rhetoric surrounding Brexit escalated into real-world violence.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Jackie Walorski and the Trump-Russia Angle: The Political Backdrop</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike Jo Cox, whose death was directly triggered by the political flashpoint of her country, Jackie Walorski’s tragic death in a 2022 car accident had no connection to her political views. However, her career was heavily shaped by the <strong>Trump-Russia</strong> dynamic that reshaped the American Republican Party during her tenure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Staunch Trump Ally:</strong> Representing a conservative district in Indiana, Walorski pivoted from being a traditional corporate Republican to a loyal ally of Donald Trump following his 2016 election. As the Trump-Russia investigation (the Mueller Probe) dominated Washington, Walorski consistently aligned with the Trump administration, viewing the investigations as a partisan \"witch hunt\" designed to delegitimize Trump\'s victory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Voting Record:</strong> She voted against both Trump impeachments—the first of which was tied to foreign leverage regarding Ukraine, a geopolitical flashpoint inherently tied to U.S.-Russia relations. She also supported Trump\'s \"America First\" foreign policy, which moved away from traditional, hawkish international interventionism.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sanctioned by Russia:</strong> Despite the domestic political battles over the \"Trump-Russia\" narrative, Walorski’s official legislative stance toward Russian aggression was aligned with broader U.S. policy. Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, she voted in favor of massive U.S. aid packages to Ukraine and strict economic penalties against Moscow. Because of this, she was officially placed on a Kremlin blacklist and sanctioned by the Russian Foreign Ministry in April 2022, just months before her death.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary of the Angles</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The intersection of these two global political shifts highlights a fundamental difference in how we view both tragedies:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jo Cox</strong> became a literal martyr of the Brexit debate. Her assassination was the direct, horrific culmination of a highly localized, fiercely toxic ideological battle over national identity and international alignment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jackie Walorski</strong> was a lawmaker operating within the institutional machinery of the Trump era. The Trump-Russia angle defines the polarizing political environment she fought in, her alignment with the populist shift in the GOP, and her stance against adversarial foreign regimes—but it remains entirely separate from the tragic, accidental nature of her passing.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Jo Cox and the Brexit Angle','','trash','open','open','','jo-cox-and-the-brexit-angle__trashed','','','2026-05-18 14:49:25','2026-05-18 14:49:25','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=46',0,'post','',0),
(47,1,'2026-05-18 07:48:12','2026-05-18 07:48:12','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrating the <strong>Brexit</strong> and <strong>Trump-Russia</strong> angles into the discussion of Jo Cox and Jackie Walorski reveals a striking contrast in how their respective political eras—and the hyper-polarized geopolitical climates they existed in—defined their lives and legacies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the geopolitical forces surrounding them were similarly chaotic, the connection to these specific angles is deeply intrinsic to the death of Jo Cox, whereas for Jackie Walorski, it was part of the broader political backdrop of her career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Jo Cox and the Brexit Angle: A Direct Catalyst</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The connection between Jo Cox’s murder and Brexit is profound, direct, and universally recognized as a defining moment of modern British political history.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>An Intimate Connection to the Campaign:</strong> Jo Cox was killed on June 16, 2016—exactly one week before the United Kingdom voted in the historic EU Referendum. She was a passionate, highly vocal campaigner for the \"Remain\" camp, advocating for Britain to stay in the European Union. She championed multiculturalism, immigration, and the rights of Syrian refugees.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Ideological Motive:</strong> Her assassin, Thomas Mair, targeted her specifically because of her pro-EU and pro-immigration stances, which far-right nationalists viewed as \"treason.\" During the attack, witnesses heard him shout, <em>\"This is for Britain!\"</em> and <em>\"Keep Britain independent!\"</em> When later asked to state his name in court, he said, <em>\"Death to traitors, freedom for Britain.\"</em></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Nation at a \"Breaking Point\":</strong> Cox’s death occurred at the peak of an incredibly vitriolic referendum campaign. On the very morning she was killed, the pro-Brexit UK Independence Party (UKIP) unveiled their infamous \"Breaking Point\" billboard, showing a massive line of non-white refugees. Following her murder, both the Leave and Remain campaigns suspended activities out of respect. Her assassination stands as a tragic monument to how political rhetoric surrounding Brexit escalated into real-world violence.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Jackie Walorski and the Trump-Russia Angle: The Political Backdrop</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike Jo Cox, whose death was directly triggered by the political flashpoint of her country, Jackie Walorski’s tragic death in a 2022 car accident had no connection to her political views. However, her career was heavily shaped by the <strong>Trump-Russia</strong> dynamic that reshaped the American Republican Party during her tenure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Staunch Trump Ally:</strong> Representing a conservative district in Indiana, Walorski pivoted from being a traditional corporate Republican to a loyal ally of Donald Trump following his 2016 election. As the Trump-Russia investigation (the Mueller Probe) dominated Washington, Walorski consistently aligned with the Trump administration, viewing the investigations as a partisan \"witch hunt\" designed to delegitimize Trump\'s victory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Voting Record:</strong> She voted against both Trump impeachments—the first of which was tied to foreign leverage regarding Ukraine, a geopolitical flashpoint inherently tied to U.S.-Russia relations. She also supported Trump\'s \"America First\" foreign policy, which moved away from traditional, hawkish international interventionism.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sanctioned by Russia:</strong> Despite the domestic political battles over the \"Trump-Russia\" narrative, Walorski’s official legislative stance toward Russian aggression was aligned with broader U.S. policy. Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, she voted in favor of massive U.S. aid packages to Ukraine and strict economic penalties against Moscow. Because of this, she was officially placed on a Kremlin blacklist and sanctioned by the Russian Foreign Ministry in April 2022, just months before her death.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary of the Angles</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The intersection of these two global political shifts highlights a fundamental difference in how we view both tragedies:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jo Cox</strong> became a literal martyr of the Brexit debate. Her assassination was the direct, horrific culmination of a highly localized, fiercely toxic ideological battle over national identity and international alignment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jackie Walorski</strong> was a lawmaker operating within the institutional machinery of the Trump era. The Trump-Russia angle defines the polarizing political environment she fought in, her alignment with the populist shift in the GOP, and her stance against adversarial foreign regimes—but it remains entirely separate from the tragic, accidental nature of her passing.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Jo Cox and the Brexit Angle','','inherit','closed','closed','','46-revision-v1','','','2026-05-18 07:48:12','2026-05-18 07:48:12','',46,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=47',0,'revision','',0),
(48,1,'2026-05-18 11:07:13','2026-05-18 11:07:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Comparing <strong>Lagos</strong>, <strong>Winter Park</strong>, and <strong>Detroit</strong> is a study in contrasts. You are looking at a hyper-populated, rapidly developing African megacity alongside an affluent, brick-lined Florida suburb and a major American industrial city undergoing a cultural renaissance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because the currency, purchasing power, and local infrastructure vary wildly, the actual day-to-day cost of living looks completely different in each location.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Lagos, Nigeria 🇳🇬</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lagos is a massive, high-energy economic engine. For expats or those earning in foreign currencies (like USD), Lagos can offer a highly affordable baseline, but local economic pressures have caused severe inflation in recent years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Average Monthly Cost (Single Person):</strong><!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Local/Modest Lifestyle:</em> ₦250,000 to ₦350,000 per month.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Comfortable/Expat Lifestyle:</em> ₦600,000+ per month (roughly <strong>$400 – $600 USD</strong>, depending on fluctuating exchange rates).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Housing:</strong> Extremely fragmented. Renting a modern 1-bedroom apartment in secure, upscale neighborhoods on \"The Island\" (like Victoria Island or Ikoyi) can cost anywhere from $500 to over $1,500 USD a month, often requiring a full year\'s rent upfront. Meanwhile, living on \"The Mainland\" is a fraction of that cost.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Hidden Costs:</strong> Infrastructure challenges mean you must factor in alternative power. Most comfortable households rely heavily on diesel/petrol generators or solar inverter systems due to grid instability, which significantly drives up utility bills.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Winter Park, Florida 🇺🇸</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_b6b8c5cafd52e72b-52\">Located just north of Orlando, Winter Park is an affluent, highly desirable community known for its upscale shopping, lakes, and pristine estates.<sup></sup> It is the most expensive city on this list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Average Monthly Cost (Single Person):</strong> Roughly <strong>$2,300 – $2,600</strong> (including rent).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Housing:</strong> This is the primary budget driver. The average rent for a 1-bedroom apartment sits around <strong>$1,450 – $1,520</strong>. Purchasing a home is also premium, with median home prices well above the national average.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Perks &amp; Trade-offs:</strong> Florida has no state income tax, which leaves more money in your paycheck. However, you will absolutely need a car to get around, meaning auto insurance and gas are mandatory monthly expenses.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Detroit, Michigan 🇺🇸</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_b6b8c5cafd52e72b-54\">Detroit offers an \"urban-affordable\" sweet spot.<sup></sup> While certain gentrified neighborhoods (like Downtown, Midtown, and Corktown) have seen a major spike in premium luxury pricing, the city as a whole remains right around the U.S. national average.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Average Monthly Cost (Single Person):</strong> Roughly <strong>$2,200 – $2,400</strong> (including rent).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Housing:</strong> Significantly more accessible than Winter Park. While luxury lofts in Midtown command high premiums, the citywide average for a standard 1-bedroom apartment sits around <strong>$1,100 – $1,150</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Hidden Costs:</strong> Michigan\'s car insurance rates are notoriously among the highest in the country, often costing drivers an extra $150–$200+ a month. Additionally, due to the harsh Great Lakes winters, heating costs from December through March will heavily inflate your winter utility bills.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">At-A-Glance Comparison Table</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><td><strong>Category</strong></td><td><strong>Lagos, Nigeria</strong></td><td><strong>Winter Park, FL</strong></td><td><strong>Detroit, MI</strong></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Overall Cost Level</strong></td><td>Very Low (if earning USD); High (on local wages due to inflation).</td><td>High (7% above U.S. average; highly affluent).</td><td>Moderate (sits right at the U.S. national average).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Avg. 1-Bed Rent</strong></td><td>$300 - $1,200+ USD <em>(Highly dependent on Island vs. Mainland)</em></td><td>$1,450 - $1,520</td><td>$1,100 - $1,150</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Transportation</strong></td><td>Cheap local transit (Danfos/BRT) or Uber; buying a car is highly expensive.</td><td>Car required. High gas/maintenance, standard insurance.</td><td>Car required. Highest auto insurance rates in the U.S.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Utilities</strong></td><td>High hidden costs (generator fuel, private water delivery).</td><td>Moderate (mostly AC/cooling costs in summer).</td><td>Variable (heavy heating costs in winter).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Dining / Groceries</strong></td><td>Cheap for local goods; expensive for imported Western products.</td><td>High-end dining options; average U.S. grocery costs.</td><td>Affordable local food scene; average U.S. grocery costs.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Takeaway:</strong> If you have a remote U.S. salary, your purchasing power will stretch the furthest in Lagos by an incredibly wide margin, though you compromise on public infrastructure. Between the two American cities, Detroit offers a much lower barrier to entry for housing, whereas Winter Park charges a premium for its suburban aesthetic and Florida sunshine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Lagos, Winter Park, and Detroit is a study in contrasts','','trash','open','open','','lagos-winter-park-and-detroit-is-a-study-in-contrasts__trashed','','','2026-05-18 14:49:25','2026-05-18 14:49:25','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=48',0,'post','',0),
(49,1,'2026-05-18 11:07:13','2026-05-18 11:07:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Comparing <strong>Lagos</strong>, <strong>Winter Park</strong>, and <strong>Detroit</strong> is a study in contrasts. You are looking at a hyper-populated, rapidly developing African megacity alongside an affluent, brick-lined Florida suburb and a major American industrial city undergoing a cultural renaissance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because the currency, purchasing power, and local infrastructure vary wildly, the actual day-to-day cost of living looks completely different in each location.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Lagos, Nigeria 🇳🇬</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lagos is a massive, high-energy economic engine. For expats or those earning in foreign currencies (like USD), Lagos can offer a highly affordable baseline, but local economic pressures have caused severe inflation in recent years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Average Monthly Cost (Single Person):</strong><!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Local/Modest Lifestyle:</em> ₦250,000 to ₦350,000 per month.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Comfortable/Expat Lifestyle:</em> ₦600,000+ per month (roughly <strong>$400 – $600 USD</strong>, depending on fluctuating exchange rates).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Housing:</strong> Extremely fragmented. Renting a modern 1-bedroom apartment in secure, upscale neighborhoods on \"The Island\" (like Victoria Island or Ikoyi) can cost anywhere from $500 to over $1,500 USD a month, often requiring a full year\'s rent upfront. Meanwhile,