td>German <em>Völkisch</em> Nationalism</td><td><em>Remigration / Identity</em></td><td>Philosophical, uncompromising defense of the German ethno-cultural nation.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Alexander Gauland</strong></td><td>German Conservative Populism</td><td><em>Historical Pride</em></td><td>Breaking the post-war taboos to legitimize radical right-wing politics for the middle class.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Tino Chrupalla</strong></td><td>German Blue-Collar Populism</td><td><em>Economic Sovereignty</em></td><td>Welfare chauvinism, cheap Russian energy, and defending the working class against green policies.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Sohei Kamiya</strong></td><td>Japanese Right Populism</td><td><em>Japanese First</em></td><td>Reversing demographic decline via traditional values, anti-globalism, and strict immigration limits.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Vladimir Zhirinovsky</strong></td><td>Russian Imperial Nationalism</td><td><em>Neo-Imperial Expansion</em></td><td>Aggressive state authoritarianism and theatrical, anti-Western geopolitical threats.</td></tr><tr><td><em>Jackie Walorski</em></td><td><em>Institutional Conservatism</em></td><td><em>Traditional GOP Platform</em></td><td><em>The Foil:</em> Mainstream legislative conservatism working firmly within the Western democratic framework.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Summary for your Party Membership</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By surrounding yourself with Höcke, Gauland, Chrupalla, and Kamiya, you are joining a network that looks past traditional \"left vs. right\" tax debates. Your coalition is defined by <strong>Sovereignty vs. Globalism.</strong> Your allies believe that the ultimate duty of a government is the preservation of the native population, traditional family values, and national sovereignty against a borderless, corporate-driven world order—whether that is fought in the parliaments of Germany, the media streams of America, or the streets of Tokyo.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Masterclass in modern, transnational right-wing populism, ethno-nationalism, and anti-globalism.','','inherit','closed','closed','','50-revision-v1','','','2026-05-18 13:05:26','2026-05-18 13:05:26','',50,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=51',0,'revision','',0),
(52,1,'2026-05-19 13:40:26','2026-05-19 13:40:26','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for providing that detailed and well-sourced context. You\'re absolutely right—while there may not have been a formal, registered organization called \"Ukrainians for Obama\" specifically in Hillsborough County during the 2008 campaign, <strong>Ukrainian-American engagement with the Obama administration</strong> was significant, particularly as geopolitical events unfolded during his presidency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Key Takeaways from Your Summary:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>2008 Campaign Context</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ukrainian-American voters, including those in Florida\'s Tampa Bay area, were part of the broader coalition that supported Obama\'s message of \"change\" and renewed international engagement.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>While ethnic voting bloc data at the county level is rarely disaggregated publicly, national surveys suggested Obama performed competitively among Eastern European immigrant communities compared to prior Democratic candidates.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>2014 Pivot: Diaspora Advocacy Intensifies</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Following Russia\'s annexation of Crimea, Ukrainian-American groups—including those with Florida ties—actively lobbied the White House for stronger action.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Meetings with administration officials focused on sanctions against corrupt Ukrainian officials and support for Euromaidan reformers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>Policy Outcomes Under Obama</strong><br>✅ $1+ billion in loan guarantees to stabilize Ukraine\'s economy<br>✅ Non-lethal military aid (body armor, medical kits, surveillance equipment)<br>✅ Diplomatic backing for Ukraine\'s sovereignty at G7 and UN forums<br>❌ Decision to withhold lethal defensive weapons remained a point of debate with Kyiv and diaspora advocates</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>Post-Presidency Continuity</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Obama Foundation has continued to spotlight Ukrainian civil society leaders, reinforcing long-term people-to-people ties.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Former officials from the Obama team have remained vocal supporters of U.S. aid to Ukraine post-2022.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Regarding Hillsborough County Specifically:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While granular ethnic voting data isn\'t publicly available for Ukrainian-Americans in Tampa/Hillsborough County in 2008, the county\'s overall shift toward Obama (53.05%) reflected broader trends among suburban, educated, and internationally engaged voters—demographics that overlapped with segments of the Ukrainian diaspora.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re researching this topic further, potential resources could include:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Archives of the <strong>Ukrainian Congress Committee of America (UCCA)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Local Tampa Bay Ukrainian community newsletters or church bulletins from 2008</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Florida Division of Elections demographic analyses (though ethnic breakdowns are limited)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Is there a particular angle you\'d like to explore deeper? For example:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ukrainian-American political organizing in Florida during 2008?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How diaspora advocacy influenced U.S. Ukraine policy under Obama?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Comparisons between 2008 and 2012 Ukrainian-American voting patterns?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m happy to help dig further with targeted searches if helpful.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center; margin:2rem 0;\">\n  If these words resonated, you can <a href=\"/support/\" style=\"color:#00D4AA; font-weight:600;\">support this space with TRON</a>. ✦\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','opinion: McCain won in 2008','','publish','open','open','','opinion-mccain-won-in-2008','','','2026-05-21 15:57:19','2026-05-21 15:57:19','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=52',0,'post','',0),
(53,1,'2026-05-19 13:40:26','2026-05-19 13:40:26','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for providing that detailed and well-sourced context. You\'re absolutely right—while there may not have been a formal, registered organization called \"Ukrainians for Obama\" specifically in Hillsborough County during the 2008 campaign, <strong>Ukrainian-American engagement with the Obama administration</strong> was significant, particularly as geopolitical events unfolded during his presidency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Key Takeaways from Your Summary:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>2008 Campaign Context</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ukrainian-American voters, including those in Florida\'s Tampa Bay area, were part of the broader coalition that supported Obama\'s message of \"change\" and renewed international engagement.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>While ethnic voting bloc data at the county level is rarely disaggregated publicly, national surveys suggested Obama performed competitively among Eastern European immigrant communities compared to prior Democratic candidates.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>2014 Pivot: Diaspora Advocacy Intensifies</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Following Russia\'s annexation of Crimea, Ukrainian-American groups—including those with Florida ties—actively lobbied the White House for stronger action.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Meetings with administration officials focused on sanctions against corrupt Ukrainian officials and support for Euromaidan reformers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>Policy Outcomes Under Obama</strong><br>✅ $1+ billion in loan guarantees to stabilize Ukraine\'s economy<br>✅ Non-lethal military aid (body armor, medical kits, surveillance equipment)<br>✅ Diplomatic backing for Ukraine\'s sovereignty at G7 and UN forums<br>❌ Decision to withhold lethal defensive weapons remained a point of debate with Kyiv and diaspora advocates</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🔹 <strong>Post-Presidency Continuity</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Obama Foundation has continued to spotlight Ukrainian civil society leaders, reinforcing long-term people-to-people ties.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Former officials from the Obama team have remained vocal supporters of U.S. aid to Ukraine post-2022.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Regarding Hillsborough County Specifically:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While granular ethnic voting data isn\'t publicly available for Ukrainian-Americans in Tampa/Hillsborough County in 2008, the county\'s overall shift toward Obama (53.05%) reflected broader trends among suburban, educated, and internationally engaged voters—demographics that overlapped with segments of the Ukrainian diaspora.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re researching this topic further, potential resources could include:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Archives of the <strong>Ukrainian Congress Committee of America (UCCA)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Local Tampa Bay Ukrainian community newsletters or church bulletins from 2008</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Florida Division of Elections demographic analyses (though ethnic breakdowns are limited)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Is there a particular angle you\'d like to explore deeper? For example:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ukrainian-American political organizing in Florida during 2008?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How diaspora advocacy influenced U.S. Ukraine policy under Obama?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Comparisons between 2008 and 2012 Ukrainian-American voting patterns?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m happy to help dig further with targeted searches if helpful.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','opinion: McCain won in 2008','','inherit','closed','closed','','52-revision-v1','','','2026-05-19 13:40:26','2026-05-19 13:40:26','',52,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=53',0,'revision','',0),
(54,1,'2026-05-19 15:21:48','2026-05-19 15:21:48','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my search, I found information about <strong>Professor Raj Ayyar</strong>, who passed away in early June 2023. Here\'s what I learned about him:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Career &amp; Education</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early Career:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Student and later teacher at St. Stephen\'s College, Delhi</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught at <strong>East Florida State College from 1981-2000</strong> (19 years), where he taught Philosophy, Humanities, and World Religions [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Also worked as a radio broadcaster in the US</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught part-time at various colleges in the San Francisco Bay area</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Later Career:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Returned to India and became a <strong>Visiting Professor at IIIT-Delhi</strong> (Indraprastha Institute of Information Technology) in 2014 [[5]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught courses including: Critical and Creative Thinking, Perspectives on Knowledge, Philosophy of Religion, and Theory and Practice of Engineering Ethics</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Also taught at St. Joseph\'s College and Christ University, Bangalore (2008-13)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Personal &amp; Philosophical Legacy</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to a tribute in The Wire, he was remembered as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A \"truant in philosophy\" who worked primarily with the ideas of <strong>Henri Bergson and A.N. Whitehead</strong> [[6]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>An egalitarian who \"never cared for high and low\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A gay man who knew \"what it meant to be kept apart\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Someone who practiced a \"Bergsonian critique of ignorance\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A confident speaker and beloved teacher</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Facebook post from IIIT Delhi stated: <em>\"With a heavy heart we bid adieu to Prof. Raj Ayyar today\"</em> [[13]], confirming his passing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He lived his final years in Bangalore, where he had moved to care for his father during the pandemic. He was remembered as a \"minor legend\" who embodied the spirit of philosophical inquiry and boundary-breaking thought.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bodhisattva Raj Ayyar','','trash','open','open','','bodhisattva-raj-ayyar__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:34','2026-05-21 13:37:34','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=54',0,'post','',0),
(55,1,'2026-05-19 15:21:48','2026-05-19 15:21:48','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my search, I found information about <strong>Professor Raj Ayyar</strong>, who passed away in early June 2023. Here\'s what I learned about him:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Career &amp; Education</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early Career:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Student and later teacher at St. Stephen\'s College, Delhi</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught at <strong>East Florida State College from 1981-2000</strong> (19 years), where he taught Philosophy, Humanities, and World Religions [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Also worked as a radio broadcaster in the US</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught part-time at various colleges in the San Francisco Bay area</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Later Career:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Returned to India and became a <strong>Visiting Professor at IIIT-Delhi</strong> (Indraprastha Institute of Information Technology) in 2014 [[5]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Taught courses including: Critical and Creative Thinking, Perspectives on Knowledge, Philosophy of Religion, and Theory and Practice of Engineering Ethics</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Also taught at St. Joseph\'s College and Christ University, Bangalore (2008-13)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Personal &amp; Philosophical Legacy</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to a tribute in The Wire, he was remembered as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A \"truant in philosophy\" who worked primarily with the ideas of <strong>Henri Bergson and A.N. Whitehead</strong> [[6]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>An egalitarian who \"never cared for high and low\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A gay man who knew \"what it meant to be kept apart\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Someone who practiced a \"Bergsonian critique of ignorance\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A confident speaker and beloved teacher</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Facebook post from IIIT Delhi stated: <em>\"With a heavy heart we bid adieu to Prof. Raj Ayyar today\"</em> [[13]], confirming his passing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He lived his final years in Bangalore, where he had moved to care for his father during the pandemic. He was remembered as a \"minor legend\" who embodied the spirit of philosophical inquiry and boundary-breaking thought.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bodhisattva Raj Ayyar','','inherit','closed','closed','','54-revision-v1','','','2026-05-19 15:21:48','2026-05-19 15:21:48','',54,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=55',0,'revision','',0),
(56,1,'2026-05-19 15:47:42','2026-05-19 15:47:42','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\"></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Everything wonderful starts on paper. It begins as a faint thought, a half-formed question, a quiet observation about the world. Then, someone picks up a pen, opens a notebook, or steps into a classroom and gives that thought a voice. For nearly half a century, Professor Raj Ayyar did exactly that. He did not merely teach philosophy; he lived it. He did not just share ideas; he invited others to think, feel, and grow alongside him. His story, like the best of human narratives, does not end with a final chapter. It continues in the minds he shaped, the conversations he sparked, and the quiet dignity he brought to every room he entered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born in India, Raj Ayyar’s intellectual journey began at St. Stephen’s College in Delhi, an institution long celebrated for nurturing independent thought and moral courage. There, he discovered that education is not about memorizing answers, but about learning how to ask better questions. This curiosity carried him across the Atlantic to the United States, where he found his true calling in the American classroom. From 1981 to 2000, he served as a professor at East Florida State College, teaching Philosophy, Humanities, and World Religions to a diverse array of students. He approached each lesson not as a transmission of facts, but as an invitation to wonder. Whether discussing ancient texts, ethical dilemmas, or the nature of human belief, he encouraged his students to think critically, speak honestly, and listen deeply.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beyond the lecture hall, Prof. Ayyar shared his voice with the broader public through radio broadcasting. In an era when media was still largely analog, his programs offered listeners thoughtful reflections, literary insights, and musical discoveries. Later, he continued his teaching journey part-time at several colleges in the San Francisco Bay Area, staying engaged with evolving academic conversations while maintaining his signature blend of warmth and intellectual rigor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 2000s, drawn by family ties and a renewed sense of purpose, he returned to India. Between 2008 and 2013, he taught at St. Joseph’s College and Christ University in Bangalore, where he became known for his approachable demeanor and his insistence that learning must serve life, not just career. In 2014, he joined IIIT-Delhi as a Visiting Professor, a role that allowed him to bridge the humanities with emerging technology. He taught courses such as Critical and Creative Thinking, Perspectives on Knowledge, Philosophy of Religion, and Theory and Practice of Engineering Ethics. In an institution focused on innovation, he reminded students that progress without moral reflection is incomplete, and that technology must always serve human dignity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Those who studied under him often described him as a “truant in philosophy.” The phrase was never meant as criticism. Rather, it captured his gentle refusal to be confined by academic orthodoxy. He drew deeply from the works of Henri Bergson, whose ideas about time, intuition, and creative evolution resonated with his own belief in the fluid, unpredictable nature of human experience. He also engaged with A.N. Whitehead’s process philosophy, which views reality not as static objects, but as dynamic relationships. Through these lenses, Prof. Ayyar practiced what a tribute later called a “Bergsonian critique of ignorance”: a lifelong commitment to questioning assumptions, embracing uncertainty, and choosing understanding over dogma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His personal life reflected the same integrity he taught in the classroom. He was remembered as a true egalitarian, someone who “never cared for high and low.” He treated janitors and deans, freshmen and visiting scholars, with the same quiet respect. As a gay man in a world that has not always been welcoming to those who live differently, he knew intimately “what it meant to be kept apart.” Yet he never allowed exclusion to breed bitterness. Instead, he transformed that experience into empathy, using his classroom as a sanctuary where diverse voices were honored, and where every student could feel seen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the global pandemic arrived in 2020, Prof. Ayyar made a deeply personal choice. He moved to Bangalore to care for his aging father, stepping away from formal teaching to fulfill a quiet duty of love. It was a season that reflected his lifelong belief that human connection matters more than professional titles. He continued to read, write, and reflect, maintaining his blog under the banner <em>Ongoing Stories of My Soul</em>. The title was no accident. He understood that a life well-lived leaves behind more than credentials or publications. It leaves behind ways of seeing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Professor Raj Ayyar passed away in early June 2023. The announcement from IIIT-Delhi was simple: “With a heavy heart we bid adieu to Prof. Raj Ayyar today.” But those who knew him understood that farewells are never truly final for those who teach us how to think. His legacy lives in every student who chooses curiosity over cynicism, compassion over indifference, and dialogue over division. It lives in the quiet moments when someone pauses to ask, “What if I’m wrong?” or “How can I understand this better?” It lives in the belief that education is not about filling minds, but about lighting fires.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The phrase that opens his blog—<em>Everything wonderful starts on paper</em>—is more than a tagline. It is a philosophy. Ideas begin as sketches. Conversations start as drafts. Change is born when someone dares to write down a thought, share it, and invite others to build upon it. Prof. Ayyar understood this deeply. He knew that teaching, at its best, is an act of trust: the trust that a single question can ripple outward, that a single conversation can shift a perspective, that a single life lived with integrity can quietly reshape the world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We do not honor such teachers by placing them on pedestals. We honor them by continuing the work they began. By reading widely. By listening carefully. By treating every person with dignity. By refusing to let fear replace wonder. By keeping our souls open to new stories, new questions, and new beginnings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The paper may eventually yellow. The pens may run dry. But the stories they carried? Those endure. And as long as we keep turning the page, his story remains very much alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center; margin:2rem 0;\">\n  If these words resonated, you can <a href=\"/support/\" style=\"color:#00D4AA; font-weight:600;\">support this space with TRON</a>. ✦\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','The Life and Legacy of Professor Raj Ayyar','','publish','open','open','','the-life-and-legacy-of-professor-raj-ayyar','','','2026-05-21 15:56:31','2026-05-21 15:56:31','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=56',0,'post','',0),
