(61,1,'2026-05-20 03:34:04','2026-05-20 03:34:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-19\"><strong>Dr. Vicken Cheterian</strong> (often spelled Cheterian) is a Lebanese-born journalist, political scientist, and author of Armenian descent.<sup></sup> He specializes in international relations, nationalism, ethnic conflicts, and peacebuilding, with a specific focus on the Middle East, North Africa, and the post-Soviet space (particularly the Caucasus and Central Asia).<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Academic &amp; Professional Background</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Teaching:</strong> He serves as a lecturer in history and international relations at the <strong>University of Geneva</strong> (Global Studies Institute) and <strong>Webster University Geneva</strong>. He has also previously lectured at SOAS University of London.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Journalism:</strong> Cheterian worked as a journalist in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War. Over his career, he has written for mainstream international media outlets, including <em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, and <em>Al-Hayat</em>, and he is a regular columnist for <em>Agos</em>, a bilingual Armenian-Turkish weekly newspaper based in Istanbul.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Peacebuilding &amp; Advising:</strong> As a practitioner, he has been involved in peacebuilding and good governance projects. He founded the Caucasus Media Institute in Yerevan and has acted as a policy and media advisor for international bodies, including the United Nations (serving on two UN Commissions of Inquiry), the World Bank, and the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-19\"><strong>Dr. Vicken Cheterian</strong> (often spelled Cheterian) is a Lebanese-born journalist, political scientist, and author of Armenian descent.<sup></sup> He specializes in international relations, nationalism, ethnic conflicts, and peacebuilding, with a specific focus on the Middle East, North Africa, and the post-Soviet space (particularly the Caucasus and Central Asia).<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Academic &amp; Professional Background</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Teaching:</strong> He serves as a lecturer in history and international relations at the <strong>University of Geneva</strong> (Global Studies Institute) and <strong>Webster University Geneva</strong>. He has also previously lectured at SOAS University of London.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Journalism:</strong> Cheterian worked as a journalist in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War. Over his career, he has written for mainstream international media outlets, including <em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, and <em>Al-Hayat</em>, and he is a regular columnist for <em>Agos</em>, a bilingual Armenian-Turkish weekly newspaper based in Istanbul.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Peacebuilding &amp; Advising:</strong> As a practitioner, he has been involved in peacebuilding and good governance projects. He founded the Caucasus Media Institute in Yerevan and has acted as a policy and media advisor for international bodies, including the United Nations (serving on two UN Commissions of Inquiry), the World Bank, and the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-19\"><strong>Dr. Vicken Cheterian</strong> (often spelled Cheterian) is a Lebanese-born journalist, political scientist, and author of Armenian descent.<sup></sup> He specializes in international relations, nationalism, ethnic conflicts, and peacebuilding, with a specific focus on the Middle East, North Africa, and the post-Soviet space (particularly the Caucasus and Central Asia).<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Academic &amp; Professional Background</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Teaching:</strong> He serves as a lecturer in history and international relations at the <strong>University of Geneva</strong> (Global Studies Institute) and <strong>Webster University Geneva</strong>. He has also previously lectured at SOAS University of London.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Journalism:</strong> Cheterian worked as a journalist in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War. Over his career, he has written for mainstream international media outlets, including <em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, and <em>Al-Hayat</em>, and he is a regular columnist for <em>Agos</em>, a bilingual Armenian-Turkish weekly newspaper based in Istanbul.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Peacebuilding &amp; Advising:</strong> As a practitioner, he has been involved in peacebuilding and good governance projects. He founded the Caucasus Media Institute in Yerevan and has acted as a policy and media advisor for international bodies, including the United Nations (serving on two UN Commissions of Inquiry), the World Bank, and the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Thanks to Dr. Vicken Cheterian','','trash','open','open','','thanks-to-dr-vicken-cheterian__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=61',0,'post','',0),
