 -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-19\"><strong>Dr. Vicken Cheterian</strong> (often spelled Cheterian) is a Lebanese-born journalist, political scientist, and author of Armenian descent.<sup></sup> He specializes in international relations, nationalism, ethnic conflicts, and peacebuilding, with a specific focus on the Middle East, North Africa, and the post-Soviet space (particularly the Caucasus and Central Asia).<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Academic &amp; Professional Background</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Teaching:</strong> He serves as a lecturer in history and international relations at the <strong>University of Geneva</strong> (Global Studies Institute) and <strong>Webster University Geneva</strong>. He has also previously lectured at SOAS University of London.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Journalism:</strong> Cheterian worked as a journalist in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War. Over his career, he has written for mainstream international media outlets, including <em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, and <em>Al-Hayat</em>, and he is a regular columnist for <em>Agos</em>, a bilingual Armenian-Turkish weekly newspaper based in Istanbul.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Peacebuilding &amp; Advising:</strong> As a practitioner, he has been involved in peacebuilding and good governance projects. He founded the Caucasus Media Institute in Yerevan and has acted as a policy and media advisor for international bodies, including the United Nations (serving on two UN Commissions of Inquiry), the World Bank, and the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-19\"><strong>Dr. Vicken Cheterian</strong> (often spelled Cheterian) is a Lebanese-born journalist, political scientist, and author of Armenian descent.<sup></sup> He specializes in international relations, nationalism, ethnic conflicts, and peacebuilding, with a specific focus on the Middle East, North Africa, and the post-Soviet space (particularly the Caucasus and Central Asia).<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Academic &amp; Professional Background</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Teaching:</strong> He serves as a lecturer in history and international relations at the <strong>University of Geneva</strong> (Global Studies Institute) and <strong>Webster University Geneva</strong>. He has also previously lectured at SOAS University of London.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Journalism:</strong> Cheterian worked as a journalist in Beirut during the Lebanese Civil War. Over his career, he has written for mainstream international media outlets, including <em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, and <em>Al-Hayat</em>, and he is a regular columnist for <em>Agos</em>, a bilingual Armenian-Turkish weekly newspaper based in Istanbul.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Peacebuilding &amp; Advising:</strong> As a practitioner, he has been involved in peacebuilding and good governance projects. He founded the Caucasus Media Institute in Yerevan and has acted as a policy and media advisor for international bodies, including the United Nations (serving on two UN Commissions of Inquiry), the World Bank, and the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Notable Books</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_1e8142709719f72f-23\">Cheterian has authored several widely cited books and academic papers analyzing geopolitical transitions and historical trauma:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>War and Peace in the Caucasus: Ethnic Conflict and the New Geopolitics</em></strong> (2008) – An in-depth look at post-Soviet friction and border wars in the Caucasus region.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>From Perestroika to Rainbow Revolutions: Reform and Revolution After Socialism</em></strong> (2013) – An exploration of political shifts and civil uprisings across former communist states.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Open Wounds: Armenians, Turks and a Century of Genocide</em></strong> (2015) – An examination of the legacy, memory, and international relations surrounding the Armenian Genocide.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Thanks to Dr. Vicken Cheterian','','inherit','closed','closed','','61-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 03:34:04','2026-05-20 03:34:04','',61,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=62',0,'revision','',0),
(63,1,'2026-05-20 06:13:42','2026-05-20 06:13:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Amber Gold Allegations (2018): Verified Facts</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on verified search results and documentation, here is a fact-checked breakdown of the claims about Polish Prime Minister Donald Tusk and the \"Trump-like collusion\" comparisons:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. The Amber Gold Allegations (2018): Verified Facts</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Scandal</strong>: Amber Gold was a Polish financial pyramid scheme that defrauded approximately <strong>19,000 investors of over 850 million zlotys ($225 million)</strong> [[4]]. The company operated as a pseudo-investment platform promising high returns on gold and amber investments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tusk\'s Connection</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Donald Tusk was <strong>Prime Minister of Poland from 2007–2014</strong>, during which Amber Gold operated (founded 2009, collapsed 2012) [[1]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In <strong>November 2018</strong>, while serving as President of the European Council, Tusk testified before a Polish parliamentary commission investigating the scandal [[2]][[5]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A key line of questioning involved whether <strong>Tusk\'s son, Michał Tusk, was employed by an airline owned by Amber Gold</strong>, raising questions about potential conflicts of interest [[1]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Outcome</strong>: The parliamentary commission was led by Poland\'s then-ruling Law and Justice (PiS) party, Tusk\'s political opponents. No criminal charges were filed against Tusk personally. Critics viewed the investigation as politically motivated; supporters argued it addressed legitimate oversight failures during his premiership.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Rhetoric Shift and \"Trump\" Comparisons: Context Matters</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Incident</strong>: In 2019, Tusk released a campaign video criticizing the PiS government for admitting migrants \"from Islamic countries\" while opposing EU relocation quotas [[11]]. The video was titled <em>\"Polish people must regain control over their country and its borders.\"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Criticism</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Left-wing MEP <strong>Maciej Konieczny tweeted</strong>: <em>\"Is it still Donald Tusk or maybe Donald Trump?\"</em>, calling the speech \"madness\" [[11]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Socialist MEP <strong>Robert Biedroń</strong> labeled the video \"racist\" and argued the opposition \"should not compete in smear campaigns\" against migrants [[11]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Important Nuance</strong>: Tusk\'s rhetoric was directed at <strong>domestic political opponents</strong> (PiS), not as an endorsement of Trump\'s policies. He was criticizing PiS for what he framed as inconsistent migration policy—admitting labor migrants while stoking fear about refugees. This is distinct from Trump\'s blanket anti-immigration platform.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Tusk\'s Actual Relationship with Trump: Strategic Friction, Not Collusion</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Public Criticism</strong>: Tusk has been one of Trump\'s most consistent European critics:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>At a 2018 NATO summit, Tusk stated: <em>\"Looking at the latest decisions of President Trump, someone could even think: With friends like that, who needs enemies?\"</em> [[14]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>He has repeatedly emphasized that <strong>\"coercion is not a good method, especially in relations with our transatlantic partners\"</strong> while affirming the U.S. as Poland\'s most important security partner [[13]].</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>**Current Stance **(2026): As Polish Prime Minister, Tusk has described EU-U.S. relations under Trump as being *\"in crisis\"* but stressed the need to protect the relationship without becoming \"anti-American\" [[13]]. He has drawn a distinction between \"domination and leadership\" in transatlantic affairs [[13]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Why the \"Collusion\" Framing Is Misleading</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Claim</th><th>Reality Check</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>\"Amber Gold = Trump-style business collusion\"</strong></td><td>The Amber Gold investigation focused on regulatory oversight during Tusk\'s premiership, not personal financial gain. No evidence links Tusk to the fraud.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>\"Anti-immigrant rhetoric = Trump alignment\"</strong></td><td>Tusk\'s migration comments targeted domestic opponents\' policy inconsistencies, not a philosophical embrace of nativism. He remains a pro-EU, pro-multilateralism leader.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>\"Collusion with Trump\"</strong></td><td>Public record shows persistent policy disagreement. Tusk has criticized Trump\'s approach to NATO, trade, and democratic norms repeatedly.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Broader Context: Polish Political Polarization</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The \"Trump-like\" comparisons often emerge from Poland\'s intensely polarized media environment:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>PiS-aligned outlets</strong> have used the Amber Gold hearings to undermine Tusk\'s credibility.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Opposition critics</strong> on the left have accused Tusk of adopting right-wing rhetoric to win elections.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>International observers</strong> sometimes conflate tactical political messaging with ideological alignment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bottom Line</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The phrase \"almost Trump-like whiff of collusion\" appears to be a rhetorical flourish rather than a substantiated analytical claim. While Tusk has faced legitimate scrutiny over regulatory oversight during the Amber Gold scandal, and has occasionally used hardline migration rhetoric for domestic political effect, his <strong>policy record, institutional commitments, and public statements place him firmly in the pro-European, transatlanticist camp</strong>—in direct tension with Trump\'s \"America First\" approach.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'d like, I can search for more specific information on:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The current status of Poland\'s migration policy under Tusk\'s government</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Detailed analysis of the Amber Gold parliamentary commission\'s final report</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How other European leaders have navigated rhetoric vs. policy when responding to Trump-era pressures</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','The Amber Gold Allegations','','trash','open','open','','the-amber-gold-allegations__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=63',0,'post','',0),
