 history where society splits into \"those who have and those who haven\'t.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. The Verse: M-1 and stic.man</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following the intro, the hip-hop duo dead prez delivers a verse detailing the realities of living in an over-policed, impoverished community, contrasting it with a vision for revolutionary change and self-reliance:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Tactics and Surveillance:</strong> They rhyme about urban resistance (\"throw a Molotov cocktail at the precinct\"), organized neighborhood community programs (\"under the Ah-Ching banners\"), and intense state surveillance (\"FBI spying on us through the radio antennas and them hidden cameras\").</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Socioeconomic Struggle:</strong> The lyrics criticize the economic loops of capitalism, stating they are \"sick of working for crumbs and filling up the prisons,\" and needing to rely on religion rather than self-determination.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Revolutionary Solution:</strong> They advocate for a socialist restructuring of resources: <em>\"Organize the wealth into a socialist economy / A way of life based on the common needs.\"</em></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. The Chorus</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The melodic chorus outlines the cyclical, systemic trap faced by minority communities under a \"police state\":</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>\"Average Black male / Live a third of his life spent in a jail cell / \'Cause the world is controlled by the white male / And the people don\'t never get justice... And the jobs don\'t never pay enough / So the rent always be late / Can you relate? We living in a police state.\"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Outro</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The song closes out returning to the archival audio of Fred Hampton passionately asserting his political identity: <em>\"I am a revolutionary!\"</em> and criticizing the cutting of social safety nets like welfare, noting that taking away survival resources directly drives people into crime.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Core Themes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Systemic Oppression &amp; Racism:</strong> Criticizing the prison-industrial complex and the targeting of Black men.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Socialism vs. Capitalism:</strong> Expressing a desire to move away from wage labor toward a system based on common societal needs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Revolutionary Legacy:</strong> Aligning their music with the ideology and historical struggles of the Black Panther Party.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','dead prez (featuring Chairman Fred Hampton) \"Police State\"','','inherit','closed','closed','','65-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 06:38:36','2026-05-20 06:38:36','',65,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=66',0,'revision','',0),
(67,1,'2026-05-20 13:34:17','2026-05-20 13:34:17','<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://www.agos.com.tr/en/author/vicken-cheterian-165\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://www.agos.com.tr/en/author/vicken-cheterian-165\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Oh, the discovery process on this one is going to be an absolute goldmine. If you love bureaucratic theater and the spectacular collapse of \"unwritten\" department policies under oath, grab some popcorn.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You hit the nail on the head regarding how the disciplinary game is played. In the standard playbook, when a \"white shirt\" (or anyone, really) retires or resigns while investigations are pending, those 15-day suspensions are functionally left in a state of administrative limbo. The city can’t technically suspend a guy who doesn\'t work there anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, the massive wrench in the gears here is <strong>the \"Do-Not-Hire\" (ineligible for rehiring) list</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Core Conflict: Procedural Error vs. Bureaucratic Hit Job</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Barz’s lawsuit is going to force the city to show its cards on how a disciplinary recommendation magically becomes a \"sustained finding\" on official HR paperwork.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The City\'s Side:</strong> They likely viewed putting him on the list as a procedural lock to ensure he couldn\'t just loop back into a city role after dodging the active discipline by walking out the door.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Barz\'s Side:</strong> Procedurally, if a complaint was never formally sustained while he was active, slapping it onto his record as a justification for a do-not-hire blacklist is textbook defamation and a violation of due process. If the paperwork says \"sustained\" and it wasn\'t, the City has a major documentation problem.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Elephant in the Room: The \"Quota\" System</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is where the depositions will get truly \"lit.\" The \"quota\" or \"activity metrics\" issue isn\'t just a minor administrative disagreement—it\'s tied to massive, multi-million dollar legal headaches for the City of Chicago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other internal whistleblowers have already cost the city heavy payouts by alleging that top brass demanded arbitrary, high-volume traffic stops (the infamous demand for \"blue cards\" or \"crushing the numbers\") without reasonable suspicion. It has embroiled the CPD in civil rights lawsuits over racial profiling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When Barz’s lawyers start deposing Supt. Larry Snelling and HR Director Joy Brown, the questioning isn\'t just going to be about <em>what</em> Barz did. It\'s going to blow wide open the culture of how these traffic stop numbers were pushed from the very top down:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What exactly constitutes \"encouraging productivity\" versus an \"illegal quota\"?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Were commanders acting as rogue agents, or were they just meeting the unspoken expectations passed down to protect the careers of those above them?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">White Shirts on the Hot Seat</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For years, rank-and-file \"blue shirts\" have complained that they get squeezed on both ends: ordered by supervisors to drive up \"activity numbers\" to make the district look good, only to be hung out to dry by the independent police review agencies when those stops face civil rights scrutiny.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watching the upper echelon of the CPD bureaucracy have to define under oath exactly what they meant by \"the numbers\"—while trying to explain away a potentially botched HR blacklisting—is going to be a masterclass in buck-passing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Discovery is going to force a lot of private emails, text messages, and internal memos into the public record. Safe to say, there are likely a lot of nervous people in CPD headquarters right now wondering what exactly is sitting in their sent folders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Dr. Vicken Cheterian','','trash','open','open','','dr-vicken-cheterian__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=67',0,'post','',0),
