g it onto his record as a justification for a do-not-hire blacklist is textbook defamation and a violation of due process. If the paperwork says \"sustained\" and it wasn\'t, the City has a major documentation problem.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Elephant in the Room: The \"Quota\" System</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is where the depositions will get truly \"lit.\" The \"quota\" or \"activity metrics\" issue isn\'t just a minor administrative disagreement—it\'s tied to massive, multi-million dollar legal headaches for the City of Chicago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other internal whistleblowers have already cost the city heavy payouts by alleging that top brass demanded arbitrary, high-volume traffic stops (the infamous demand for \"blue cards\" or \"crushing the numbers\") without reasonable suspicion. It has embroiled the CPD in civil rights lawsuits over racial profiling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When Barz’s lawyers start deposing Supt. Larry Snelling and HR Director Joy Brown, the questioning isn\'t just going to be about <em>what</em> Barz did. It\'s going to blow wide open the culture of how these traffic stop numbers were pushed from the very top down:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What exactly constitutes \"encouraging productivity\" versus an \"illegal quota\"?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Were commanders acting as rogue agents, or were they just meeting the unspoken expectations passed down to protect the careers of those above them?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">White Shirts on the Hot Seat</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For years, rank-and-file \"blue shirts\" have complained that they get squeezed on both ends: ordered by supervisors to drive up \"activity numbers\" to make the district look good, only to be hung out to dry by the independent police review agencies when those stops face civil rights scrutiny.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watching the upper echelon of the CPD bureaucracy have to define under oath exactly what they meant by \"the numbers\"—while trying to explain away a potentially botched HR blacklisting—is going to be a masterclass in buck-passing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Discovery is going to force a lot of private emails, text messages, and internal memos into the public record. Safe to say, there are likely a lot of nervous people in CPD headquarters right now wondering what exactly is sitting in their sent folders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','','','inherit','closed','closed','','67-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 13:33:29','2026-05-20 13:33:29','',67,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=68',0,'revision','',0),
