g it onto his record as a justification for a do-not-hire blacklist is textbook defamation and a violation of due process. If the paperwork says \"sustained\" and it wasn\'t, the City has a major documentation problem.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Elephant in the Room: The \"Quota\" System</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is where the depositions will get truly \"lit.\" The \"quota\" or \"activity metrics\" issue isn\'t just a minor administrative disagreement—it\'s tied to massive, multi-million dollar legal headaches for the City of Chicago.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other internal whistleblowers have already cost the city heavy payouts by alleging that top brass demanded arbitrary, high-volume traffic stops (the infamous demand for \"blue cards\" or \"crushing the numbers\") without reasonable suspicion. It has embroiled the CPD in civil rights lawsuits over racial profiling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When Barz’s lawyers start deposing Supt. Larry Snelling and HR Director Joy Brown, the questioning isn\'t just going to be about <em>what</em> Barz did. It\'s going to blow wide open the culture of how these traffic stop numbers were pushed from the very top down:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What exactly constitutes \"encouraging productivity\" versus an \"illegal quota\"?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Were commanders acting as rogue agents, or were they just meeting the unspoken expectations passed down to protect the careers of those above them?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">White Shirts on the Hot Seat</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For years, rank-and-file \"blue shirts\" have complained that they get squeezed on both ends: ordered by supervisors to drive up \"activity numbers\" to make the district look good, only to be hung out to dry by the independent police review agencies when those stops face civil rights scrutiny.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watching the upper echelon of the CPD bureaucracy have to define under oath exactly what they meant by \"the numbers\"—while trying to explain away a potentially botched HR blacklisting—is going to be a masterclass in buck-passing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Discovery is going to force a lot of private emails, text messages, and internal memos into the public record. Safe to say, there are likely a lot of nervous people in CPD headquarters right now wondering what exactly is sitting in their sent folders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Dr. Vicken Cheterian','','inherit','closed','closed','','67-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 13:34:17','2026-05-20 13:34:17','',67,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=69',0,'revision','',0),
(70,1,'2026-05-20 13:40:34','2026-05-20 13:40:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The text provided is the official community announcement text for the <strong>OpenBSD 7.9 operating system release</strong>, originally published on the community site <em>Undeadly (The OpenBSD Journal)</em> by contributor \"rueda\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is the backstory of OpenBSD as a project, the context of this specific 60th release, and what the key technical features mentioned actually mean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Project Backstory: What is OpenBSD?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OpenBSD is a free, open-source, Unix-like operating system spun out of NetBSD in <strong>1995</strong> by its founder, <strong>Theo de Raadt</strong>, following a famous dispute among the NetBSD core developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based in Canada, the OpenBSD project emphasizes a highly specific philosophy:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Proactive Security:</strong> Instead of waiting for a hack and patching it, developers audit the entire codebase line-by-line to fix vulnerability patterns before they can be exploited.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"Default Secure\":</strong> A standard installation has almost all non-essential services turned off. Their famous homepage slogan boasts having only two remote holes in the default install \"in a heck of a long time.\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Pure Open Source &amp; Code Clarity:</strong> They strictly refuse to include proprietary binary blobs or restrictive licensing. They are famous for completely rewriting software if the existing versions are messy or restrictively licensed (this is how <strong>OpenSSH</strong>, the software securing almost every server on Earth, was born).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"p-rc_76588a07f1929499-43\">Unlike most modern tech projects that slip deadlines, OpenBSD operates like clockwork. They release a new version <strong>exactly every six months</strong> (usually around May and November). OpenBSD 7.9 represents the <strong>60th official release</strong> in the project\'s history.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Key Technical Backstory for the 7.9 Release Notes</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are wondering why some of these specific features matter, here is what is happening under the hood:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Modern Hardware Survival (<code>nhi(4)</code>, <code>MAXCPU</code>, <code>hw.blockcpu</code>)<sup></sup></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As Intel, AMD, and Apple move toward complex modern architectures, OpenBSD has to adapt.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>MAXCPU</code> to 255:</strong> Modern servers frequently have massive core counts. Moving the hard limit on the <code>amd64</code> architecture ensures OpenBSD can scale natively on high-end hardware.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>hw.blockcpu</code> (Selective Core Blocking):</strong> Modern chips mix performance cores (P-cores) and efficiency cores (E-cores), or utilize SMT (hyperthreading). This new sysctl feature allows an administrator to explicitly command the kernel scheduler to avoid scheduling tasks on weaker or hyperthreaded cores—crucial for securing a system against side-channel CPU hardware vulnerabilities like Spectre/Meltdown.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>nhi(4)</code> driver:</strong> USB4 controllers on newer AMD laptops were trapping power. This new controller lets the hardware properly drop down into ultra-low-power idle states (<code>S0ix</code>), preventing your laptop battery from draining in your backpack.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. \"Delayed Hibernation\"</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On standard operating systems, when you close a laptop lid, it goes to Sleep (Suspend-to-RAM). If left too long, the battery dies, and you lose your open work. \"Delayed Hibernation\" tells the laptop: <em>“Sleep normally for a few hours. If I haven’t opened the lid by then, wake up briefly, write everything safely to the hard drive (Hibernate), and shut down completely to save the remaining battery.”</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Virtualization Overhaul (<code>vmboot</code>, Apple Hypervisor)<sup></sup></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OpenBSD has its own native hypervisor called <code>vmd(8)</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Moving the VirtIO SCSI device into a <strong>subprocess</strong> is a classic OpenBSD security tactic—privilege separation. If an attacker manages to exploit the virtual disk system, they are trapped in a sandboxed subprocess rather than gaining control of the main virtualization daemon.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The addition of <strong><code>vmboot</code></strong> assists with AMD SEV (Secure Encrypted Virtualization), making it possible to safely automate upgrades (<code>sysupgrade</code>) on highly secured, encrypted cloud virtual machines.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>It can also natively run smoothly as a guest inside macOS environments using Apple\'s Hypervisor framework.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. The Retirement of <code>tmppath</code></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OpenBSD relies heavily on <strong><code>pledge(2)</code></strong>, a security feature where a program voluntarily tells the kernel, <em>\"I promise I only need to do X and Y.\"</em> If it tries to do Z, the kernel immediately kills it. The <code>tmppath</code> promise used to allow programs restricted access to create files specifically in <code>/tmp</code>. Over time, developers realized they could handle these path permissions more securely through standard file system paths (<code>rpath</code>/<code>wpath</code>), keeping the kernel codebase leaner and cleaner.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">5. Multimedia Quality of Life (Chromium + VA-API / Widevine)</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While OpenBSD is primarily known as a rock-solid server or firewall OS, a dedicated contingent uses it as a daily desktop operating system. Giving the Chromium browser <strong>VA-API</strong> (hardware video acceleration) means streaming video uses the graphics card rather than melting the CPU, while <strong>Widevine</strong> support allows desktop OpenBSD users to watch DRM-protected video content (like Netflix or commercial streaming sites) without jumping through hoops.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What is OpenBSD?','','trash','open','open','','what-is-openbsd__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=70',0,'post','',0),
(71,1,'2026-05-20 13:40:32','2026-05-20 13:40:32','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The text provided is the official community announcement text for the <strong>OpenBSD 7.9 operating system release</strong>, originally published on the community site <em>Undeadly (The OpenBSD Journal)</em> by contributor \"rueda\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is the backstory of OpenBSD as a project, the context of this specific 60th release, and what the key technical features mentioned actually mean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Project Backstory: What is OpenBSD?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>OpenBSD is a free, open-source, Unix-like operating system spun out of NetBSD in <strong>1995</strong> by its founder, <strong>Theo de Raadt</strong>, following a famous dispute among the NetBSD core developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based in Canada, the OpenBSD project emphasizes a highly specific philosophy:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Proactive Security:</strong> Instead of waiting for a hack and patching it, developers audit the entire codebase line-by-line to fix vulnerability patterns before they can be exploited.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"Default Secure\":</strong> A standard installation has almost all non-essential services turned off. Their famous homepage slogan boasts having only two remote holes in the default install \"in a heck of a long time.\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Pure Open Source &amp; Code Clarity:</strong> They strictly refuse to include proprietary binary blobs or restrictive licensing. They are famous for completely rewriting software if the existing versions are messy or restrictively licensed (this is how <strong>OpenSSH</strong>, the softw