a father of eight who had worked as a security guard at the Islamic Center for more than a decade. He knew the children by name. He greeted worshippers at the door. He was, by all accounts, a gentle man who understood that his job was to protect — and he did exactly that.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His family released a statement: \"Our father died a hero. He loved his community and his faith. We are heartbroken, but we are also proud.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A Community\'s Response</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the days following the tragedy, a fundraiser was established to support the families of the three victims. As of this writing, it has raised more than $2.9 million — a testament to the outpouring of love from a city that refuses to be defined by hate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>San Diego\'s mayor stood before reporters and said something that should be remembered: \"These three Muslim men represent the city far more than the suspects ever could.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What Amin Abdullah Knew</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amin Abdullah understood that protecting children is not a political act. It is not a religious statement. It is simply human decency. He didn\'t ask to be a hero. He just did his job — and in doing so, he gave 140 children the chance to go home to their families.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He leaves behind eight children who will grow up without their father. He leaves behind a community that will never forget his name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And he leaves behind a question for all of us: When hate knocks on the door, will we be the ones who stand in the way?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>How You Can Honor His Memory</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The families of the victims still need support. The fundraiser remains active, and every donation helps. But beyond money, we can honor Amin Abdullah by refusing to let hate win — by standing up for our neighbors, by protecting the vulnerable, and by never looking away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Rest in power, Amin Abdullah. You did your job. You did it well. And you will not be forgotten.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>See less</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Condolences for Amin Abdullah','','inherit','closed','closed','','76-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 15:26:47','2026-05-20 15:26:47','',76,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=77',0,'revision','',0),
(78,1,'2026-05-20 15:27:58','2026-05-20 15:27:58','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/702364377_122132067513041489_6706544659125828802_n.jpg?_nc_cat=1&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=127cfc&amp;_nc_ohc=9V-RrMXbCV0Q7kNvwFTw-HH&amp;_nc_oc=AdoFl8ptW0aLbNdnyo4Fi7Uj1EtdZjurmNxIhtlBCyx9CU-5evzSQPKd0lsGBEZn6DY&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia3-1.xx&amp;_nc_gid=0Soj0k1emwsPY2FOGFQotg&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af5QgvnbYpakbr_jr7TeC0MarutN5BXbtHr8vKpUMXmyCg&amp;oe=6A1391D7\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He Died Protecting 140 Children: The Hero of San Diego</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amin Abdullah showed up to work on Monday to do what he had done for more than a decade: keep the worshippers at the Islamic Center of San Diego safe. He was a father of eight, a security guard, and a man who took his job seriously. By the time the sun set, he had given his life — but not before saving 140 children.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the story of a hero you need to know.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Attack</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On a weekday morning, the Islamic Center of San Diego was full of activity. A school was in session inside the mosque, with 140 children learning, playing, and laughing. Adults were scattered throughout the building for prayer and community business.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then the suspects arrived.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Two teenagers, armed with firearms and driven by a hateful ideology that police later described as targeting anyone who wasn\'t like them, opened fire. The shooting was swift, brutal, and entirely unprovoked.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amin Abdullah, the security guard stationed at the entrance, was the first line of defense. He didn\'t run. He didn\'t hide. He engaged the attackers — buying precious seconds for the 140 children to be moved to safety.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was shot and killed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But his actions forced the suspects to flee the building before they could reach the school wing. Police Chief Scott Wahl later called his response \"heroic\" and said it \"undoubtedly pushed the suspects to flee.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Other Victims</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Two other worshippers were also killed that day. They were in the parking lot when the shooting began, and they drew the attackers\' attention away from the building — another act of sacrifice that likely saved lives.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The two teenage attackers fled the scene and were later found dead of self-inflicted wounds nearby. Investigators seized more than 30 firearms from residences connected to the suspects, along with a manifesto outlining their hate-filled beliefs. The FBI is investigating the shooting as a hate crime, with one agent noting that the suspects \"did not discriminate on who they hated.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Man Behind the Uniform</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amin Abdullah was not a professional soldier or a SWAT officer. He was a father of eight who had worked as a security guard at the Islamic Center for more than a decade. He knew the children by name. He greeted worshippers at the door. He was, by all accounts, a gentle man who understood that his job was to protect — and he did exactly that.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His family released a statement: \"Our father died a hero. He loved his community and his faith. We are heartbroken, but we are also proud.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A Community\'s Response</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the days following the tragedy, a fundraiser was established to support the families of the three victims. As of this writing, it has raised more than $2.9 million — a testament to the outpouring of love from a city that refuses to be defined by hate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>San Diego\'s mayor stood before reporters and said something that should be remembered: \"These three Muslim men represent the city far more than the suspects ever could.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What Amin Abdullah Knew</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amin Abdullah understood that protecting children is not a political act. It is not a religious statement. It is simply human decency. He didn\'t ask to be a hero. He just did his job — and in doing so, he gave 140 children the chance to go home to their families.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He leaves behind eight children who will grow up without their father. He leaves behind a community that will never forget his name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And he leaves behind a question for all of us: When hate knocks on the door, will we be the ones who stand in the way?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>How You Can Honor His Memory</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The families of the victims still need support. The fundraiser remains active, and every donation helps. But beyond money, we can honor Amin Abdullah by refusing to let hate win — by standing up for our neighbors, by protecting the vulnerable, and by never looking away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Rest in power, Amin Abdullah. You did your job. You did it well. And you will not be forgotten.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Condolences for Amin Abdullah','','inherit','closed','closed','','76-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 15:27:58','2026-05-20 15:27:58','',76,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=78',0,'revision','',0),
(79,1,'2026-05-20 15:47:07','2026-05-20 15:47:07','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia3-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/702306729_122132109069041489_6440268446651750229_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s640x640_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=107&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=833d8c&amp;_nc_ohc=YhZ1H-FS25UQ7kNvwEnLXPl&amp;_nc_oc=Adq06Y2g6QyTN666WCq0qiVU8EOROJ6wUhCXk3glHJW8JzCWDWW1R0DjUKCCjKCF03E&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia3-2.xx&amp;_nc_gid=FIoY-soNo-mN6tR8ZKcaLA&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af7CEL5SrrVa9WFHjbLmqEZmnuDSVfZPHW9AveOW3vffGw&amp;oe=6A13ABE3\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was a swampy mosquito pit where the Marine Corps sent Black men it never intended to accept. The white drill instructors called them names they couldn\'t print in newspapers. Fellow service members told Edgar Huff he was too weak for the uniform, too Black for the title, and that no one would miss him when he was gone.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He answered them with three words: \"Hell no.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before long, the men who tried to break him were saluting him. Edgar R. Huff became the first African‑American sergeant major in U.S. Marine Corps history—and the man who built the very training camp that was supposed to keep Black Marines invisible.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the story of a bulldog who refused to let go of his bowl.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Steelworker Who Saw an Opening</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edgar R. Huff was born on December 2, 1919, in Gadsden, Alabama, a gritty industrial town where the blast furnaces of Republic Steel lit up the night sky. By 1942, Huff was a crane rigger in the shipping department, a job that built the kind of physical toughness that would serve him well in the Marine Corps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the morning of June 25, 1942, Huff scanned the local paper and saw an announcement that would change his life: the Marine Corps was finally going to accept Black men. For 167 years, the service had kept its ranks exclusively white. Now, under pressure from President Franklin D. Roosevelt, the Corps reluctantly opened its doors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next morning, Huff walked into the recruiting sergeant\'s office in Gadsden and told him he wanted to join. The recruiter looked him over and said, \"You\'re exactly the kind of man we\'re looking for\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huff signed up, but he wasn\'t sent to Parris Island like white recruits. Instead, he was shipped to a freshly cleared patch of swamp adjacent to Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, called Montford Point. The camp had no barracks, no paved roads, and no real training program. Huff and the other Black recruits spent their first weeks building the camp themselves—hammering nails, digging latrines, stringing electrical wire.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"I Said, \'Hell No\'\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The white drill instructors who ran Montford Point weren\'t volunteers. Most had been given a choice: train Black Marines or face court‑martial. Many took their resentment out on the recruits. \"They said, \'Leave,\'\" Huff later recalled. \"I said, \'Hell no.\' I was going to hold on like a bulldog to a bowl\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huff completed basic training and was assigned to a 155mm gun battery of the 51st Composite Defense Battalion, serving as a gun commander. When the battalion was ordered overseas, Huff was pulled aside and offered an unexpected assignment: drill instructor school. He graduated in March 1943 and became one of the first Black drill instructors in Marine Corps history, shoulder‑to‑shoulder with his brother‑in‑law, Gilbert \"Hashmark\" Johnson.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By November 1944, Huff had been promoted to first sergeant and placed in charge of all recruit training at Montford Point as field sergeant major. The men who had tried to push him out now answered to him.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Three Wars, One Backbone</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huff\'s World War II service took him to the blood-soaked islands of Saipan and Okinawa, and then to North China, where his depot company provided logistics support for Marine divisions fighting in the Pacific. He left the Marines briefly after the war, but civilian life couldn\'t hold him. He reenlisted and was soon headed to Korea with the legendary 1st Marine Division.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a company gunnery sergeant with the 2nd Battalion, 1st Marines, Huff saw heavy combat in the \"Punch Bowl\" area and participated in the spring‑summer offensive on the West Central front. He was wounded—three times—but each time he refused evacuation until his men were safe. His chest carries three Purple Hearts and two Bronze Stars with Combat \"V\" as proof of those decisions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vietnam came next. Huff served two tours as sergeant major of the III Marine Amphibious Force, one of the most dangerous assignments in the war, from May 1967 to June 1968 and again from October 1970 to October 1971. In his late forties and early fifties, he was older than most Marines in combat. He went anyway.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The First Black Sergeant Major</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On December 30, 1955, Huff was promoted to first sergeant in the new rank structure. The very next day—December 31, 1955—he was promoted to sergeant major, becoming the first African‑American to hold that rank in the history of the United States Marine Corps. From that day forward, Huff served as sergeant major consecutively at posts stretching from French Morocco to Camp Pendleton, from Okinawa to the 2nd Marine Aircraft Wing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In his later years, Huff walked with a cane that he had decorated with 20 copper rings, each one engraved with the name of a battle or operation he had taken part in. The cane clinked like a string of dog tags—Saipan, Okinawa, the Punch Bowl, Vietnam—a reminder that the old man with the slow gait had once carried a nation\'s weight on his back.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Legacy That Still Marches</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huff retired on September 30, 1972, after 30 years of service. He died on May 2, 1994—exactly 52 years to the day after he had first dreamed of becoming a Marine—at the Camp Lejeune Naval Hospital in North Carolina. He was 74 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His body was laid to rest in Coastal Carolina State Veterans Cemetery in Jacksonville, North Carolina. The Montford Point Marine Association, an organization he helped found, continues to honor his memory with an annual scholarship in his name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2011, the Montford Point Marines received the Congressional Gold Medal, the nation\'s highest civilian award, for their service during World War II. Huff was among those honored.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What Sergeant Major Huff Knew</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edgar Huff didn\'t join the Marine Corps to become a symbol. He joined because he had heard that the Marines were \"the toughest outfit going,\" and he considered himself \"the toughest going\". He wanted to belong to the best organization, not the most comfortable one.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a 1972 oral history interview, Huff was asked if he had any advice for young Black Marines coming up behind him. He paused, then said: \"The Marine Corps has been good to me, and I feel I have been good to the Marine Corps\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That quiet pride—not bitter, not boastful, just matter‑of‑fact—summed up his 30 years of service. He had built the barracks that were supposed to segregate him. He had trained the recruits who were supposed to never exist. He had bled on three continents for a country that sometimes didn\'t want his blood. And when it was all over, he didn\'t ask for a statue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He just asked that his men remember: when someone tells you to leave, hold on like a bulldog to a bowl</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Rest in peace Brother','','trash','open','open','','rest-in-peace-brother__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=79',0,'post','',0),
(80,1,'2026-05-20 15:47:07','2026-05-20 15:47:07','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia3-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/702306729_122132109069041489_6440268446651750229_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s640x640_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=107&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=833d8c&amp;_nc_ohc=YhZ1H-FS25UQ7kNvwEnLXPl&amp;_nc_oc=Adq06Y2g6QyTN666WCq0qiVU8EOROJ6wUhCXk3glHJW8JzCWDWW1R0DjUKCCjKCF03E&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia3-2.xx&amp;_nc_gid=FIoY-soNo-mN6tR8ZKcaLA&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af7CEL5SrrVa9WFHjbLmqEZmnuDSVfZPHW9AveOW3vffGw&amp;oe=6A13ABE3\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was a swampy mosquito pit where the Marine Corps sent Black men it never intended to accept. The white drill instructors called them names they couldn\'t print in newspapers. Fellow service members told Edgar Huff he was too weak for the uniform, too Black for the title, and that no one would miss him when he was gone.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He answered them with three words: \"Hell no.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before long, the men who tried to break him were saluting him. Edgar R. Huff became the first African‑American sergeant major in U.S. Marine Corps history—and the man who built the very training camp that was supposed to keep Black Marines invisible.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the story of a bulldog who refused to let go of his bowl.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Steelworker Who Saw an Opening</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edgar R. Huff was born on December 2, 1919, in Gadsden, Alabama, a gritty industrial town where the blast furnaces of Republic Steel lit up the night sky. By 1942, Huff was a crane rigger in the shipping department, a job that built the kind of ph