eant Major</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On December 30, 1955, Huff was promoted to first sergeant in the new rank structure. The very next day—December 31, 1955—he was promoted to sergeant major, becoming the first African‑American to hold that rank in the history of the United States Marine Corps. From that day forward, Huff served as sergeant major consecutively at posts stretching from French Morocco to Camp Pendleton, from Okinawa to the 2nd Marine Aircraft Wing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In his later years, Huff walked with a cane that he had decorated with 20 copper rings, each one engraved with the name of a battle or operation he had taken part in. The cane clinked like a string of dog tags—Saipan, Okinawa, the Punch Bowl, Vietnam—a reminder that the old man with the slow gait had once carried a nation\'s weight on his back.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Legacy That Still Marches</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huff retired on September 30, 1972, after 30 years of service. He died on May 2, 1994—exactly 52 years to the day after he had first dreamed of becoming a Marine—at the Camp Lejeune Naval Hospital in North Carolina. He was 74 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His body was laid to rest in Coastal Carolina State Veterans Cemetery in Jacksonville, North Carolina. The Montford Point Marine Association, an organization he helped found, continues to honor his memory with an annual scholarship in his name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2011, the Montford Point Marines received the Congressional Gold Medal, the nation\'s highest civilian award, for their service during World War II. Huff was among those honored.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>---</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What Sergeant Major Huff Knew</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edgar Huff didn\'t join the Marine Corps to become a symbol. He joined because he had heard that the Marines were \"the toughest outfit going,\" and he considered himself \"the toughest going\". He wanted to belong to the best organization, not the most comfortable one.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In a 1972 oral history interview, Huff was asked if he had any advice for young Black Marines coming up behind him. He paused, then said: \"The Marine Corps has been good to me, and I feel I have been good to the Marine Corps\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That quiet pride—not bitter, not boastful, just matter‑of‑fact—summed up his 30 years of service. He had built the barracks that were supposed to segregate him. He had trained the recruits who were supposed to never exist. He had bled on three continents for a country that sometimes didn\'t want his blood. And when it was all over, he didn\'t ask for a statue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He just asked that his men remember: when someone tells you to leave, hold on like a bulldog to a bowl</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Rest in peace Brother','','inherit','closed','closed','','79-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 15:47:07','2026-05-20 15:47:07','',79,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=80',0,'revision','',0),
(81,1,'2026-05-20 17:27:06','2026-05-20 17:27:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here\'s what data is available about military voting records:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">National Military Voting Data (UOCAVA)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Federal Sources:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The <strong>Federal Voting Assistance Program (FVAP)</strong> is the primary source for military voting data, compiling statistics from administrative records and post-election surveys of active duty personnel www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>About <strong>three-quarters of the 1.4 million active duty military members</strong> are eligible to vote absentee under UOCAVA protections because they\'re stationed away from their voting residence www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the <strong>2008 presidential election</strong>, states transmitted nearly <strong>1 million UOCAVA ballots</strong>, with 48.6% going to uniformed services members and 37.9% to civilian citizens living overseas www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Of those transmitted, <strong>69% (682,341)</strong> were returned and submitted for counting www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>93.6%</strong> of submitted UOCAVA ballots were ultimately counted; the most common reason for rejection was missing deadlines (43.7% of rejected ballots) www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Florida/Hillsborough County Specific Data</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Hillsborough County</strong> has a dedicated webpage for military and overseas voters with information on the Federal Post Card Application (FPCA) and absentee voting procedures www.votehillsborough.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the <strong>2008 general election</strong>, Hillsborough County had <strong>701,464 registered voters</strong> with <strong>515,983 ballots cast</strong> (73.56% turnout) results.enr.clarityelections.com. However, the county\'s public results pages do <strong>not break out military/UOCAVA ballots separately</strong> from general absentee voting totals.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Florida as a whole</strong> transmitted <strong>88,187 UOCAVA ballots</strong> in 2008, with <strong>70%+ going to uniformed services members</strong>—a higher military proportion than most states www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Important Limitations</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":1} -->\n<ol start=\"1\" class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>No partisan breakdown</strong>: Federal law and most state systems do not track or publish <em>how</em> military voters voted (Republican/Democrat), only <em>whether</em> they voted. This is intentional to protect ballot secrecy.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>County-level granularity is limited</strong>: While the EAC collects county-level UOCAVA data, most public-facing portals (including Hillsborough\'s) aggregate military ballots into general \"absentee\" categories.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Turnout gap</strong>: FVAP research indicates military voter participation rates tend to be <strong>lower than comparable civilian populations</strong>, with gaps attributed to logistical obstacles (ballot transmission timing) and a \"residual gap\" of motivation/interest factors www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FWAB usage</strong>: Federal Write-in Absentee Ballots (emergency backup ballots) accounted for only ~4% of UOCAVA ballots submitted in 2008, but faced a <strong>22% rejection rate</strong>—much higher than regular absentee ballots www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">If You\'re Researching a Specific Claim</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re investigating whether military voting patterns affected a particular race in Hillsborough County (e.g., the 2008 presidential election), the available data shows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Obama won Hillsborough County with ~53.5% of the vote</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military ballots were a small subset of the ~36,000 total absentee ballots cast</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>No public dataset breaks down those absentee ballots by military status <em>and</em> candidate preference</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For deeper analysis, you would likely need to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>File a public records request with the Hillsborough County Supervisor of Elections for anonymized UOCAVA ballot metadata</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Consult FVAP\'s restricted research datasets (available to qualified researchers)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Review academic studies like those cited by FVAP on military voting behavior</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Would you like me to help you locate contact information for filing a records request, or search for academic studies on military voting patterns in Florida?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>+72</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Copy</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ask Qwen</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Explain</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Translate(en-US)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Can we determine ratios per service and numners</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thinking completed</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here is what data exists regarding military voting ratios and numbers <strong>by service branch</strong>, along with important limitations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Available Service-Branch Data (National Level)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>From FVAP\'s 2020 Report to Congress</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>www.fvap.gov:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Army</th><th>Navy</th><th>Air Force</th><th>Marine Corps</th><th>Coast Guard*</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Voter Participation Rate</strong></td><td>46%</td><td>51%</td><td>49%</td><td>45%</td><td>Not separately reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Sought FVAP Assistance</strong></td><td>62%</td><td>69%</td><td>59%</td><td>49%</td><td>Not reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ballot Return Rate</strong> (among those who needed assistance AND sought DoD help)</td><td>~38%</td><td>42%</td><td>21%</td><td>~38%</td><td>Not reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>FPCA Distribution Rate</strong></td><td>Exceeded requirement</td><td>Below requirement</td><td>Exceeded requirement</td><td>Below requirement</td><td>Not reported</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>*Coast Guard data is often aggregated with other services or reported separately in smaller datasets due to its smaller size (~40,000 active duty vs. 300K–1.3M for other branches).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Additional Context:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>About <strong>1.05 million of the 1.4 million active duty members</strong> are UOCAVA-eligible (stationed away from voting residence) www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In 2020, the military collectively distributed <strong>~3 million FPCAs</strong> and provided <strong>~4 million assistance sessions</strong> across all services www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>79% of uniformed service members voting away from home mailed their ballots back</strong> in the 2018 general election counteveryhero.org.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Critical Limitations</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":1} -->\n<ol start=\"1\" class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>No partisan preference data</strong>: Federal law prohibits tracking <em>how</em> military personnel voted by candidate or party. All publicly available data measures <em>participation</em> (did they vote?), not <em>preference</em> (who did they vote for?).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>No Hillsborough County service-branch breakdown</strong>: While Hillsborough County tracks military/overseas voters as a category www.votehillsborough.gov, it does not publish absentee ballot data broken down by Army/Navy/Air Force/etc. This granularity is not collected at the county level in Florida\'s public reporting.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Survey-based estimates</strong>: Participation rates by branch come from FVAP\'s Post-Election Voting Survey of Active Duty Military (PEVS-ADM), which is a sample survey—not a full census of ballots cast. Margins of error apply.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"Assistance sought\" ≠ \"voted\"</strong>: The table above shows rates of seeking help from DoD resources. Only a subset of those who sought help ultimately returned a ballot (see \"Ballot Return Rate\" row).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Coast Guard data scarcity</strong>: Due to its smaller size and different administrative structure, Coast Guard-specific voting metrics are rarely disaggregated in public reports.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">If You Need Hillsborough-Specific Numbers</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get service-branch data for Hillsborough County voters, you would likely need to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":1} -->\n<ol start=\"1\" class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>File a Florida public records request</strong> with the Hillsborough County Supervisor of Elections asking for anonymized UOCAVA voter registration records that include military branch affiliation (if collected) www.votehillsborough.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Contact FVAP\'s research division</strong> to inquire about restricted-access datasets that may allow county-level cross-tabulation by service branch (typically available only to accredited researchers).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Review DoD\'s annual Voting Assistance Program reports</strong>, which sometimes include state-level summaries but rarely county-level service breakdowns www.dodig.mil.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bottom Line</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>We can determine</strong>: National participation rates, assistance utilization, and ballot return metrics by service branch via FVAP surveys.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❌ <strong>We cannot determine</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How Hillsborough County military voters by branch voted (partisan preference)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Exact counts of ballots cast per branch in Hillsborough</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Whether service-branch composition affected any specific race outcome in the county</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re testing a hypothesis about military voting influence in a particular Hillsborough election, I can help you:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate the total absentee/UOCAVA ballot counts for that election</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find academic studies on military voting behavior in Florida</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Draft a public records request template</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What specific ratio or number are you trying to calculate? That would help me narrow the search further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','National Military Voting Data','','trash','open','open','','national-military-voting-data__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=81',0,'post','',0),
