item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FWAB usage</strong>: Federal Write-in Absentee Ballots (emergency backup ballots) accounted for only ~4% of UOCAVA ballots submitted in 2008, but faced a <strong>22% rejection rate</strong>—much higher than regular absentee ballots www.eac.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">If You\'re Researching a Specific Claim</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re investigating whether military voting patterns affected a particular race in Hillsborough County (e.g., the 2008 presidential election), the available data shows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Obama won Hillsborough County with ~53.5% of the vote</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military ballots were a small subset of the ~36,000 total absentee ballots cast</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>No public dataset breaks down those absentee ballots by military status <em>and</em> candidate preference</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For deeper analysis, you would likely need to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>File a public records request with the Hillsborough County Supervisor of Elections for anonymized UOCAVA ballot metadata</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Consult FVAP\'s restricted research datasets (available to qualified researchers)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Review academic studies like those cited by FVAP on military voting behavior</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Would you like me to help you locate contact information for filing a records request, or search for academic studies on military voting patterns in Florida?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>+72</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Copy</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ask Qwen</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Explain</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Translate(en-US)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Can we determine ratios per service and numners</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thinking completed</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here is what data exists regarding military voting ratios and numbers <strong>by service branch</strong>, along with important limitations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Available Service-Branch Data (National Level)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>From FVAP\'s 2020 Report to Congress</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>www.fvap.gov:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Army</th><th>Navy</th><th>Air Force</th><th>Marine Corps</th><th>Coast Guard*</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Voter Participation Rate</strong></td><td>46%</td><td>51%</td><td>49%</td><td>45%</td><td>Not separately reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Sought FVAP Assistance</strong></td><td>62%</td><td>69%</td><td>59%</td><td>49%</td><td>Not reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ballot Return Rate</strong> (among those who needed assistance AND sought DoD help)</td><td>~38%</td><td>42%</td><td>21%</td><td>~38%</td><td>Not reported</td></tr><tr><td><strong>FPCA Distribution Rate</strong></td><td>Exceeded requirement</td><td>Below requirement</td><td>Exceeded requirement</td><td>Below requirement</td><td>Not reported</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>*Coast Guard data is often aggregated with other services or reported separately in smaller datasets due to its smaller size (~40,000 active duty vs. 300K–1.3M for other branches).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Additional Context:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>About <strong>1.05 million of the 1.4 million active duty members</strong> are UOCAVA-eligible (stationed away from voting residence) www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In 2020, the military collectively distributed <strong>~3 million FPCAs</strong> and provided <strong>~4 million assistance sessions</strong> across all services www.fvap.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>79% of uniformed service members voting away from home mailed their ballots back</strong> in the 2018 general election counteveryhero.org.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Critical Limitations</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":1} -->\n<ol start=\"1\" class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>No partisan preference data</strong>: Federal law prohibits tracking <em>how</em> military personnel voted by candidate or party. All publicly available data measures <em>participation</em> (did they vote?), not <em>preference</em> (who did they vote for?).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>No Hillsborough County service-branch breakdown</strong>: While Hillsborough County tracks military/overseas voters as a category www.votehillsborough.gov, it does not publish absentee ballot data broken down by Army/Navy/Air Force/etc. This granularity is not collected at the county level in Florida\'s public reporting.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Survey-based estimates</strong>: Participation rates by branch come from FVAP\'s Post-Election Voting Survey of Active Duty Military (PEVS-ADM), which is a sample survey—not a full census of ballots cast. Margins of error apply.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"Assistance sought\" ≠ \"voted\"</strong>: The table above shows rates of seeking help from DoD resources. Only a subset of those who sought help ultimately returned a ballot (see \"Ballot Return Rate\" row).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Coast Guard data scarcity</strong>: Due to its smaller size and different administrative structure, Coast Guard-specific voting metrics are rarely disaggregated in public reports.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">If You Need Hillsborough-Specific Numbers</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get service-branch data for Hillsborough County voters, you would likely need to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":1} -->\n<ol start=\"1\" class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>File a Florida public records request</strong> with the Hillsborough County Supervisor of Elections asking for anonymized UOCAVA voter registration records that include military branch affiliation (if collected) www.votehillsborough.gov.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Contact FVAP\'s research division</strong> to inquire about restricted-access datasets that may allow county-level cross-tabulation by service branch (typically available only to accredited researchers).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Review DoD\'s annual Voting Assistance Program reports</strong>, which sometimes include state-level summaries but rarely county-level service breakdowns www.dodig.mil.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bottom Line</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>We can determine</strong>: National participation rates, assistance utilization, and ballot return metrics by service branch via FVAP surveys.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❌ <strong>We cannot determine</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>How Hillsborough County military voters by branch voted (partisan preference)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Exact counts of ballots cast per branch in Hillsborough</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Whether service-branch composition affected any specific race outcome in the county</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re testing a hypothesis about military voting influence in a particular Hillsborough election, I can help you:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate the total absentee/UOCAVA ballot counts for that election</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find academic studies on military voting behavior in Florida</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Draft a public records request template</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What specific ratio or number are you trying to calculate? That would help me narrow the search further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','National Military Voting Data','','inherit','closed','closed','','81-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 17:27:06','2026-05-20 17:27:06','',81,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=82',0,'revision','',0),
(83,1,'2026-05-20 18:01:02','2026-05-20 18:01:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, I need to clarify an important distinction: <strong>the voting-specific statutes we discussed (18 U.S.C. §§ 594, 597, 610) are rarely, if ever, used to prosecute traditional \"organized street crime\"</strong> (e.g., gangs, drug trafficking organizations, racketeering enterprises). Here\'s what the data shows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔍 Why These Statutes Don\'t Typically Apply to Street Crime</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Statute</th><th>Primary Scope</th><th>Why It Rarely Targets Street Organizations</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>§ 594 (Voter Intimidation)</strong></td><td>Interference with federal election voting rights</td><td>Requires proof of <em>intent to influence how someone votes for a federal candidate</em>—not general coercion or violence</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 597 (Vote Buying)</strong></td><td>Expenditures to influence vote choice</td><td>Targets quid-pro-quo vote transactions, not broader criminal enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 610 (Political Coercion)</strong></td><td>Coercion of <em>federal employees</em> (including military) regarding political activity</td><td>Narrowly focused on government employment relationships</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These statutes are <strong>election-specific</strong>, not general anti-coercion laws. Prosecutors pursuing organized crime groups typically use broader tools like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>RICO Act</strong> (18 U.S.C. §§ 1961–1968) for pattern-of-racketeering cases [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Conspiracy statutes</strong> (18 U.S.C. § 371)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Mail/Wire Fraud</strong> (18 U.S.C. §§ 1341, 1343)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Civil rights violations</strong> (18 U.S.C. § 242) for deprivation of rights under color of law</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">📋 Closest Examples: Voter Intimidation by Organized Groups</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>New Black Panther Party Case (2008)</strong> – <em>Civil, Not Criminal</em></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Two members stood outside a Philadelphia polling place in paramilitary attire; one carried a billy club [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>DOJ filed a <em>civil suit</em> under the <strong>Voting Rights Act</strong>, not a criminal prosecution under § 594</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Charges were later narrowed amid controversy over enforcement priorities [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key takeaway</strong>: Even in a high-profile case involving an organized group, prosecutors opted for civil remedies over criminal Title 18 charges</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>Puerto Rico \"Drugs-for-Votes\" Investigation (Reported 2024)</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Federal prosecutors investigated allegations that a prison gang provided drugs to inmates in exchange for voting support [[55]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>This would more likely be prosecuted under <strong>conspiracy</strong>, <strong>bribery</strong>, or <strong>RICO</strong> statutes rather than § 597, because:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The scheme involved ongoing criminal enterprise activity</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Evidence of vote-buying was embedded in broader racketeering conduct</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>RICO carries stronger penalties and broader evidentiary rules</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>Historical Context: \"Ballot Security\" Groups</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Some prosecutions have targeted organized groups deploying armed individuals near polling places</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>These cases typically invoke <strong>§ 594</strong> but are exceptionally rare and usually involve small, ad-hoc groups—not established street crime organizations [[41]][[44]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">📊 DOJ Prosecution Data: What\'s Actually Charged</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to the DOJ\'s <em>Federal Prosecution of Election Offenses</em> manual and FBI guidance:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Federal election crimes fall into three categories: <strong>campaign finance violations</strong>, <strong>voter/ballot fraud</strong>, and <strong>civil rights violations</strong> [[51]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Voter intimidation prosecutions under § 594 are exceedingly rare</strong>: The manual notes that \"prosecutions for voter intimidation are uncommon\" and typically require clear evidence of targeted coercion linked to a federal candidate [[62]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When organized crime intersects with elections, prosecutors prefer <strong>RICO</strong> or <strong>conspiracy charges</strong> because they:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Allow introduction of broader pattern-of-conduct evidence</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Carry higher penalties</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Avoid the narrow intent requirements of election-specific statutes</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">✅ Bottom Line</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Answer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Are there criminal cases prosecuting street gangs under 18 U.S.C. § 594, 597, or 610?</strong></td><td>No publicly reported cases directly applying these statutes to traditional organized street crime enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Can organized crime groups be prosecuted for election interference?</strong></td><td>Yes—but typically under RICO, conspiracy, fraud, or civil rights statutes, not the narrow voting statutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Why the gap?</strong></td><td>The voting statutes require proof of <em>election-specific intent</em> (influencing a federal vote), whereas street crime prosecutions focus on broader criminal patterns</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔎 If You\'re Researching a Specific Hypothesis</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re investigating whether military voting data or election interference by organized groups affected a Hillsborough County race, I can help you:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for Florida-specific election fraud prosecutions involving organized groups</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate academic studies on military voting behavior and potential coercion risks</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Draft a public records request for Hillsborough County absentee ballot metadata (anonymized)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What specific angle are you exploring? That would help me narrow the search further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Don\'t Typically Apply to Street Crime','','trash','open','open','','dont-typically-apply-to-street-crime__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=83',0,'post','',0),
(84,1,'2026-05-20 18:01:02','2026-05-20 18:01:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, I need to clarify an important distinction: <strong>the voting-specific statutes we discussed (18 U.S.C. §§ 594, 597, 610) are rarely, if ever, used to prosecute traditional \"organized street crime\"</strong> (e.g., gangs, drug trafficking organizations, racketeering enterprises). Here\'s what the data shows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔍 Why These Statutes Don\'t Typically Apply to Street Crime</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Statute</th><th>Primary Scope</th><th>Why It Rarely Targets Street Organizations</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>§ 594 (Voter Intimidation)</strong></td><td>Interference with federal election voting rights</td><td>Requires proof of <em>intent to influence how someone votes for a federal candidate</em>—not general coercion or violence</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 597 (Vote Buying)</strong></td><td>Expenditures to influence vote choice</td><td>Targets quid-pro-quo vote transactions, not broader criminal enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 610 (Political Coercion)</strong></td><td>Coercion of <em>federal employees</em> (including military) regarding political activity</td><td>Narrowly focused on government employment relationships</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These statutes are <strong>election-specific</strong>, not general anti-coercion laws. Prosecutors pursuing organized crime groups typically use broader tools like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>RICO Act</strong> (18 U.S.C. §§ 1961–1968) for pattern-of-racketeering cases [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Conspiracy statutes</strong> (18 U.S.C. § 371)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Mail/Wire Fraud</strong> (18 U.S.C. §§ 1341, 1343)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Civil rights violations</strong> (18 U.S.C. § 242) for deprivation of rights under color of law</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">📋 Closest Examples: Voter Intimidation by Organized Groups</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>New Black Panther Party Case (2008)</strong> – <em>Civil, Not Criminal</em></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Two members stood outside a Philadelphia polling place in paramilitary attire; one carried a billy club [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>DOJ filed a <em>civil suit</em> under the <strong>Voting Rights Act</strong>, not a criminal prosecution under § 594</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Charges were later narrowed amid controversy over enforcement priorities [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key takeaway</strong>: Even in a high-profile case involving an organized group, prosecutors opted for civil remedies over criminal Title 18 charges</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>Puerto Rico \"Drugs-for-Votes\" Investigation (Reported 2024)</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Federal prosecutors investigated allegations that a prison gang provided drugs to inmates in exchange for voting support [[55]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>This would more likely be prosecuted under <strong>conspiracy</strong>, <strong>bribery</strong>, or <strong>RICO</strong> statutes rather than § 597, because:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The scheme involved ongoing criminal enterprise activity</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Evidence of vote-buying was embedded in broader racketeering conduct</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>RICO carries stronger penalties and broader evidentiary rules</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>Historical Context: \"Ballot Security\" Groups</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Some prosecutions have targeted organized groups deploying armed individuals near polling places</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>These cases typically invoke <strong>§ 594</strong> but are exceptionally rare and usually involve small, ad-hoc groups—not established street crime organizations [[41]][[44]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">📊 DOJ Prosecution Data: What\'s Actually Charged</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to the DOJ\'s <em>Federal Prosecution of Election Offenses</em> manual and FBI guidance:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Federal election crimes fall into three categories: <strong>campaign finance violations</strong>, <strong>voter/ballot fraud</strong>, and <strong>civil rights violations</strong> [[51]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Voter intimidation prosecutions under § 594 are exceedingly rare</strong>: The manual notes that \"prosecutions for voter intimidation are uncommon\" and typically require clear evidence of targeted coercion linked to a federal candidate [[62]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When organized crime intersects with elections, prosecutors prefer <strong>RICO</strong> or <strong>conspiracy charges</strong> because they:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Allow introduction of broader pattern-of-conduct evidence</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Carry higher penalties</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Avoid the narrow intent requirements of election-specific statutes</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">✅ Bottom Line</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Answer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Are there criminal cases prosecuting street gangs under 18 U.S.C. § 594, 597, or 610?</strong></td><td>No publicly reported cases directly applying these statutes to traditional organized street crime enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Can organized crime groups be prosecuted for election interference?</strong></td><td>Yes—but typically under RICO, conspiracy, fraud, or civil rights statutes, not the narrow voting statutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Why the gap?</strong></td><td>The voting statutes require proof of <em>election-specific intent</em> (influencing a federal vote), whereas street crime prosecutions focus on broader criminal patterns</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔎 If You\'re Researching a Specific Hypothesis</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re investigating whether military voting data or election interference by organized groups affected a Hillsborough County race, I can help you:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for Florida-specific election fraud prosecutions involving organized groups</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate academic studies on military voting behavior and potential coercion risks</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Draft a public records request for Hillsborough County absentee ballot metadata (anonymized)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What specific angle are you exploring? That would help me narrow the search further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Don\'t Typically Apply to Street Crime','','inherit','closed','closed','','83-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:01:02','2026-05-20 18:01:02','',83,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=84',0,'revision','',0),
(85,1,'2026-05-20 18:05:13','2026-05-20 18:05:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, I need to clarify an important distinction: <strong>the voting-specific statutes we discussed (18 U.S.C. §§ 594, 597, 610) are rarely, if ever, used to prosecute traditional \"organized street crime\"</strong> (e.g., gangs, drug trafficking organizations, racketeering enterprises). Here\'s what the data shows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔍 Why These Statutes Don\'t Typically Apply to Street Crime</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Statute</th><th>Primary Scope</th><th>Why It Rarely Targets Street Organizations</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>§ 594 (Voter Intimidation)</strong></td><td>Interference with federal election voting rights</td><td>Requires proof of <em>intent to influence how someone votes for a federal candidate</em>—not general coercion or violence</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 597 (Vote Buying)</strong></td><td>Expenditures to influence vote choice</td><td>Targets quid-pro-quo vote transactions, not broader criminal enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>§ 610 (Political Coercion)</strong></td><td>Coercion of <em>federal employees</em> (including military) regarding political activity</td><td>Narrowly focused on government employment relationships</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These statutes are <strong>election-specific</strong>, not general anti-coercion laws. Prosecutors pursuing organized crime groups typically use broader tools like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>RICO Act</strong> (18 U.S.C. §§ 1961–1968) for pattern-of-racketeering cases [[30]