wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Voter intimidation prosecutions under § 594 are exceedingly rare</strong>: The manual notes that \"prosecutions for voter intimidation are uncommon\" and typically require clear evidence of targeted coercion linked to a federal candidate [[62]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When organized crime intersects with elections, prosecutors prefer <strong>RICO</strong> or <strong>conspiracy charges</strong> because they:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Allow introduction of broader pattern-of-conduct evidence</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Carry higher penalties</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Avoid the narrow intent requirements of election-specific statutes</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">✅ Bottom Line</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Answer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Are there criminal cases prosecuting street gangs under 18 U.S.C. § 594, 597, or 610?</strong></td><td>No publicly reported cases directly applying these statutes to traditional organized street crime enterprises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Can organized crime groups be prosecuted for election interference?</strong></td><td>Yes—but typically under RICO, conspiracy, fraud, or civil rights statutes, not the narrow voting statutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Why the gap?</strong></td><td>The voting statutes require proof of <em>election-specific intent</em> (influencing a federal vote), whereas street crime prosecutions focus on broader criminal patterns</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔎 If You\'re Researching a Specific Hypothesis</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'re investigating whether military voting data or election interference by organized groups affected a Hillsborough County race, I can help you:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for Florida-specific election fraud prosecutions involving organized groups</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Locate academic studies on military voting behavior and potential coercion risks</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Draft a public records request for Hillsborough County absentee ballot metadata (anonymized)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What specific angle are you exploring? That would help me narrow the search further.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Based on my research...','','inherit','closed','closed','','85-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:05:13','2026-05-20 18:05:13','',85,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=86',0,'revision','',0),
(87,1,'2026-05-20 18:10:55','2026-05-20 18:10:55','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here are <strong>key academic studies on military voting behavior and potential coercion risks</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Core Academic Studies on Military Voting Behavior</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>1. Veteran Turnout &amp; Political Participation</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Teigen, Jeremy M. (2006). \"Enduring Effects of the Uniform: Previous Military Experience and Voting Turnout.\" <em>Political Research Quarterly</em>, 59(4), 601-607.</strong> [[109]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Methodology</strong>: Analysis of three decades of pooled national cross-sectional data among males</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Findings</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military service positively influences turnout for WWII, Korean War, and post-conscription era veterans</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Vietnam-era veterans exhibited <em>lower</em> turnout rates than nonveteran peers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Socialization effects rival self-selection bias</strong> in explaining increased veteran turnout</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military service inculcates politically relevant traits that influence participation later in life</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Button, Eric D. &amp; Diallo, Anne (2020). \"Voting Behavior of Active Duty Military Spouses: Trends in Interest and Participation.\" <em>Armed Forces &amp; Society</em>.</strong> [[98]][[100]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Methodology</strong>: Logistic regression analysis of FVAP\'s 2010 Post-Election Voting Survey of Active Duty Military Spouses</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Framework</strong>: Matsusaka\'s information theory-based economic model of voter turnout</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Findings</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Voting interest/participation increased among those who: planned to vote, received more election information, voted within previous 6 years, and were older</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Absentee status did NOT diminish voting interest or participation</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military spouses are \"uniquely positioned between military service and civilian life\" and underserved by current protections</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. Partisan Bias &amp; Political Attitudes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Partisan Bias Among U.S. Military Service Members and Veterans\" (University of Kansas)</strong> [[69]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines partisanship as influence on political attitudes and behavior</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>References foundational work by Bartels (2000, 2002), Campbell et al. (1960), Green, Palmquist</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Golby, Jonathan, Cohn, Lindsay, &amp; Feaver, Peter (2016). Research on military officer partisan identification</strong> [[70]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Studies demonstrate increase in partisan identification among military officers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cited in \"Veterans and Bipartisanship\" research</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Are the U.S. Military\'s Nonpartisan Norms Eroding?\" (2022). <em>Armed Forces &amp; Society</em>.</strong> [[71]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines evidence for eroding nonpartisan norms</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analyzes U.S. military servicemembers\' partisan affiliations and political activism levels</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Polarized Patriots: Political Giving by U.S. Military Officers\" (2025). <em>Armed Forces &amp; Society</em>.</strong> [[74]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Finding</strong>: Military officer donors are polarized, sorted by partisan donation tendencies and divided by political ideology</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>3. Military Political Behavior - Comprehensive Analysis</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Inbody, Donald S. (2016). \"American Military Political Behavior.\" In <em>The Soldier Vote</em>. Palgrave Macmillan.</strong> [[35]][[77]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Findings</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Soldiers vote much like most Americans; usual demographic predictors are good</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Officers tend to vote for Republicans while enlisted are more evenly divided</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Addresses civil-military relations and the \"gap\" between military and civilian society</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>References extensive prior research on voting patterns among high-ranking military officers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>4. Self-Selection vs. Socialization</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Would You Like to Know More? Selection, Socialization, and the Political Attitudes of Military Veterans\" (2022). <em>Political Research Quarterly</em>.</strong> [[113]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Revisits Vietnam-era research on whether veteran political attitudes differ from civilians</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Explores selection vs. socialization mechanisms</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Johnson, Brian. (2010). \"Service Matters: The Influence of Military Service on Political Behavior, Ideology and…\"</strong> [[76]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Explores influence of military service on political behaviors and attitudes</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines existing studies of the topic</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Critical Gap: Coercion Risk Research</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Notably, I found NO academic studies directly examining coercion risks or command influence in U.S. military voting.</strong> This is a significant research gap. However, related work includes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>5. Civil-Military Relations &amp; Norms</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"No Right to Be Wrong: What Americans Think about Civil-Military Relations\" (2021). <em>Perspectives on Politics</em>.</strong> [[67]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Americans are extraordinarily deferential to the military</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do not accept basic premises of democratic civil-military relations</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Unlawful Command Influence\" - ACLU</strong> [[78]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Discusses command influence in military justice context (not voting specifically)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>6. Structural Vulnerabilities (Non-Academic Sources)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Brennan Center for Justice (2009). \"Voting Obstacles Suppress Military Vote.\"</strong> [[83]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Documents procedural barriers to military voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Discusses bipartisan overhaul of absentee voting process</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pew Charitable Trusts. \"No Time to Vote.\"</strong> [[82]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Highlights timing challenges for overseas military personnel</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Documents ballot transit problems</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>NIST (2011). \"Security Considerations for Remote Electronic UOCAVA Voting.\"</strong> [[88]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Technical analysis of security risks in electronic voting for military/overseas voters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Does not address coercion specifically</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Primary Data Sources Used in These Studies</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Post-Election Voting Surveys (PEVS)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-ADM (Active Duty Military)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-Spouse (Military Spouses)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-O (Overseas Citizens)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Interactive Data Center</strong> [[51]][[105]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Most comprehensive data on U.S. military and overseas voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Reports registration and voting activities</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>National cross-sectional surveys</strong> (ANES, CPS Voting and Registration Supplements)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Reports to Congress</strong> (mandated under UOCAVA) [[58]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Key Research Gaps Identified</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❌ <strong>No empirical studies on:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Command influence or coercion in military voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Effectiveness of ballot secrecy protections for service members</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Vulnerability of junior enlisted personnel to political pressure</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Impact of unit-level voting assistance programs on voter autonomy</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Comparison of coercion risks across service branches</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Well-documented areas:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Turnout rates (veterans vote at higher rates)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Partisan preferences (officers lean Republican; enlisted more mixed)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Procedural barriers (ballot timing, transmission issues)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Socialization vs. self-selection effects</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Would you like me to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for specific FVAP research notes or technical reports?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Look for comparative studies from other democracies with military voting?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find legal scholarship on unlawful command influence and voting rights?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Core Academic Studies on Military Voting Behavior','','trash','open','open','','core-academic-studies-on-military-voting-behavior__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=87',0,'post','',0),
