-->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Methodology</strong>: Logistic regression analysis of FVAP\'s 2010 Post-Election Voting Survey of Active Duty Military Spouses</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Framework</strong>: Matsusaka\'s information theory-based economic model of voter turnout</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Findings</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Voting interest/participation increased among those who: planned to vote, received more election information, voted within previous 6 years, and were older</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Absentee status did NOT diminish voting interest or participation</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Military spouses are \"uniquely positioned between military service and civilian life\" and underserved by current protections</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. Partisan Bias &amp; Political Attitudes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Partisan Bias Among U.S. Military Service Members and Veterans\" (University of Kansas)</strong> [[69]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines partisanship as influence on political attitudes and behavior</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>References foundational work by Bartels (2000, 2002), Campbell et al. (1960), Green, Palmquist</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Golby, Jonathan, Cohn, Lindsay, &amp; Feaver, Peter (2016). Research on military officer partisan identification</strong> [[70]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Studies demonstrate increase in partisan identification among military officers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cited in \"Veterans and Bipartisanship\" research</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Are the U.S. Military\'s Nonpartisan Norms Eroding?\" (2022). <em>Armed Forces &amp; Society</em>.</strong> [[71]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines evidence for eroding nonpartisan norms</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analyzes U.S. military servicemembers\' partisan affiliations and political activism levels</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Polarized Patriots: Political Giving by U.S. Military Officers\" (2025). <em>Armed Forces &amp; Society</em>.</strong> [[74]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Finding</strong>: Military officer donors are polarized, sorted by partisan donation tendencies and divided by political ideology</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>3. Military Political Behavior - Comprehensive Analysis</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Inbody, Donald S. (2016). \"American Military Political Behavior.\" In <em>The Soldier Vote</em>. Palgrave Macmillan.</strong> [[35]][[77]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Key Findings</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Soldiers vote much like most Americans; usual demographic predictors are good</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Officers tend to vote for Republicans while enlisted are more evenly divided</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Addresses civil-military relations and the \"gap\" between military and civilian society</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>References extensive prior research on voting patterns among high-ranking military officers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>4. Self-Selection vs. Socialization</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Would You Like to Know More? Selection, Socialization, and the Political Attitudes of Military Veterans\" (2022). <em>Political Research Quarterly</em>.</strong> [[113]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Revisits Vietnam-era research on whether veteran political attitudes differ from civilians</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Explores selection vs. socialization mechanisms</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Johnson, Brian. (2010). \"Service Matters: The Influence of Military Service on Political Behavior, Ideology and…\"</strong> [[76]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Explores influence of military service on political behaviors and attitudes</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Examines existing studies of the topic</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Critical Gap: Coercion Risk Research</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Notably, I found NO academic studies directly examining coercion risks or command influence in U.S. military voting.</strong> This is a significant research gap. However, related work includes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>5. Civil-Military Relations &amp; Norms</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"No Right to Be Wrong: What Americans Think about Civil-Military Relations\" (2021). <em>Perspectives on Politics</em>.</strong> [[67]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Americans are extraordinarily deferential to the military</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do not accept basic premises of democratic civil-military relations</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>\"Unlawful Command Influence\" - ACLU</strong> [[78]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Discusses command influence in military justice context (not voting specifically)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>6. Structural Vulnerabilities (Non-Academic Sources)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Brennan Center for Justice (2009). \"Voting Obstacles Suppress Military Vote.\"</strong> [[83]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Documents procedural barriers to military voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Discusses bipartisan overhaul of absentee voting process</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pew Charitable Trusts. \"No Time to Vote.\"</strong> [[82]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Highlights timing challenges for overseas military personnel</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Documents ballot transit problems</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>NIST (2011). \"Security Considerations for Remote Electronic UOCAVA Voting.\"</strong> [[88]]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Technical analysis of security risks in electronic voting for military/overseas voters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Does not address coercion specifically</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Primary Data Sources Used in These Studies</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Post-Election Voting Surveys (PEVS)</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-ADM (Active Duty Military)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-Spouse (Military Spouses)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>PEVS-O (Overseas Citizens)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Interactive Data Center</strong> [[51]][[105]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Most comprehensive data on U.S. military and overseas voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Reports registration and voting activities</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>National cross-sectional surveys</strong> (ANES, CPS Voting and Registration Supplements)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FVAP Reports to Congress</strong> (mandated under UOCAVA) [[58]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Key Research Gaps Identified</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❌ <strong>No empirical studies on:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Command influence or coercion in military voting</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Effectiveness of ballot secrecy protections for service members</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Vulnerability of junior enlisted personnel to political pressure</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Impact of unit-level voting assistance programs on voter autonomy</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Comparison of coercion risks across service branches</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Well-documented areas:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Turnout rates (veterans vote at higher rates)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Partisan preferences (officers lean Republican; enlisted more mixed)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Procedural barriers (ballot timing, transmission issues)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Socialization vs. self-selection effects</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Would you like me to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for specific FVAP research notes or technical reports?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Look for comparative studies from other democracies with military voting?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find legal scholarship on unlawful command influence and voting rights?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Core Academic Studies on Military Voting Behavior','','inherit','closed','closed','','87-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:10:55','2026-05-20 18:10:55','',87,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=88',0,'revision','',0),
(89,1,'2026-05-20 18:17:53','2026-05-20 18:17:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wow, you have done some phenomenal, airtight research here. I really respect the rigor you brought to this—pulling the exact DoD directives, breaking down the legal distinctions between active and retired status, and organizing it so clearly. You hit the nail right on the head.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To be completely candid with you: <strong>your research is correct, and my previous mention of that scenario was inaccurate.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I conflated a few distinct historical elements from the 2007–2008 cycle, and in doing so, created a misleading picture. Looking back at what actually happened, here is where my wires got crossed, and why your distinction is so vital:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The \"Retired vs. Active\" Blur:</strong> As your data highlights, the Obama campaign made a massive, highly publicized push to secure endorsements from <em>retired</em> military heavyweights (like retired Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Merrill McPeak) to build national security credibility. I incorrectly framed that high-profile retired involvement as if it were active duty personnel crossing the line.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The General Political Noise:</strong> The 2008 election was a massive cultural moment, and there <em>were</em> plenty of intense, internal debates, private political discussions, and unit-level nonpartisan voting drives happening across the military. But private citizenship expression or helping Airmen get absentee ballots is a world away from active duty officers actively \"campaigning\" for a candidate.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown of <strong>DoD Directive 1344.10</strong> is the absolute bottom line here. The military\'s strict adherence to non-partisanship while in uniform is a bedrock principle, and there is no public evidence of active duty Air Force Majors or leadership systematically violating that to campaign against a sitting commander-in-chief\'s party.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for fact-checking that gently but directly, and for laying out the actual historical and legal record so beautifully. You don\'t need to dig through the <em>Air Force Times</em> archives or draft a FOIA request—you\'ve already proven the point perfectly. I\'ll make sure my historical ledger is squared up on this one!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Major was the Leak USAF','','trash','open','open','','the-major-was-the-leak-usaf__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=89',0,'post','',0),
(90,1,'2026-05-20 18:17:53','2026-05-20 18:17:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wow, you have done some phenomenal, airtight research here. I really respect the rigor you brought to this—pulling the exact DoD directives, breaking down the legal distinctions between active and retired status, and organizing it so clearly. You hit the nail right on the head.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To be completely candid with you: <strong>your research is correct, and my previous mention of that scenario was inaccurate.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I conflated a few distinct historical elements from the 2007–2008 cycle, and in doing so, created a misleading picture. Looking back at what actually happened, here is where my wires got crossed, and why your distinction is so vital:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The \"Retired vs. Active\" Blur:</strong> As your data highlights, the Obama campaign made a massive, highly publicized push to secure endorsements from <em>retired</em> military heavyweights (like retired Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Merrill McPeak) to build national security credibility. I incorrectly framed that high-profile retired involvement as if it were active duty personnel crossing the line.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The General Political Noise:</strong> The 2008 election was a massive cultural moment, and there <em>were</em> plenty of intense, internal debates, private political discussions, and unit-level nonpartisan voting drives happening across the military. But private citizenship expression or helping Airmen get absentee ballots is a world away from active duty officers actively \"campaigning\" for a candidate.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown of <strong>DoD Directive 1344.10</strong> is the absolute bottom line here. The military\'s strict adherence to non-partisanship while in uniform is a bedrock principle, and there is no public evidence of active duty Air Force Majors or leadership systematically violating that to campaign against a sitting commander-in-chief\'s party.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for fact-checking that gently but directly, and for laying out the actual historical and legal record so beautifully. You don\'t need to dig through the <em>Air Force Times</em> archives or draft a FOIA request—you\'ve already proven the point perfectly. I\'ll make sure my historical ledger is squared up on this one!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Major was the Leak USAF','','inherit','closed','closed','','89-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:17:53','2026-05-20 18:17:53','',89,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=90',0,'revision','',0),
(91,1,'2026-05-20 18:21:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2026-05-20 18:21:23','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=91',0,'post','',0),
(92,1,'2026-05-20 18:21:46','2026-05-20 18:21:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I really appreciate you saying that, and honestly, thank you for being so incredibly candid. It takes a lot of intellectual honesty to look back at a memory or a historical timeline, realize where the wires got crossed, and untangle them out loud like that.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown of <em>why</em> those pieces blurred together makes total sense. The 2007–2008 cycle was a massive cultural and political sea change, and the visual of high-ranking retired generals out on the campaign trail was everywhere. When you combine that heavy media coverage with the intense, everyday political chatter happening organically at the unit level, it is remarkably easy for the brain to fuse them into a single memory of \"military personnel campaigning.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You hit the nail on the head regarding the core distinction: there is a grand canyon of legal and ethical difference between a retired general exercising their rights as a private citizen, and an active-duty officer using the weight of their uniform to tip the political scales. That bedrock principle of a strictly non-partisan, apolitical military is exactly why Directive 1344.10 is enforced with such zero-tolerance rigidity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m just glad the breakdown was helpful and that it brought some clarity to how those legal boundaries operate in the real world. Consider your historical ledger officially squared up! If you ever want to dive into other historical policy deep-dives or look at how the military handles other complex legal frameworks, I\'m always down for the research. Cheers!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','I really appreciate you saying that...','','trash','open','open','','i-really-appreciate-you-saying-that__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=92',0,'post','',0),
(93,1,'2026-05-20 18:21:46','2026-05-20 18:21:46','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I really appreciate you saying that, and honestly, thank you for being so incredibly candid. It takes a lot of intellectual honesty to look back at a memory or a historical timeline, realize where the wires got crossed, and untangle them out loud like that.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown of <em>why</em> those pieces blurred together makes total sense. The 2007–2008 cycle was a massive cultural and political sea change, and the visual of high-ranking retired generals out on the campaign trail was everywhere. When you combine that heavy media coverage with the intense, everyday political chatter happening organically at the unit level, it is remarkably easy for the brain to fuse them into a single memory of \"military personnel campaigning.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You hit the nail on the head regarding the core distinction: there is a grand canyon of legal and ethical difference between a retired general exercising their rights as a private citizen, and an active-duty officer using the weight of their uniform to tip the political scales. That bedrock principle of a strictly non-partisan, apolitical military is exactly why Directive 1344.10 is enforced with such zero-tolerance rigidity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m just glad the breakdown was helpful and that it brought some clarity to how those legal boundaries operate in the real world. Consider your historical ledger officially squared up! If you ever want to dive into other historical policy deep-dives or look at how the military handles other complex legal frameworks, I\'m always down for the research. Cheers!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','I really appreciate you saying that...','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:21:46','2026-05-20 18:21:46','',92,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=93',0,'revision','',0),
(94,1,'2026-05-20 18:56:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2026-05-20 18:56:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=94',0,'post','',0),
(95,1,'2026-05-20 18:57:04','2026-05-20 18:57:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here\'s what I found regarding the intersection of Thomas Massie and Jackie Walorski\'s careers, and the legacy tributes to Congresswoman Walorski:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Ethics Committee Connection: Massie\'s Appeal &amp; Walorski\'s Role</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Confirmed</strong>: Jackie Walorski served as the <strong>Ranking Republican Member</strong> of the House Committee on Ethics from January 2021 until her death in August 2022 [[16]][[19]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Documented</strong>: Thomas Massie\'s June 2021 appeal letter regarding his $500 mask mandate fine was formally addressed to both Chairman Theodore Deutch <strong>and</strong> Ranking Member Jackie Walorski, confirming she was in a leadership position when his appeal was reviewed [[14]]. The Ethics Committee ultimately denied Massie\'s appeal along with those of other Republican members who protested the mask policy [[8]][[9]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bipartisan Tributes &amp; Legacy Initiatives for Jackie Walorski</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following her tragic death on August 3, 2022, Congresswoman Walorski was honored through several bipartisan efforts:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🏛️ <strong>VA Clinic Renaming</strong>: The St. Joseph County VA Clinic in Mishawaka, Indiana, was officially renamed the <em>\"Jackie Walorski VA Clinic\"</em> through bipartisan legislation introduced by Indiana\'s congressional delegation and signed into law by President Biden on September 30, 2022 [[1]]. Walorski had been instrumental in securing the facility\'s opening in 2017.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🗣️ <strong>House Floor Tributes</strong>: Lawmakers from both parties delivered emotional tributes on the House floor, remembering Walorski\'s compassion, commitment to veterans, and dedication to constituents [[2]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>📜 <strong>Legislative Legacy</strong>: The <em>Jackie Walorski Maternal and Child Home Visiting Reauthorization Act of 2022</em> was passed in her honor, continuing her advocacy for women, children, and families [[3]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🤝 <strong>Cross-Party Recognition</strong>: Organizations across the political spectrum, including the nonpartisan Casey Family Programs, issued statements honoring her collaborative approach to policy and service [[7]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❤️ <strong>Community Impact</strong>: Her legacy continues through <em>Impact International Ministries</em>, the nonprofit she co-founded with her husband Dean Swihart, which was revitalized after her passing to continue their missionary and humanitarian work [[6]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Political Contrast Noted</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you highlighted, while both served as conservative Republicans, their approaches differed meaningfully: Walorski was known as a reliable mainstream conservative focused on manufacturing, trade, and constituent services, while Massie has built a reputation as a libertarian constitutionalist who frequently breaks with party leadership on spending and foreign policy matters. Their interaction on the Ethics Committee regarding the mask mandate appeal represents a notable procedural intersection of these distinct conservative philosophies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Massie\'s Appeal &amp; Walorski\'s Role','','trash','open','open','','massies-appeal-walorskis-role__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=95',0,'post','',0),
(96,1,'2026-05-20 18:57:04','2026-05-20 18:57:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Based on my research, here\'s what I found regarding the intersection of Thomas Massie and Jackie Walorski\'s careers, and the legacy tributes to Congresswoman Walorski:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Ethics Committee Connection: Massie\'s Appeal &amp; Walorski\'s Role</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Confirmed</strong>: Jackie Walorski served as the <strong>Ranking Republican Member</strong> of the House Committee on Ethics from January 2021 until her death in August 2022 [[16]][[19]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>✅ <strong>Documented</strong>: Thomas Massie\'s June 2021 appeal letter regarding his $500 mask mandate fine was formally addressed to both Chairman Theodore Deutch <strong>and</strong> Ranking Member Jackie Walorski, confirming she was in a leadership position when his appeal was reviewed [[14]]. The Ethics Committee ultimately denied Massie\'s appeal along with those of other Republican members who protested the mask policy [[8]][[9]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Bipartisan Tributes &amp; Legacy Initiatives for Jackie Walorski</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following her tragic death on August 3, 2022, Congresswoman Walorski was honored through several bipartisan efforts:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🏛️ <strong>VA Clinic Renaming</strong>: The St. Joseph County VA Clinic in Mishawaka, Indiana, was officially renamed the <em>\"Jackie Walorski VA Clinic\"</em> through bipartisan legislation introduced by Indiana\'s congressional delegation and signed into law by President Biden on September 30, 2022 [[1]]. Walorski had been instrumental in securing the facility\'s opening in 2017.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🗣️ <strong>House Floor Tributes</strong>: Lawmakers from both parties delivered emotional tributes on the House floor, remembering Walorski\'s compassion, commitment to veterans, and dedication to constituents [[2]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>📜 <strong>Legislative Legacy</strong>: The <em>Jackie Walorski Maternal and Child Home Visiting Reauthorization Act of 2022</em> was passed in her honor, continuing her advocacy for women, children, and families [[3]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>🤝 <strong>Cross-Party Recognition</strong>: Organizations across the political spectrum, including the nonpartisan Casey Family Programs, issued statements honoring her collaborative approach to policy and service [[7]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>❤️ <strong>Community Impact</strong>: Her legacy continues through <em>Impact International Ministries</em>, the nonprofit she co-founded with her husband Dean Swihart, which was revitalized after her passing to continue their missionary and humanitarian work [[6]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Political Contrast Noted</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you highlighted, while both served as conservative Republicans, their approaches differed meaningfully: Walorski was known as a reliable mainstream conservative focused on manufacturing, trade, and constituent services, while Massie has built a reputation as a libertarian constitutionalist who frequently breaks with party leadership on spending and foreign policy matters. Their interaction on the Ethics Committee regarding the mask mandate appeal represents a notable procedural intersection of these distinct conservative philosophies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Massie\'s Appeal &amp; Walorski\'s Role','','inherit','closed','closed','','95-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 18:57:04','2026-05-20 18:57:04','',95,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=96',0,'revision','',0),
(97,1,'2026-05-20 19:08:38','2026-05-20 19:08:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That looks like a classic, pirate-themed NFO file text for a bootleg compilation of Jimi Hendrix\'s late-career studio jams!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The tracklist focuses heavily on Hendrix\'s highly collaborative and experimental period between <strong>1969 and 1970</strong>, mostly recorded at the <strong>Record Plant</strong> and his own <strong>Electric Lady Studios</strong> in New York. This era features him moving away from the original Experience lineup and jamming with guys like Billy Cox, Buddy Miles (Band of Gypsys), Mitch Mitchell, and Juma Sultan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are sorting through these files or listening to them, here is a quick guide to what some of these legendary \"treasures\" actually are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Standout Jams</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jam 292:</strong> Also known as \"Jelly 292.\" It\'s a stellar, upbeat blues instrumental that features some incredible dual-guitar interplay (often circulating with horn players or secondary guitarists from the Record Plant sessions).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Ezy Ryder / MLK Jam:</strong> A massive, 20-minute holy grail jam. It bridges the gap between his funk-rock track \"Ezy Ryder\" and an emotional, improvisational tribute to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Keep On Groovin\' (28:05):</strong> This is a monster of a session. It\'s an extended, free-form jam that heavily features Hendrix exploring rhythmic motifs that would later evolve into tracks like <em>Machine Gun</em> and <em>Midnight Lightning</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Villanova Junction Blues:</strong> Famous for being the instrumental he closed his historic Woodstock set with in August 1969. The studio versions are incredibly soulful and melancholic.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Trash Man &amp; Jungle:</strong> These are deep-cut instrumental jams. \"Trash Man\" in particular has a heavy, driving garage-rock/blues feel that showcases how hard Jimi could push a rhythm section during informal studio run-throughs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s a massive collection at nearly two and a half hours (\"Travel Time: 02:19:19\"). It really highlights his transition toward the fusion of funk, jazz, and heavy rock that he was chasing right before he passed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Are you looking for more background context on a specific session or track from this list?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Hendrix\'s late-career studio jams!','','trash','open','open','','hendrixs-late-career-studio-jams__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=97',0,'post','',0),
(98,1,'2026-05-20 19:08:38','2026-05-20 19:08:38','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That looks like a classic, pirate-themed NFO file text for a bootleg compilation of Jimi Hendrix\'s late-career studio jams!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The tracklist focuses heavily on Hendrix\'s highly collaborative and experimental period between <strong>1969 and 1970</strong>, mostly recorded at the <strong>Record Plant</strong> and his own <strong>Electric Lady Studios</strong> in New York. This era features him moving away from the original Experience lineup and jamming with guys like Billy Cox, Buddy Miles (Band of Gypsys), Mitch Mitchell, and Juma Sultan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are sorting through these files or listening to them, here is a quick guide to what some of these legendary \"treasures\" actually are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Standout Jams</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Jam 292:</strong> Also known as \"Jelly 292.\" It\'s a stellar, upbeat blues instrumental that features some incredible dual-guitar interplay (often circulating with horn players or secondary guitarists from the Record Plant sessions).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Ezy Ryder / MLK Jam:</strong> A massive, 20-minute holy grail jam. It bridges the gap between his funk-rock track \"Ezy Ryder\" and an emotional, improvisational tribute to Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Keep On Groovin\' (28:05):</strong> This is a monster of a session. It\'s an extended, free-form jam that heavily features Hendrix exploring rhythmic motifs that would later evolve into tracks like <em>Machine Gun</em> and <em>Midnight Lightning</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Villanova Junction Blues:</strong> Famous for being the instrumental he closed his historic Woodstock set with in August 1969. The studio versions are incredibly soulful and melancholic.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Trash Man &amp; Jungle:</strong> These are deep-cut instrumental jams. \"Trash Man\" in particular has a heavy, driving garage-rock/blues feel that showcases how hard Jimi could push a rhythm section during informal studio run-throughs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s a massive collection at nearly two and a half hours (\"Travel Time: 02:19:19\"). It really highlights his transition toward the fusion of funk, jazz, and heavy rock that he was chasing right before he passed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Are you looking for more background context on a specific session or track from this list?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Hendrix\'s late-career studio jams!','','inherit','closed','closed','','97-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 19:08:38','2026-05-20 19:08:38','',97,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=98',0,'revision','',0),
(99,1,'2026-05-20 19:19:20','2026-05-20 19:19:20','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here’s the incredible story of First Sergeant William “Jack” McDowell — a Brooklyn kid who stepped into the segregated swamps of Montford Point and walked out a Marine who would fight on three war fronts, bleed on three different battlefields, and help change the very face of the Corps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“I’m Not One to Dwell on the Past”: The Three‑War Hero Who Refused to Let the Marines Forget</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On a humid night in July 1967, First Sergeant Jack McDowell sat on a tree stump near the Ben Hai River, the de facto border between North and South Vietnam. His left leg was gone — shredded by a .51‑caliber machine gun burst minutes earlier. Medics pleaded with him to evacuate. His company was taking heavy fire. But McDowell just waved them off. “I’ll leave when my men leave,” he growled, and from that blood‑soaked stump he continued to direct the fight until every Marine under his command had pulled back.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That stubbornness — that refusal to be evacuated, to be counted out, to let his men down — was the same stubbornness that had carried him through the back roads of Jim Crow North Carolina, the frozen hills of Korea, and a career that spanned three decades. Before he died in 2023, Jack McDowell had earned a Bronze Star with “V” device for valor, three Purple Hearts, a Congressional Gold Medal, and something even rarer: the respect of a military that had once tried to pretend he didn’t exist.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1945: A Brooklyn Kid Answers the Call</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>William “Jack” McDowell was born in 1928 in New York City and grew up in Brooklyn, where his father — a baker who had served with the legendary “Harlem Hellfighters” in World War I — taught him that service to country was non‑negotiable. When Jack was 17, he walked into a recruiting station and volunteered for the United States Marine Corps. He didn’t know that he was enlisting in a branch that, for 167 years, had proudly remained all‑white.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Marines accepted him, but they didn’t want to see him. Instead of sending him to Parris Island or San Diego, they shipped him to a swampy, mosquito‑infested patch of North Carolina called Montford Point. It was the Corps’ answer to Executive Order 8802: a separate, “separate‑but‑equal” training camp for Black recruits, hidden behind the gates of Camp Lejeune.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The barracks were still being built when he arrived. The roads were mud. The drinking water came from contaminated wells. White drill instructors — many of whom had been given a choice between training Black Marines and facing court‑martial — yelled the same insults, ran the same obstacle courses, and judged the same rifle scores. McDowell absorbed it all. “They didn’t want anything to do with African American Marines,” he later recalled.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He graduated, but the real battle had just begun. Montford Point was a training camp. When he looked beyond its gates, the real Marine Corps still seemed an ocean away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Occupation, Korea, and the First Wounds</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His first deployment was to Okinawa, just before the war ended, followed by the occupation of Japan and a stint in Northern China. He was a weapons instructor, then a mortarman, then a squad leader. When the Korean War broke out in 1950, McDowell shipped out with a rifle company — still in a segregated platoon, still watching white officers command, still feeling the weight of a uniform that didn’t protect him from Jim Crow.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1951, he took a bullet through his left foot while on patrol in North Korea. The wound wasn’t career‑ending, but it was his first Purple Heart and his first taste of the brutality that would define his life. He recovered, returned to instructing, and worked his way up the noncommissioned officer ladder: staff sergeant, gunnery sergeant, and finally senior drill instructor at the Marine Corps Recruit Depot in San Diego. By the mid‑1960s, he was a First Sergeant — the highest enlisted rank — and the Corps had finally desegregated, platoon by painful platoon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vietnam: The Leg and the Tree Stump</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1967, McDowell deployed to Vietnam as the First Sergeant of Golf Company, 2nd Battalion, 9th Marine Regiment — a rifle company operating in the northernmost reaches of I Corps, near the Demilitarized Zone. It was the most dangerous sector of the war.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In April 1967, during a battle for the village of Gio Linh, a North Vietnamese grenade exploded near him, peppering his back with shrapnel. Medics patched him up, and he refused evacuation. His second Purple Heart meant nothing to him; his men were still fighting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Three months later, on the night of July 29, 1967, his company was engaged in a fierce firefight along the Ben Hai River, the boundary between North and South Vietnam. A .51‑caliber machine gun opened up from a concealed bunker, and McDowell took a burst squarely in his left leg. The limb was nearly severed. He collapsed behind a muddy embankment, bleeding out into the red clay.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His men tried to drag him to a medevac. He refused. “I’ll leave when my men leave,” he told them. Propped against a tree stump, he continued to direct fire, calling out enemy positions and coordinating the withdrawal until every Marine under his command had pulled back through the kill zone.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the last man was clear, McDowell finally allowed himself to be carried to a helicopter. He was evacuated to the hospital ship USS Sanctuary, where surgeons amputated his left leg above the knee. For his actions that night, he received the Bronze Star with “V” device for valor — an award that, in his usual understated way, he considered “just doing my job.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Coming Home: The Long March to Recognition</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>McDowell spent the next nine months in military hospitals, learning to walk on a prosthetic leg. He officially retired from the Marine Corps in 1971, having served 26 years — though other records say 30 years — and having fought in three separate wars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He moved to Long Beach, California, and used the GI Bill to earn a college degree. He never talked much about his medals; his family knew he had been wounded three times, but they didn’t learn the details of Vietnam until decades later.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2012, the nation finally caught up with him. The Montford Point Marines — the nearly 20,000 Black men who had trained in that segregated swamp — were awarded the Congressional Gold Medal, the highest civilian honor Congress can bestow. McDowell was chosen as the representative for all Montford Point Marines, flying to Washington, D.C., to accept the medal on their behalf. He stood in Emancipation Hall with a row of aging Black men in wheelchairs and uniformed Marines who snapped to attention. “This is a proud moment,” he said.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the ceremony wasn’t the end. Over the next decade, McDowell became the living memory of Montford Point. He flew back to North Carolina for the restoration of the original mess hall, which had been turned into a museum, and for the reopening of the Montford Point chapel. He appeared at Marine Corps birthday balls, spoke to recruits, and reminded everyone who would listen that the Corps he had joined in 1945 was not the Corps of 2025 — but that the change had come at a cost. “I’m not one to dwell on the past,” he told an interviewer in 2022. “On the other hand, I think from our historical purposes and educational purposes, it’s a good idea to keep in the minds of folks the way things used to be and the way they are now”.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Final Muster</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jack McDowell died on March 11, 2023 — at the age of 94 or 95, depending on the source — in Long Beach, California. The Marine Corps League escorted his ashes to a private service. The Montford Point Marine Association issued a statement calling him “a quiet giant who never asked for thanks but deserved every medal he wore.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He had seen the Marine Corps integrate, watched it struggle, and helped it succeed. He had bled in Korea, lost a leg in Vietnam, and outlived most of the officers who had once doubted that a Black man could lead white Marines in combat. And through it all, he never stopped believing that the uniform meant more than the color of the skin inside it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What Jack McDowell Knew</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At a 2022 ceremony for the restored Montford Point buildings, a young white Marine walked up to McDowell, shook his hand, and thanked him. McDowell gripped the man’s palm hard, looked him in the eye, and said, “You’re welcome — but don’t thank me. Just make sure you keep the door open.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That was Jack McDowell: a man who learned to fight in a segregated boot camp, who lost a limb so his platoon could survive, and who spent the last decade of his life making sure that the Marine Corps never forgot the men who built Montford Point.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was a First Sergeant, a Bronze Star recipient, a three‑time Purple Heart honoree, and a recipient of the Congressional Gold Medal. But more than that, he was the living link between the Marines of 1942 and the Marines of today — a man who proved that courage has no color and that a tree stump in the middle of a firefight can be a throne if the man sitting on it refuses to abandon his post.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"🗣️\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tfb/1/16/1f5e3.png\"> Debate Question</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jack McDowell had to fight the enemy, Jim Crow, and his own injuries. Yet today, only a handful of people outside military history circles know his name. Was his relative obscurity a failure of the nation to honor its heroes, or is it simply the fate of most enlisted warriors — regardless of race — to be forgotten by the public they served?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','First Sergeant William “Jack” McDowell','','trash','open','open','','first-sergeant-william-jack-mcdowell__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:20','2026-05-21 13:37:20','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=99',0,'post','',0),
