(113,1,'2026-05-20 23:15:48','2026-05-20 23:15:48','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gennady Zyuganov’s article frames a highly specific, state-aligned vision of a changing world order, heavily utilizing the ideological and philosophical rhetoric championed by the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) and the Kremlin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The piece serves as an analytical defense of Chinese President Xi Jinping’s <strong>Global Governance Initiative (GGI)</strong>, which was introduced at the historic Shanghai Cooperation Organization (SCO) summit in Tianjin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Decoding Zyuganov\'s Analysis of the 5 Principles</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Zyuganov translates Xi Jinping’s conceptual framework into the Russian Communist Party\'s strategic worldview. He breaks down how these principles are intended to function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sovereign Equality:</strong> Zyuganov argues that the \"house rules\" of a select few Western nations should not be imposed globally. This principle asserts that a nation’s wealth or military power should not dictate its voting weight or voice in global affairs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Rule of International Law:</strong> The text heavily emphasizes adherence to the UN Charter as a defense mechanism. Zyuganov frames this as a guardrail to stop what he calls the \"law of the jungle,\" criticizing the U.S. and NATO for bypassing international consensus.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A \"New\" Multilateralism:</strong> Rather than tearing down the United Nations, this principle advocates for reforming existing global institutions from within. The goal is to strip away unilateral veto powers or structural biases that favor the West, adapting them to modern realities.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Human-Centered Approach:</strong> This principle targets the socioeconomic gap between the Global North and the Global South. Zyuganov highlights that global governance should focus on practical quality-of-life improvements—such as resource distribution, economic stability, and poverty reduction—rather than what he describes as \"abstractly declaring\" Western-style rights and freedoms.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A Focus on Action:</strong> Zyuganov emphasizes that China does not just present theoretical concepts, but backs them with heavily capitalized infrastructure platforms like the Belt and Road Initiative, the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB), and the BRICS New Development Bank.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Geopolitical Reality Behind the Rhetoric</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While Zyuganov relies on classical Marxist-Leninist terminology (\"imperialism,\" \"global oligarchy,\" \"reactionary forces\"), the context of the article is deeply anchored in a unified front between Moscow and Beijing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The piece highlights the <strong>\"Joint Declaration of the Russian Federation and the People\'s Republic of China on the Establishment of a Multipolar World and a New Type of International Relations,\"</strong> which was signed in Beijing by Vladimir Putin and Xi Jinping during Putin\'s high-profile state visit. This strategic alignment—described by Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi as being \"as stable as a mountain\"—presents the Moscow-Beijing axis as a direct counterweight to Western economic sanctions and diplomatic isolation, particularly in light of ongoing global conflicts, such as the escalated tensions and warfare surrounding Iran.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ultimately, Zyuganov\'s piece is less about standard communist theory and more about a pragmatic, institutional pivot. He positions the SCO and BRICS as the core pillars of a brand-new global framework designed to permanently end Western hegemony.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can watch this video report on <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=djxW6isw9XU\">Putin and Xi\'s Multipolar World Order Declaration</a> to see news coverage of the summit where the leaders signed the historic declaration mentioned by Zyuganov.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Analysis of the 5 Principles','','inherit','closed','closed','','112-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 23:15:48','2026-05-20 23:15:48','',112,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=113',0,'revision','',0),
(114,1,'2026-05-21 00:05:08','2026-05-21 00:05:08','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia3-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/701906697_122132002245041489_5876881727202325943_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=127cfc&amp;_nc_ohc=dBEIhx1sMNkQ7kNvwF9BHwI&amp;_nc_oc=AdofRsbhRS7MGM_ZPg9MuU8OuMR3P5nsOSFK3478AVkgsIhj2X19IInBb2z1T00Fe4w&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia3-2.xx&amp;_nc_gid=nZOHmnOg10GvjhVKpPwTZA&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af5puIYdty0rDxnDg-EQNeUjzM9MAZaEdasNecC1uX2hGQ&amp;oe=6A143695\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The crack of gunfire echoed off the canyon walls. After days of tracking, Lieutenant John L. Bullis and his four scouts had cornered a Comanche raiding party of nearly thirty warriors on the banks of the Pecos River. In the initial assault, Bullis\'s men killed three warriors and wounded a fourth, momentarily seizing the initiative. But the Comanche were too many. They flanked the small patrol, pinning them down for forty‑five minutes before the scouts were forced to retreat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then came the nightmare.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bullis\'s horse bolted, leaving the lieutenant stranded on foot. The Comanche closed in. Surrender meant torture. Death meant mutilation. For a white officer leading a patrol of \"non‑citizen\" scouts—black Seminoles who had fled to Mexico to escape re‑enslavement—the odds of rescue were nil.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But Pompey Factor had other plans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the story of a forgotten American hero—a Black Seminole scout who received the Medal of Honor for riding back into a Comanche firing squad to save a lieutenant’s life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t9d/1/16/1f33e.png\" alt=\"🌾\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Child of Freedom and Exile<br>Pompey Factor was born about 1849 in Arkansas, the son of Hardy Factor, a Black Seminole chief, and a Biloxi Indian woman. The Black Seminoles were the descendants of runaway slaves who had found sanctuary among the Seminole Indians of Florida, intermarrying and forming a distinct, fiercely independent community. After the Second Seminole War (1835‑1842), the U.S. government forcibly removed most Seminoles and Black Seminoles to Indian Territory (present‑day Oklahoma). Fearing re‑enslavement, many Black Seminoles fled to Mexico in the 1850s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pompey Factor’s family was among those exiles. He grew up in Mexico, learning the skills of a border horseman: tracking, scouting, and surviving in the harshest terrain. For nearly two decades, the Black Seminoles lived along the Rio Grande, serving as frontier guards for the Mexican government, earning their freedom with their rifles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1870, the U.S. Army made them an offer. It needed expert trackers to fight the Apache and Comanche on the Texas frontier. In return, the Army promised land, provisions, and a permanent home in Texas. Pompey Factor enlisted on August 16, 1870, as a private in the newly formed Seminole Negro Indian Scouts, attached to the all‑Black 24th Infantry Regiment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t50/1/16/1f525.png\" alt=\"🔥\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Fight at Eagle’s Nest Crossing<br>For five years, Factor and the other scouts waged a brutal irregular war against the Comanche and Apache. They rode out of Fort Clark in Brackettville, Texas, wearing crossed‑arrows insignia that would later become the symbol of the U.S. Army Special Forces. They tracked raiders hundreds of miles into Mexico and back, living in the saddle for weeks at a time. By 1875, Factor had a reputation as a cool‑headed, deadly scout.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On April 25, 1875, Lieutenant John L. Bullis—a white Quaker from New York who had led Black troops during the Civil War—took Factor, Sergeant John Ward, and Trumpeter Isaac Payne on a four‑day patrol. They were riding south of the Pecos River near present‑day Langtry, Texas, when they found fresh tracks: a herd of seventy‑five horses, likely stolen from white settlers, led by a Comanche war party of twenty‑five to thirty warriors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bullis ordered a dismounted attack. The four men crept to within seventy‑five yards of the Comanche camp and opened fire, killing three warriors and wounding a fourth. The Comanche scattered, but quickly regrouped. After three‑quarters of an hour, the scouts realized they were being flanked. Bullis shouted the order to retreat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The scouts ran for their horses, mounted, and started to ride away. Then Factor looked back. Bullis was still on foot, his horse having bolted during the firefight. The Comanche were closing in. Without a horse, the lieutenant would be dead within minutes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Factor didn\'t hesitate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He and Payne wheeled their horses and charged back into the hail of gunfire, laying down a covering fusillade while Ward rode to Bullis, pulled him up behind him, and carried him to safety. Factor kept firing until every member of the patrol was clear.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/ta8/1/16/1f396.png\" alt=\"🎖️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Medal and the Fallout<br>On May 28, 1875—just over a month after the rescue—Pompey Factor, John Ward, and Isaac Payne each received the Medal of Honor. The citation, brief by modern standards, reads:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"With three other men, he participated in a charge against 25 hostiles while on a scouting patrol.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They were three of only eighteen Black soldiers to receive the Medal of Honor during the Indian Wars. Their commander, Bullis, survived to retire as a brigadier general, but his official reports never quite captured the full danger of that afternoon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For Factor, the medal brought prestige but little peace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t2e/1/16/1faa6.png\" alt=\"🪦\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;Desertion, Poverty, and a Forgotten Grave<br>After his heroics, Factor continued serving until New Year\'s Day 1877, when his fellow scout and Medal of Honor recipient Adam Paine was shot dead by a deputy sheriff in Brackettville. Factor, fearing for his own safety, deserted the Army and fled back to Mexico. He later surrendered and returned to service, but the spark was gone. He was finally discharged in 1880.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the next forty years, Factor lived in obscurity on the Texas‑Mexico border, working as a laborer and farmer. In 1926, at the age of 77, he applied for a military pension. His records had been lost, and he struggled to prove he had ever served. Two years later, the Army granted his pension—but it was too late. Pompey Factor died destitute on March 28, 1928, of senility and chronic nephritis. He was buried in the Seminole Indian Scout Cemetery in Brackettville, Texas, alongside his comrades John Ward and Isaac Payne.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His grave marker is simple—a white stone with the words \"Medal of Honor\" etched below his name. No grand monument. No battlefield statue. Just wind, dust, and the quiet respect of a few local descendants who still remember.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tba/1/16/1f54a.png\" alt=\"🕊️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Legacy of the Seminole Scouts<br>Between 1870 and 1914, the Seminole Negro Indian Scouts conducted twenty‑six campaigns and twelve major battles. Not one scout was ever killed or wounded in combat—a stunning record of professionalism and toughness. Four of them—Factor, Ward, Payne, and Adam Paine—received the Medal of Honor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet, in the pantheon of American military heroes, they are almost entirely forgotten. Their history belongs to no single state or tradition. They were Black. They were Indian. They were American. They fought for a nation that had enslaved their parents and a military that would not allow Black soldiers to serve as regular infantry. They took the hardest missions, chased the most dangerous enemies, and earned the highest honor—and then died in poverty, buried in an unmarked plot of Texas scrubland.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tfb/1/16/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"🗣️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;A Question for Our Audience<br>Pompey Factor was a former exile, a Black Seminole who risked his life for a country that had driven his people into Mexico. He received the Medal of Honor for turning back into a Comanche firing squad to save a white officer—a deed of extraordinary, selfless courage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But he died poor, his pension application delayed because the Army had “lost” his records.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Was this a failure of the nation to honor a true hero, or just the sad fate of many old soldiers?&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>See less</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Lieutenant John L. Bullis','','trash','open','open','','lieutenant-john-l-bullis__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=114',0,'post','',0),
(115,1,'2026-05-21 00:05:08','2026-05-21 00:05:08','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia3-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/701906697_122132002245041489_5876881727202325943_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=127cfc&amp;_nc_ohc=dBEIhx1sMNkQ7kNvwF9BHwI&amp;_nc_oc=AdofRsbhRS7MGM_ZPg9MuU8OuMR3P5nsOSFK3478AVkgsIhj2X19IInBb2z1T00Fe4w&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia3-2.xx&amp;_nc_gid=nZOHmnOg10GvjhVKpPwTZA&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af5puIYdty0rDxnDg-EQNeUjzM9MAZaEdasNecC1uX2hGQ&amp;oe=6A143695\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The crack of gunfire echoed off the canyon walls. After days of tracking, Lieutenant John L. Bullis and his four scouts had cornered a Comanche raiding party of nearly thirty warriors on the banks of the Pecos River. In the initial assault, Bullis\'s men killed three warriors and wounded a fourth, momentarily seizing the initiative. But the Comanche were too many. They flanked the small patrol, pinning them down for forty‑five minutes before the scouts were forced to retreat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then came the nightmare.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bullis\'s horse bolted, leaving the lieutenant stranded on foot. The Comanche closed in. Surrender meant torture. Death meant mutilation. For a white officer leading a patrol of \"non‑citizen\" scouts—black Seminoles who had fled to Mexico to escape re‑enslavement—the odds of rescue were nil.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But Pompey Factor had other plans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the story of a forgotten American hero—a Black Seminole scout who received the Medal of Honor for riding back into a Comanche firing squad to save a lieutenant’s life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t9d/1/16/1f33e.png\" alt=\"🌾\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Child of Freedom and Exile<br>Pompey Factor was born about 1849 in Arkansas, the son of Hardy Factor, a Black Seminole chief, and a Biloxi Indian woman. The Black Seminoles were the descendants of runaway slaves who had found sanctuary among the Seminole Indians of Florida, intermarrying and forming a distinct, fiercely independent community. After the Second Seminole War (1835‑1842), the U.S. government forcibly removed most Seminoles and Black Seminoles to Indian Territory (present‑day Oklahoma). Fearing re‑enslavement, many Black Seminoles fled to Mexico in the 1850s.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pompey Factor’s family was among those exiles. He grew up in Mexico, learning the skills of a border horseman: tracking, scouting, and surviving in the harshest terrain. For nearly two decades, the Black Seminoles lived along the Rio Grande, serving as frontier guards for the Mexican government, earning their freedom with their rifles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1870, the U.S. Army made them an offer. It needed expert trackers to fight the Apache and Comanche on the Texas frontier. In return, the Army promised land, provisions, and a permanent home in Texas. Pompey Factor enlisted on August 16, 1870, as a private in the newly formed Seminole Negro Indian Scouts, attached to the all‑Black 24th Infantry Regiment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t50/1/16/1f525.png\" alt=\"🔥\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Fight at Eagle’s Nest Crossing<br>For five years, Factor and the other scouts waged a brutal irregular war against the Comanche and Apache. They rode out of Fort Clark in Brackettville, Texas, wearing crossed‑arrows insignia that would later become the symbol of the U.S. Army Special Forces. They tracked raiders hundreds of miles into Mexico and back, living in the saddle for weeks at a time. By 1875, Factor had a reputation as a cool‑headed, deadly scout.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On April 25, 1875, Lieutenant John L. Bullis—a white Quaker from New York who had led Black troops during the Civil War—took Factor, Sergeant John Ward, and Trumpeter Isaac Payne on a four‑day patrol. They were riding south of the Pecos River near present‑day Langtry, Texas, when they found fresh tracks: a herd of seventy‑five horses, likely stolen from white settlers, led by a Comanche war party of twenty‑five to thirty warriors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bullis ordered a dismounted attack. The four men crept to within seventy‑five yards of the Comanche camp and opened fire, killing three warriors and wounding a fourth. The Comanche scattered, but quickly regrouped. After three‑quarters of an hour, the scouts realized they were being flanked. Bullis shouted the order to retreat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The scouts ran for their horses, mounted, and started to ride away. Then Factor looked back. Bullis was still on foot, his horse having bolted during the firefight. The Comanche were closing in. Without a horse, the lieutenant would be dead within minutes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Factor didn\'t hesitate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He and Payne wheeled their horses and charged back into the hail of gunfire, laying down a covering fusillade while Ward rode to Bullis, pulled him up behind him, and carried him to safety. Factor kept firing until every member of the patrol was clear.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/ta8/1/16/1f396.png\" alt=\"🎖️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Medal and the Fallout<br>On May 28, 1875—just over a month after the rescue—Pompey Factor, John Ward, and Isaac Payne each received the Medal of Honor. The citation, brief by modern standards, reads:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"With three other men, he participated in a charge against 25 hostiles while on a scouting patrol.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They were three of only eighteen Black soldiers to receive the Medal of Honor during the Indian Wars. Their commander, Bullis, survived to retire as a brigadier general, but his official reports never quite captured the full danger of that afternoon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For Factor, the medal brought prestige but little peace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t2e/1/16/1faa6.png\" alt=\"🪦\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;Desertion, Poverty, and a Forgotten Grave<br>After his heroics, Factor continued serving until New Year\'s Day 1877, when his fellow scout and Medal of Honor recipient Adam Paine was shot dead by a deputy sheriff in Brackettville. Factor, fearing for his own safety, deserted the Army and fled back to Mexico. He later surrendered and returned to service, but the spark was gone. He was finally discharged in 1880.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the next forty years, Factor lived in obscurity on the Texas‑Mexico border, working as a laborer and farmer. In 1926, at the age of 77, he applied for a military pension. His records had been lost, and he struggled to prove he had ever served. Two years later, the Army granted his pension—but it was too late. Pompey Factor died destitute on March 28, 1928, of senility and chronic nephritis. He was buried in the Seminole Indian Scout Cemetery in Brackettville, Texas, alongside his comrades John Ward and Isaac Payne.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His grave marker is simple—a white stone with the words \"Medal of Honor\" etched below his name. No grand monument. No battlefield statue. Just wind, dust, and the quiet respect of a few local descendants who still remember.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tba/1/16/1f54a.png\" alt=\"🕊️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;The Legacy of the Seminole Scouts<br>Between 1870 and 1914, the Seminole Negro Indian Scouts conducted twenty‑six campaigns and twelve major battles. Not one scout was ever killed or wounded in combat—a stunning record of professionalism and toughness. Four of them—Factor, Ward, Payne, and Adam Paine—received the Medal of Honor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet, in the pantheon of American military heroes, they are almost entirely forgotten. Their history belongs to no single state or tradition. They were Black. They were Indian. They were American. They fought for a nation that had enslaved their parents and a military that would not allow Black soldiers to serve as regular infantry. They took the hardest missions, chased the most dangerous enemies, and earned the highest honor—and then died in poverty, buried in an unmarked plot of Texas scrubland.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tfb/1/16/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"🗣️\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;A Question for Our Audience<br>Pompey Factor was a former exile, a Black Seminole who risked his life for a country that had driven his people into Mexico. He received the Medal of Honor for turning back into a Comanche firing squad to save a white officer—a deed of extraordinary, selfless courage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But he died poor, his pension application delayed because the Army had “lost” his records.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Was this a failure of the nation to honor a true hero, or just the sad fate of many old soldiers?&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>See less</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Lieutenant John L. Bullis','','inherit','closed','closed','','114-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 00:05:08','2026-05-21 00:05:08','',114,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=115',0,'revision','',0),
(116,1,'2026-05-21 00:20:57','2026-05-21 00:20:57','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia5-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/702191495_122131922457041489_8070777643641857006_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s600x600_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=102&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=127cfc&amp;_nc_ohc=t1LGipVk30UQ7kNvwHgXPXY&amp;_nc_oc=Adon-_GXyMubhk4cVz5B39aJLSAfpYQYncCIbzaREgCkAoQTBsk51XNKfYAOxAIxQEE&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia5-1.xx&amp;_nc_gid=1ls8Dpqq7WdAuA-JFQLL2w&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af6PTLpncGl71EVgc33yMxx01HqkkUmXu4y_MUqdePZyig&amp;oe=6A14235A\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was a former slave who could read and write—a rare and dangerous skill for a Black man in post‑Civil War Louisiana. He rode with the legendary Buffalo Soldiers of the 9th Cavalry, leading patrols through the harshest frontiers of Texas. On a single mission in 1870, he rescued a kidnapped boy, captured enemy horses, and routed a band of Apaches without losing a single man.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For that, Sergeant Emanuel Stance became the first African American Regular Army soldier to receive the Medal of Honor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet the same man who wore the nation’s highest award also had a dark side—a raging temper, a thirst for alcohol, and a violent streak that would lead to five demotions and, finally, his own murder on Christmas Eve, 1887. No one was ever arrested. Many believe he was killed by his own troops, men who had simply had enough.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the complex, forgotten story of a hero and a haunted man. <img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"🧵\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/ta0/1/16/1f9f5.png\"><img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"👇\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t4f/1/16/1f447.png\"></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance: The First Black Regular to Wear the Medal of Honor</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From Slave to Buffalo Soldier</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance was born into slavery in 1844 (some sources say 1843 or 1847) in Carroll Parish, Louisiana. His early life was spent picking cotton and avoiding the overseer’s whip, but behind the quarters, a secret was being passed: how to read.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike most enslaved people, Stance learned to read and write—a skill that would later set him apart in the U.S. Army.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On October 2, 1866, less than two months after the 9th Cavalry Regiment was formed, Stance enlisted in Lake Providence, Louisiana. The Army noted his occupation as “farmer”—a common euphemism for former slave—but also recorded that he was literate. That made him an “attractive recruit” in a regiment where most formerly enslaved men could not read or write.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By March 1867, just five months after enlisting, he was promoted to sergeant. The 9th Cavalry soon headed to Texas to take up its position on the frontier. Stance was stationed at Fort Davis with F Troop, where he quickly gained a reputation as a skilled leader in the field.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between 1868 and 1869, Stance led multiple patrols, logging over 630 miles of hard riding, scouting, and fighting against American Indian tribes. By the end of 1869, his unit had moved to Fort McKavett, a remote outpost in west‑central Texas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Mission That Earned a Medal</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On May 20, 1870, the commander of F Troop, Captain Henry Carroll, received urgent news: Apache raiders had kidnapped two young boys, Herman and Willie Lehmann, about 40 miles east of Fort McKavett. Carroll immediately sent Sergeant Stance with a 10‑man detachment to find the boys and recover them from the Apaches.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fourteen miles from the fort, near Kickapoo Springs, Stance’s patrol encountered a group of Apaches. A sharp skirmish erupted, and the Apaches fled into the nearby mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Stance did not stop. He pursued the raiders, captured fifteen of their horses, protected government supplies, and—most importantly—secured the release of young Willie Lehmann. The boy arrived at the Kickapoo Springs subpost the next day, bruised and hungry, but very much alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>(His brother, Herman, remained with the Comanche until 1878.)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this two‑day mission, Captain Carroll immediately recommended Stance for the Medal of Honor—the nation’s highest military award.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Gallantry on Scout After Indians”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 28, 1870, President Ulysses S. Grant approved the award. The citation was unusually brief:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Gallantry on scout after Indians.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sergeant Emanuel Stance became the first African American Regular Army soldier to receive the Medal of Honor in the post‑Civil War era. Eleven other members of the 9th Cavalry would eventually receive the medal, but Stance was the first.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a man who had begun life as a piece of property, this was an extraordinary achievement. The Army did not hand out Medals of Honor lightly in 1870.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Dark Side of a Hero</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the same man who showed “gallantry” in the field was also a nightmare in garrison. Stance was known as a “good fighter with a bad temper.” He brawled with other soldiers, drank heavily, and repeatedly failed to report for duty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between July 1870 and April 1871—less than a year after receiving the Medal of Honor—he was demoted to private. He finished his five‑year enlistment at the lowest rank.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He reenlisted almost immediately, this time in M Troop of the 9th Cavalry. But his behavior did not improve. In December 1872, he got into a fight with his own sergeant, Henry Green, who had reported him drunk while on duty. During the fight, Stance bit off part of Green’s lower lip.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That earned him another demotion and six months in the guardhouse. Over his 21‑year career, he was reduced to private five times and barely avoided discharge on multiple occasions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet he kept reenlisting. And somehow, he kept getting promoted back to non‑commissioned officer. By the mid‑1880s, he had clawed his way up to First Sergeant, the highest enlisted rank.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Christmas Eve, 1887: The Murder of a Hero</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By December 1887, Stance was stationed at Fort Robinson, Nebraska. On the night of December 24—Christmas Eve—he went off post to drink and celebrate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometime after midnight, he was found shot to death near the town of Crawford, Nebraska, about 12 miles from the fort. He was 43 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>No one was ever arrested. No one was ever charged. But the whispers at the fort told a damning story: Stance was killed by his own men. They had grown sick of his abusive behavior, his violent temper, and his drunken rages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The murder weapon was never found. The investigation went nowhere. The first Black soldier to receive the Medal of Honor was buried in an unmarked grave in the post cemetery—now Fort McPherson National Cemetery in Maxwell, Nebraska.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For decades, his final resting place was almost indistinguishable from the paupers\' graves around it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Legacy: A Hero With Wounds We Couldn\'t See</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance left a complicated legacy. He was the first African American Regular to win the Medal of Honor, yet he was demoted five times. He rescued a kidnapped child, yet he bit off another man’s lip. He was a hero, but he was also an alcoholic, an abuser, and a man who may have been murdered by the very soldiers he led.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Historian Frank Schubert put it best:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Stance was a good soldier who lived in a brutal world; under better conditions with better leadership, he might have lived a better life.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1990s, a proper headstone was finally placed at his grave, and Stance’s story was rediscovered by a new generation. Children’s books have been written about him, motivational speakers invoke his name, and he is finally being remembered as the complex human being he was—a hero not because he was perfect, but because he kept fighting despite his demons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"🗣️\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tfb/1/16/1f5e3.png\"> What Do You Think?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Should Emanuel Stance be remembered primarily as a hero who broke a racial barrier, or as a deeply flawed man whose violent end was a direct result of his own behavior?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Was he a victim of his brutal environment—the racism, the frontier violence, the trauma of being born into bondage? Or did his later actions cancel out the valor he showed on May 20, 1870?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drop your thoughts below. <img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"👇\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t4f/1/16/1f447.png\"></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Black man in post‑Civil War Louisiana','','trash','open','open','','black-man-in-post-civil-war-louisiana__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=116',0,'post','',0),
(117,1,'2026-05-21 00:20:57','2026-05-21 00:20:57','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://scontent-mia5-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/702191495_122131922457041489_8070777643641857006_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s600x600_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=102&amp;ccb=1-7&amp;_nc_sid=127cfc&amp;_nc_ohc=t1LGipVk30UQ7kNvwHgXPXY&amp;_nc_oc=Adon-_GXyMubhk4cVz5B39aJLSAfpYQYncCIbzaREgCkAoQTBsk51XNKfYAOxAIxQEE&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-mia5-1.xx&amp;_nc_gid=1ls8Dpqq7WdAuA-JFQLL2w&amp;_nc_ss=7b2a8&amp;oh=00_Af6PTLpncGl71EVgc33yMxx01HqkkUmXu4y_MUqdePZyig&amp;oe=6A14235A\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was a former slave who could read and write—a rare and dangerous skill for a Black man in post‑Civil War Louisiana. He rode with the legendary Buffalo Soldiers of the 9th Cavalry, leading patrols through the harshest frontiers of Texas. On a single mission in 1870, he rescued a kidnapped boy, captured enemy horses, and routed a band of Apaches without losing a single man.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For that, Sergeant Emanuel Stance became the first African American Regular Army soldier to receive the Medal of Honor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet the same man who wore the nation’s highest award also had a dark side—a raging temper, a thirst for alcohol, and a violent streak that would lead to five demotions and, finally, his own murder on Christmas Eve, 1887. No one was ever arrested. Many believe he was killed by his own troops, men who had simply had enough.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the complex, forgotten story of a hero and a haunted man. <img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"🧵\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/ta0/1/16/1f9f5.png\"><img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"👇\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t4f/1/16/1f447.png\"></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance: The First Black Regular to Wear the Medal of Honor</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From Slave to Buffalo Soldier</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance was born into slavery in 1844 (some sources say 1843 or 1847) in Carroll Parish, Louisiana. His early life was spent picking cotton and avoiding the overseer’s whip, but behind the quarters, a secret was being passed: how to read.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike most enslaved people, Stance learned to read and write—a skill that would later set him apart in the U.S. Army.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On October 2, 1866, less than two months after the 9th Cavalry Regiment was formed, Stance enlisted in Lake Providence, Louisiana. The Army noted his occupation as “farmer”—a common euphemism for former slave—but also recorded that he was literate. That made him an “attractive recruit” in a regiment where most formerly enslaved men could not read or write.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By March 1867, just five months after enlisting, he was promoted to sergeant. The 9th Cavalry soon headed to Texas to take up its position on the frontier. Stance was stationed at Fort Davis with F Troop, where he quickly gained a reputation as a skilled leader in the field.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between 1868 and 1869, Stance led multiple patrols, logging over 630 miles of hard riding, scouting, and fighting against American Indian tribes. By the end of 1869, his unit had moved to Fort McKavett, a remote outpost in west‑central Texas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Mission That Earned a Medal</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On May 20, 1870, the commander of F Troop, Captain Henry Carroll, received urgent news: Apache raiders had kidnapped two young boys, Herman and Willie Lehmann, about 40 miles east of Fort McKavett. Carroll immediately sent Sergeant Stance with a 10‑man detachment to find the boys and recover them from the Apaches.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fourteen miles from the fort, near Kickapoo Springs, Stance’s patrol encountered a group of Apaches. A sharp skirmish erupted, and the Apaches fled into the nearby mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Stance did not stop. He pursued the raiders, captured fifteen of their horses, protected government supplies, and—most importantly—secured the release of young Willie Lehmann. The boy arrived at the Kickapoo Springs subpost the next day, bruised and hungry, but very much alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>(His brother, Herman, remained with the Comanche until 1878.)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For this two‑day mission, Captain Carroll immediately recommended Stance for the Medal of Honor—the nation’s highest military award.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>“Gallantry on Scout After Indians”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 28, 1870, President Ulysses S. Grant approved the award. The citation was unusually brief:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Gallantry on scout after Indians.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sergeant Emanuel Stance became the first African American Regular Army soldier to receive the Medal of Honor in the post‑Civil War era. Eleven other members of the 9th Cavalry would eventually receive the medal, but Stance was the first.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a man who had begun life as a piece of property, this was an extraordinary achievement. The Army did not hand out Medals of Honor lightly in 1870.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Dark Side of a Hero</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But the same man who showed “gallantry” in the field was also a nightmare in garrison. Stance was known as a “good fighter with a bad temper.” He brawled with other soldiers, drank heavily, and repeatedly failed to report for duty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between July 1870 and April 1871—less than a year after receiving the Medal of Honor—he was demoted to private. He finished his five‑year enlistment at the lowest rank.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He reenlisted almost immediately, this time in M Troop of the 9th Cavalry. But his behavior did not improve. In December 1872, he got into a fight with his own sergeant, Henry Green, who had reported him drunk while on duty. During the fight, Stance bit off part of Green’s lower lip.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That earned him another demotion and six months in the guardhouse. Over his 21‑year career, he was reduced to private five times and barely avoided discharge on multiple occasions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet he kept reenlisting. And somehow, he kept getting promoted back to non‑commissioned officer. By the mid‑1880s, he had clawed his way up to First Sergeant, the highest enlisted rank.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Christmas Eve, 1887: The Murder of a Hero</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By December 1887, Stance was stationed at Fort Robinson, Nebraska. On the night of December 24—Christmas Eve—he went off post to drink and celebrate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometime after midnight, he was found shot to death near the town of Crawford, Nebraska, about 12 miles from the fort. He was 43 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>No one was ever arrested. No one was ever charged. But the whispers at the fort told a damning story: Stance was killed by his own men. They had grown sick of his abusive behavior, his violent temper, and his drunken rages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The murder weapon was never found. The investigation went nowhere. The first Black soldier to receive the Medal of Honor was buried in an unmarked grave in the post cemetery—now Fort McPherson National Cemetery in Maxwell, Nebraska.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For decades, his final resting place was almost indistinguishable from the paupers\' graves around it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Legacy: A Hero With Wounds We Couldn\'t See</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emanuel Stance left a complicated legacy. He was the first African American Regular to win the Medal of Honor, yet he was demoted five times. He rescued a kidnapped child, yet he bit off another man’s lip. He was a hero, but he was also an alcoholic, an abuser, and a man who may have been murdered by the very soldiers he led.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Historian Frank Schubert put it best:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Stance was a good soldier who lived in a brutal world; under better conditions with better leadership, he might have lived a better life.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1990s, a proper headstone was finally placed at his grave, and Stance’s story was rediscovered by a new generation. Children’s books have been written about him, motivational speakers invoke his name, and he is finally being remembered as the complex human being he was—a hero not because he was perfect, but because he kept fighting despite his demons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"🗣️\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/tfb/1/16/1f5e3.png\"> What Do You Think?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Should Emanuel Stance be remembered primarily as a hero who broke a racial barrier, or as a deeply flawed man whose violent end was a direct result of his own behavior?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Was he a victim of his brutal environment—the racism, the frontier violence, the trauma of being born into bondage? Or did his later actions cancel out the valor he showed on May 20, 1870?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drop your thoughts below. <img height=\"16\" width=\"16\" alt=\"👇\" src=\"https://static.xx.fbcdn.net/images/emoji.php/v9/t4f/1/16/1f447.png\"></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Black man in post‑Civil War Louisiana','','inherit','closed','closed','','116-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 00:20:57','2026-05-21 00:20:57','',116,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=117',0,'revision','',0),
