tem -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Origins and Trajectory of the Conflicts in the Caucasus,\" <em>Europe-Asia Studies</em> (2012) [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Karabakh Conflict After Kosovo: No Way Out?,\" <em>Nationalities Papers</em> (2012) [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"The August 2008 War in Georgia: from ethnic conflict to border wars,\" <em>Central Asian Survey</em> (2009) [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Public Commentary:</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Regular contributor to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>openDemocracy</em> [[3]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Le Monde diplomatique</em>, <em>Neue Zürcher Zeitung</em>, <em>Al-Hayat</em> [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><em>Al Jazeera</em>, <em>SpecialEurasia</em>, <em>Baku Research Institute</em> [[7]][[10]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Policy and Practical Engagement</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Advisory Roles:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Advised governmental agencies and international organizations including:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>UNEP, UNDP, World Bank, OSCE, European Commission\'s ECHO, International Criminal Court [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Served as policy and media advisor on <strong>two UN Commissions of Inquiry</strong> [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Peacebuilding Work:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Involved in development-focused peacebuilding projects across the Middle East, Caucasus, and Central Asia [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Emphasizes the role of development initiatives in sustainable conflict resolution [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Relevance to Ukraine and Eastern Europe</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While Dr. Cheterian\'s primary regional focus is the <strong>South Caucasus</strong>, his analytical framework on:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Russian foreign policy</strong> and its use of \"frozen conflicts\" as leverage [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Ethnic nationalism</strong> and post-Soviet state formation [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Gray zone warfare</strong> and hybrid conflict strategies [[17]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Historical memory</strong> and its instrumentalization in contemporary politics [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…provides essential context for understanding the broader dynamics of the <strong>Russo-Ukrainian War</strong> and Russia\'s approach to its \"near abroad.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His comparative analysis of the 2008 Georgia-Russia war and the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh war highlights recurring patterns: receding Western influence, timing of offensives around U.S. elections, and the urgent need for independent war crimes documentation [[openDemocracy]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Connection to the Broader Group</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Together with the previously discussed figures:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Person</th><th>Primary Lens on Eastern Europe/Ukraine</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Kurt Volker</strong></td><td>U.S. diplomatic engagement and negotiation frameworks</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Arkady Babchenko</strong></td><td>On-the-ground Russian dissent and Ukrainian media perspective</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Anne Applebaum</strong></td><td>Historical scholarship on Soviet repression and authoritarianism</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Oleg Sentsov</strong></td><td>Lived experience of occupation, resistance, and military defense</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Vicken Cheterian</strong></td><td>Comparative conflict analysis, post-Soviet transition, and genocide studies</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cheterian adds critical <strong>academic depth and comparative regional perspective</strong>, helping contextualize Ukraine\'s struggle within broader patterns of post-Soviet conflict, Russian imperial strategy, and the international community\'s often inconsistent responses to aggression and human rights violations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>For further reading: See his articles at <a href=\"https://www.opendemocracy.net/author/vicken-cheterian/\">openDemocracy</a> and <a href=\"https://www.gcsp.ch/experts/dr-vicken-cheterian\">GCSP</a>, or his books through Hurst Publishers and Oxford University Press.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Vicken Cheterian','','inherit','closed','closed','','122-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 02:28:50','2026-05-21 02:28:50','',122,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=123',0,'revision','',0),
(124,1,'2026-05-21 02:36:24','2026-05-21 02:36:24','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Donald Tusk</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Background:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Born April 22, 1957, in Gdańsk, Poland [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Polish politician and historian [[2]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Father worked as a carpenter on the railway; mother worked as a secretary at a hospital [[5]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Co-founded the <strong>Civic Platform</strong> (Platforma Obywatelska, PO) party in 2001 and has served as its leader for most of its history [[3]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Political Career</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Prime Minister of Poland (2007-2014)</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Served as Prime Minister from November 2007 to September 2014 [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>First Prime Minister of Poland to serve two consecutive terms since the fall of communism in 1989 [[9]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Led Poland through the global financial crisis and strengthened Poland\'s position within the EU [[6]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>President of the European Council (2014-2019)</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Served as the second President of the European Council from December 1, 2014, to November 30, 2019 [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Replaced Herman Van Rompuy in this role [[16]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Originally elected to serve a term through May 2017, but was re-elected for a second term [[15]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>During his presidency, he worked on EU unity regarding Brexit, migration, and relations with Russia [[13]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Return as Prime Minister (2023-Present)</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Returned to office as Prime Minister of Poland in December 2023 [[2]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Replaced Mateusz Morawiecki following the 2023 Polish parliamentary election [[7]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leading a coalition government focused on restoring rule of law and Poland\'s relationship with the EU [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In 2025, his Civic Platform party began merging with coalition allies to form the \"Civic Coalition\" [[32]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Positions on Ukraine</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Strong Support for Ukrainian Sovereignty</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Donald Tusk has been one of Ukraine\'s most vocal defenders:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>January 2024</strong>: Visited Ukraine shortly after returning to office, calling the Ukraine-Russia war a fight \"between good and evil\" and promising continued Polish support [[21]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>February 2025</strong>: Called on Western countries to back Ukraine regardless of changes in U.S. policy, warning that a forced surrender of Ukraine would mean \"surrender of entire Western community\" [[20]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>September 2025</strong>: Declared that the war in Ukraine is also \"the West\'s war,\" warning that all of Western civilization is at stake [[22]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>October 2025</strong>: Stated that Ukraine had the right to attack Russia-linked targets anywhere in Europe [[26]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>December 2025</strong>: Emphasized that \"no one should pressure Zelensky on territorial concessions\" and that the international community must \"pressure Russia to end its aggression\" [[25]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>April 2026</strong>: Warned that peace talks on Ukraine cannot be held without Kyiv\'s participation and that European countries will not accept imposed settlements [[24]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>EU-Ukraine Relations</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During his tenure as European Council President:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>July 2018</strong>: Reaffirmed EU commitment to \"advancing the political association and economic integration of Ukraine with the European Union\" following the EU-Ukraine Summit [[27]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Worked to maintain EU unity on sanctions against Russia following the annexation of Crimea and invasion of Eastern Ukraine [[23]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Key Policy Positions</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>European Integration:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Strong advocate for deeper European integration and Poland\'s active role in the EU [[19]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Committed to repairing Poland-EU relations after years of tensions under the previous Law and Justice (PiS) government [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Rule of Law:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Made restoring judicial independence and rule of law in Poland a priority of his government [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>EU Presidency 2025:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Poland held the rotating EU Council Presidency in the first half of 2025 [[19]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Tusk pledged a \"proactive Polish EU presidency\" and to be \"very determined to make Europe think\" [[19]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Relevance to Ukraine and Eastern Europe</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Donald Tusk represents a critical bridge between:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Eastern Europe and Western Europe</strong> - Having led both Poland and the European Council</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>NATO\'s eastern flank</strong> - Poland under Tusk has been a staunch supporter of Ukraine</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>EU enlargement</strong> - Advocates for Ukraine\'s eventual EU membership</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Strategic Importance:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Poland under Tusk has become Ukraine\'s most important Western ally, providing military, humanitarian, and diplomatic support</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>His experience at both the national and EU levels gives him unique insight into coordinating Western response to Russian aggression</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>He has consistently warned against appeasement and emphasized that Ukraine\'s defense is essential to European security</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Connection to the Broader Group</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Together with the previously discussed figures:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Person</th><th>Primary Lens on Eastern Europe/Ukraine</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Kurt Volker</strong></td><td>U.S. diplomatic engagement and negotiation frameworks</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Arkady Babchenko</strong></td><td>On-the-ground Russian dissent and Ukrainian media perspective</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Anne Applebaum</strong></td><td>Historical scholarship on Soviet repression and authoritarianism</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Oleg Sentsov</strong></td><td>Lived experience of occupation, resistance, and military defense</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Vicken Cheterian</strong></td><td>Comparative conflict analysis, post-Soviet transition, and genocide studies</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Donald Tusk</strong></td><td><strong>European political leadership, EU coordination, and unwavering support for Ukrainian sovereignty</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tusk adds the crucial perspective of <strong>European institutional leadership</strong> and demonstrates how a post-communist EU member state can become a champion for democracy and sovereignty in the region. His dual experience as both a national leader and European Council President uniquely positions him to coordinate Western response to Russian aggression.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>For further information: See the <a href=\"https://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/european-council/former-euco-presidents/donald-tusk/\">European Council archives</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.gov.pl/web/primeminister/donald-tusk\">Polish Prime Minister\'s Office</a>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Donald Tusk','','trash','closed','closed','','donald-tusk__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:35:31','2026-05-21 13:35:31','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?page_id=124',0,'page','',0),
