aders he directly empowered over a sixty-year career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Robert L. Woodson, Sr.','','inherit','closed','closed','','135-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 03:04:55','2026-05-21 03:04:55','',135,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=136',0,'revision','',0),
(137,1,'2026-05-21 03:07:51','2026-05-21 03:07:51','<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HIyfuQQXsAIuFMU?format=jpg&amp;name=large\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a deeply moving and significant announcement. Robert L. Woodson, Sr. was a monumental figure in the landscape of American community development and civil rights, and his passing at the age of 89 marks the end of an era for grassroots empowerment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Given the date of the press release—<strong>May 20, 2026</strong>—this news is incredibly current. Passing away peacefully in his sleep just yesterday (May 19, 2026), Bob Woodson leaves behind a legacy defined by his fierce belief that local, indigenous leaders hold the keys to transforming their own troubled neighborhoods.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Legacy of Robert L. Woodson, Sr. (1937–2026)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bob Woodson rejected the top-down, bureaucratic approaches to poverty alleviation that dominated the post-civil rights era. Instead, he pioneered a philosophy centered on \"upward mobility\" and personal agency, famously asserting that the people closest to a problem are the ones best positioned to solve it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Major Milestones &amp; Achievements</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Founding the Woodson Center (1981):</strong> Based in Washington, D.C., the center spent 45 years identifying, funding, and training grassroots leaders. His work led to legendary accomplishments, including orchestrating enduring urban gang truces, revitalizing high-poverty neighborhoods, and reducing neighborhood violence.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Prestigious Recognitions:</strong> His innovative approach earned him a <strong>MacArthur \"Genius\" Fellowship</strong> and the <strong>Presidential Citizens Medal</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Intellectual and Cultural Impact:</strong> Beyond neighborhood organizing, Woodson was a prolific author and intellectual leader. In recent years, he launched the <strong>1776 Unites</strong> initiative—a nonpartisan collection of Black scholars, journalists, and activists dedicated to championing America’s founding values, promoting personal responsibility, and countering a pervasive victimhood mentality.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Structural Transition at the Woodson Center</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The press release notes that the center had a deliberate succession plan in place for several years to ensure that Woodson\'s life work would seamlessly continue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Incoming Leadership:</strong> <strong>Will Crossley</strong> will succeed Robert L. Woodson, Sr. as the President of the Woodson Center.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Mission Forward:</strong> Backed by full board support, the center will maintain its core pillars, including the <em>Community Affiliate Network</em>, <em>Voices of Black Mothers United</em>, and its specialized localized curricula.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>\"He didn’t just build an organization. He built relationships, and those relationships built a movement.\"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>— The Woodson Center Board of Directors</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His passing will undoubtedly reverberate across the civil rights movement, public policy circles, and the thousands of grassroots leaders he directly empowered over a sixty-year career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Robert L. Woodson, Sr.','','inherit','closed','closed','','135-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 03:07:51','2026-05-21 03:07:51','',135,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=137',0,'revision','',0),
