:paragraph -->\n<p>The song functions as a unique crossover because all three artists bring completely different legacies to the table:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Massiv (Wasiem Taha):</strong> A literal giant in German gangsta rap. Originally breaking out in the mid-2000s out of Berlin-Wedding (and known for his label <em>Al Massiva</em>), he is famous for his incredibly deep voice, imposing physical presence, and aggressive street anthems. Beyond music, he gained massive mainstream fame playing the character \"Latif\" in the critically acclaimed TNT/Netflix series <em>4 Blocks</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Crackaveli:</strong> A highly respected veteran of the Berlin underground rap scene. He has been putting out gritty street rap since the late 2000s, often collaborating with artists like Kalusha, Mosh36, and the late street-rap pioneer Deso Dogg.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Yasha (Yasha Conen):</strong> The secret weapon on the track\'s hook. Yasha is a singer and producer best known for providing the iconic, soulful vocals on the diamond-certified 2012 mega-hit <strong>\"Lila Wolken\"</strong> alongside Marteria and Miss Platnum. His melodic, airy style serves as the perfect contrast to the heavy street bars of Crackaveli and Massiv.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">What the Song is About</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>True to its title, <em>SKYLINE</em> plays on the contrast of looking up at the high-rise city skylines from the concrete blocks below. It leans heavily into themes of late-night reflection, street hustle, loyalty to the grid, and chasing success while staying grounded in the urban environments that raised them. Yasha’s melodic chorus gives it a driving, almost melancholic late-night driving anthem feel, while Crackaveli and Massiv anchor it with rugged, raw verses.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','CRACKAVELI x MASSIV x YASHA - SKYLINE','','inherit','closed','closed','','141-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 03:22:54','2026-05-21 03:22:54','',141,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=143',0,'revision','',0),
(144,1,'2026-05-21 03:58:57','2026-05-21 03:58:57','<!-- wp:gallery {\"linkTo\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped\"></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Arwa Mahdawi</strong> is a prominent London-born, New York-based journalist, columnist, speaker, and business consultant known for her sharp, satirical, and progressive commentary on politics, pop culture, technology, and feminism.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is a breakdown of her major work and career milestones:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Journalism and Columns</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mahdawi is most widely recognized for her work with <strong><em>The Guardian</em></strong>, where she writes regular opinion pieces.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"The Week in Patriarchy\":</strong> She pens this popular weekly Guardian newsletter, which recaps and analyzes global news relating to feminism, sexism, and gender equality with a characteristically biting, witty tone.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>General Commentary:</strong> Her columns span a massive variety of contemporary issues, frequently tackling corporate absurdity, billionaire culture, tech dystopias, and the political landscape.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Books and Academic Fellowships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Strong Female Lead: Lessons from Women in Power</em> (2021):</strong> In her first book, Mahdawi uses original research and interviews with global female leaders to challenge traditional, male-centric models of leadership, arguing for a complete redefinition of what it means to be a \"strong leader.\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fellowships:</strong> Acknowledging her impact on media analysis, she was appointed as a 2025/2026 visiting practitioner at the University of Pennsylvania\'s Center for Media Risk.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Satire and Viral Projects<sup></sup></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before focusing heavily on columns, Mahdawi made major waves in tech and media circles by creating <strong>Rent-A-Minority</strong> (which she dubbed the \"Uber for diversity\").<sup></sup> The viral website was a brilliant piece of satire designed to mock corporate \"tokenism\" and empty diversity initiatives by offering companies a way to \"rent\" minorities to look good in photos or meetings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Rent-A-Minority is a satirical response to a very serious problem: the fact that diversity is often treated as a PR exercise rather than a structural issue.\"<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>— <em>Arwa Mahdawi</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Quick Facts</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><td><strong>Attribute</strong></td><td><strong>Details</strong></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Background</strong></td><td>Born in London, UK; currently based in New York City.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Education</strong></td><td>University of Oxford; BPP Law School.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core Topics</strong></td><td>Intersection of technology, modern feminism, wealth inequality, and political satire.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Are you looking for information on a specific column she wrote, or would you like to know more about her book, <em>Strong Female Lead</em>?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Arwa Mahdawi','','trash','closed','closed','','arwa-mahdawi-is-a-prominent-london-born-new-york-based-journalist__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:35:31','2026-05-21 13:35:31','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?page_id=144',0,'page','',0),
(145,1,'2026-05-21 03:58:57','2026-05-21 03:58:57','<!-- wp:gallery {\"linkTo\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped\"></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Arwa Mahdawi</strong> is a prominent London-born, New York-based journalist, columnist, speaker, and business consultant known for her sharp, satirical, and progressive commentary on politics, pop culture, technology, and feminism.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is a breakdown of her major work and career milestones:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Journalism and Columns</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mahdawi is most widely recognized for her work with <strong><em>The Guardian</em></strong>, where she writes regular opinion pieces.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>\"The Week in Patriarchy\":</strong> She pens this popular weekly Guardian newsletter, which recaps and analyzes global news relating to feminism, sexism, and gender equality with a characteristically biting, witty tone.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>General Commentary:</strong> Her columns span a massive variety of contemporary issues, frequently tackling corporate absurdity, billionaire culture, tech dystopias, and the political landscape.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Books and Academic Fellowships</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><em>Strong Female Lead: Lessons from Women in Power</em> (2021):</strong> In her first book, Mahdawi uses original research and interviews with global female leaders to challenge traditional, male-centric models of leadership, arguing for a complete redefinition of what it means to be a \"strong leader.\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fellowships:</strong> Acknowledging her impact on media analysis, she was appointed as a 2025/2026 visiting practitioner at the University of Pennsylvania\'s Center for Media Risk.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Satire and Viral Projects<sup></sup></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before focusing heavily on columns, Mahdawi made major waves in tech and media circles by creating <strong>Rent-A-Minority</strong> (which she dubbed the \"Uber for diversity\").<sup></sup> The viral website was a brilliant piece of satire designed to mock corporate \"tokenism\" and empty diversity initiatives by offering companies a way to \"rent\" minorities to look good in photos or meetings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Rent-A-Minority is a satirical response to a very serious problem: the fact that diversity is often treated as a PR exercise rather than a structural issue.\"<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>— <em>Arwa Mahdawi</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Quick Facts</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><td><strong>Attribute</strong></td><td><strong>Details</strong></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Background</strong></td><td>Born in London, UK; currently based in New York City.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Education</strong></td><td>University of Oxford; BPP Law School.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core Topics</strong></td><td>Intersection of technology, modern feminism, wealth inequality, and political satire.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Are you looking for information on a specific column she wrote, or would you like to know more about her book, <em>Strong Female Lead</em>?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Arwa Mahdawi is a prominent London-born, New York-based journalist','','inherit','closed','closed','','144-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 03:58:57','2026-05-21 03:58:57','',144,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=145',0,'revision','',0),
(146,1,'2026-05-21 04:20:42','2026-05-21 04:20:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Salisbury nerve agent attacks in March 2018 remain one of the most high-profile, complex international and criminal incidents in modern British history. It marked the first offensive use of a nerve agent on European soil since World War II.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The events occurred across two distinct waves, turning a targeted assassination attempt into a broader public health crisis.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Target &amp; The First Wave (March 2018)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On March 4, 2018, <strong>Sergei Skripal</strong> (a former Russian military intelligence officer who acted as a double agent for the UK) and his 33-year-old daughter, <strong>Yulia Skripal</strong>, were found unconscious on a park bench near a shopping center in Salisbury, England.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A massive forensic and scientific investigation led by the UK’s Counter Terrorism Policing and scientists at the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory (Dstl) at Porton Down quickly unlocked the details:<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Weapon:</strong> The Skripals had been poisoned with <strong>Novichok</strong> (specifically the A-234 variant), a highly lethal, military-grade nerve agent originally developed by the Soviet Union.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Delivery Method:</strong> The nerve agent had been smeared in high concentrations directly onto the <strong>front door handle</strong> of Sergei Skripal\'s home.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Collateral Damage:</strong> Detective Sergeant Nick Bailey, one of the first police officers to respond and investigate the Skripal home, was also heavily exposed and fell critically ill.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Miraculously, after weeks in intensive care and intensive specialized medical treatment, Sergei, Yulia, and DS Bailey all survived, though they suffered severe, long-lasting health impacts.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Second Wave (June 2018)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the Skripals survived, the lingering danger of how the nerve agent was disposed of took a tragic turn nearly three months later in the neighboring town of Amesbury.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 30, 2018, two British citizens—<strong>Dawn Sturgess</strong> and <strong>Charlie Rowley</strong>—fell catastrophically ill.<sup></sup> Rowley had found a discarded, counterfeit Nina Ricci perfume bottle in a Salisbury litter bin and given it to Sturgess. Unbeknownst to them, the bottle was highly pure, concentrated Novichok left behind by the attackers. Sturgess sprayed it directly onto her wrist, fell ill within 15 minutes, and tragically died in the hospital on July 8. Rowley survived after extensive treatment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Perpetrators &amp; Political Fallout</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The UK government, backed by independent testing from the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW), concluded that the Russian state was definitively responsible for the attack.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Charges were brought against three Russian nationals traveling under the aliases Alexander Petrov, Ruslan Boshirov, and Sergey Fedotov.<sup></sup> Investigative journalists and UK intelligence unmasked them as highly trained undercover officers from <strong>Unit 29155 of Russia\'s GRU</strong> (military intelligence). In a bizarre and widely mocked international TV interview, the suspects later claimed they were merely \"tourists\" visiting Salisbury to see its famous cathedral and its \"123-meter spire.\"<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The diplomatic backlash was unprecedented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The UK and more than 25 ally nations expelled over 150 Russian diplomats in a coordinated response.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Severe international economic sanctions were levied against Russia.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The containment and decontamination cleanup took a full year, involving hundreds of military personnel clearing 14 contaminated sites.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Public inquiries and official assessments concluded that Russian President Vladimir Putin bears ultimate moral responsibility for the operation, highlighting a pattern of state-sponsored, external assassinations targeting dissidents and double agents on foreign soil.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Salisbury nerve agent attacks in March 2018','','trash','open','open','','the-salisbury-nerve-agent-attacks-in-march-2018__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=146',0,'post','',0),
