ond and investigate the Skripal home, was also heavily exposed and fell critically ill.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Miraculously, after weeks in intensive care and intensive specialized medical treatment, Sergei, Yulia, and DS Bailey all survived, though they suffered severe, long-lasting health impacts.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Second Wave (June 2018)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the Skripals survived, the lingering danger of how the nerve agent was disposed of took a tragic turn nearly three months later in the neighboring town of Amesbury.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June 30, 2018, two British citizens—<strong>Dawn Sturgess</strong> and <strong>Charlie Rowley</strong>—fell catastrophically ill.<sup></sup> Rowley had found a discarded, counterfeit Nina Ricci perfume bottle in a Salisbury litter bin and given it to Sturgess. Unbeknownst to them, the bottle was highly pure, concentrated Novichok left behind by the attackers. Sturgess sprayed it directly onto her wrist, fell ill within 15 minutes, and tragically died in the hospital on July 8. Rowley survived after extensive treatment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Perpetrators &amp; Political Fallout</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The UK government, backed by independent testing from the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW), concluded that the Russian state was definitively responsible for the attack.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Charges were brought against three Russian nationals traveling under the aliases Alexander Petrov, Ruslan Boshirov, and Sergey Fedotov.<sup></sup> Investigative journalists and UK intelligence unmasked them as highly trained undercover officers from <strong>Unit 29155 of Russia\'s GRU</strong> (military intelligence). In a bizarre and widely mocked international TV interview, the suspects later claimed they were merely \"tourists\" visiting Salisbury to see its famous cathedral and its \"123-meter spire.\"<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The diplomatic backlash was unprecedented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The UK and more than 25 ally nations expelled over 150 Russian diplomats in a coordinated response.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Severe international economic sanctions were levied against Russia.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The containment and decontamination cleanup took a full year, involving hundreds of military personnel clearing 14 contaminated sites.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Public inquiries and official assessments concluded that Russian President Vladimir Putin bears ultimate moral responsibility for the operation, highlighting a pattern of state-sponsored, external assassinations targeting dissidents and double agents on foreign soil.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Salisbury nerve agent attacks in March 2018','','inherit','closed','closed','','146-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 04:20:42','2026-05-21 04:20:42','',146,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=147',0,'revision','',0),
(148,1,'2026-05-21 04:24:03','2026-05-21 04:24:03','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Assuming you are looking for a book review of Lieutenant General H.R. McMaster\'s work, a five-star review would heavily depend on which of his major books you are reading.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are five-star style reviews for his three major, highly regarded books:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. For his latest memoir: <em>At War with Ourselves: My Tour of Duty in the Trump White House</em> (2024)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ <strong>An Essential, Unvarnished Look at Modern Governance</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"McMaster delivers a masterclass in modern political history with the precision of a soldier and the objective eye of a PhD historian.<sup></sup> Unlike standard Washington \'tell-all\' cash-grabs, <em>At War with Ourselves</em> rises completely above partisan vitriol.<sup></sup> McMaster is unsparingly candid about the chaotic infighting, backstabbing, and \'malicious grifters\' that plagued the Trump administration, yet he remains deeply objective—praising the administration’s necessary foreign policy pivots while detailing exactly how President Trump\'s ego and insecurities were manipulated by foreign adversaries.<sup></sup> A gripping, frustrating, and ultimately vital read for anyone who wants to understand national security in an era of hyper-partisanship.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. For his policy book: <em>Battlegrounds: The Fight to Defend the Free World</em> (2020)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ <strong>The Antidote to American \'Strategic Narcissism\'<sup></sup></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"This is a brilliant, deeply researched, and incredibly urgent blueprint for Western foreign policy. McMaster\'s core thesis—that America suffers from \'strategic narcissism\' (the flawed belief that the world revolves entirely around US actions)—is a massive wake-up call.<sup></sup> He takes the reader on a global tour of our greatest modern threats, from Russian disinformation to Chinese authoritarian economic models.<sup></sup> What makes this a 5-star book is that McMaster doesn\'t just point out where past administrations failed; he offers concrete, clear-eyed strategic solutions on how the free world can actively compete and prevail. Required reading for the next generation of leaders.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. For his classic history: <em>Dereliction of Duty: Johnson, McNamara, the Joint Chiefs, and the Lies That Led to Vietnam</em> (1997)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ <strong>A Masterwork of Historical Courage and Civil-Military Truth</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"There is a reason this book is standard, mandatory reading at military war colleges. Written while McMaster was still an active-duty officer, <em>Dereliction of Duty</em> is a breathtakingly brave piece of historical analysis. He meticulously tears through declassified documents to show how arrogance, self-interest, and deliberate deception by President Lyndon B. Johnson, Robert McNamara, and a compromised Joint Chiefs of Staff sleepwalked America into the Vietnam disaster.<sup></sup> It is a devastating, beautifully written cautionary tale about what happens when military leaders prioritize political consensus over telling hard truths to power.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>If you were actually looking for a review of H.R. McMaster\'s overall career as a military commander (like his famous tank battles in Operation Desert Storm) rather than a book review, let me know!</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Lieutenant General H.R. McMaster\'s','','trash','open','open','','lieutenant-general-h-r-mcmasters__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=148',0,'post','',0),
