ck-heading\">Broader Perspective</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This history remains deeply contested:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>U.S. perspective</strong>: Operations were defensive responses to a Soviet-aligned regime 90 miles from Florida, supporting Cuban exiles\' right to oppose authoritarian rule.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Cuban perspective</strong>: These were acts of aggression violating sovereignty, justifying defensive measures—including the 1996 intercept.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>International law</strong>: The 1996 shootdown raised complex questions about airspace violations, civilian aircraft protections under the Chicago Convention, and proportionality of response.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The timing of the indictment—on the anniversary of Cuba\'s formal independence from U.S. military occupation (1902)—adds symbolic resonance. It reflects ongoing geopolitical friction, domestic U.S. politics (particularly Florida\'s Cuban-American electorate), and unresolved historical grievances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you\'d like, I can search for:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The full text of the indictment or DOJ press release</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cuban government statements responding to the charges</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analysis from international legal experts on the 1996 incident</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>More detail on specific CIA operations referenced in declassified archives</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What aspect would you like to explore further?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Regarding the Raúl Castro Indictment (May 2026)','','inherit','closed','closed','','154-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 10:36:30','2026-05-21 10:36:30','',154,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=155',0,'revision','',0),
(156,1,'2026-05-21 10:57:31','2026-05-21 10:57:31','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The uploaded document, titled <strong>\"05.20.2026-Ukraine.1.odt\"</strong>, is an export or backup containing a collection of encyclopedic entries, analytical profiles, and personal blog posts<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. It maps out highly detailed timelines, official documentation, and political profiles centered around geopolitical conflicts in Eastern Europe, interspersed with personal reflections from a blog called <em>\"Ongoing Stories of My Soul\"</em><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A structural breakdown of the file reveals the following contents:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Geopolitical Biographies &amp; Profile Entries</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The core of the document consists of a series of comprehensive, referenced profiles detailing figures who represent opposing lines of thought, diplomacy, or physical engagement in Eastern Europe and Ukraine<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Kurt Volker:</strong> Examines his tenure as the U.S. Special Representative for Ukraine Negotiations (2017–2019), detailing his public policy work with the Minsk agreements, the context of his resignation on September 27, 2019, and his subsequent congressional depositions regarding the Trump-Ukraine scandal.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Arkady Babchenko:</strong> A Russian print/television war correspondent and vocal Putin critic who fled to Kyiv. It outlines his military service in Chechnya, his book <em>\"One Soldier\'s War\"</em>, and his collaboration with the SBU to stage his own assassination in May 2018 to expose Russian agents.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Anne Applebaum:</strong> An American-Polish Pulitzer Prize-winning historian and <em>The Atlantic</em> staff writer. The entry lists her major literary works exploring communist and Soviet history, specifically highlighting <em>\"Red Famine: Stalin\'s War on Ukraine\"</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Oleg Sentsov:</strong> A Ukrainian film director and activist from Crimea who was illegally detained by the Russian FSB in 2014 on fabricated terrorism charges. It chronicles his 5-year imprisonment, his grueling 145-day hunger strike, his 2019 release via a prisoner swap, and his active combat role in the Armed Forces of Ukraine following the 2022 invasion.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Dr. Vicken Cheterian: A Swiss-based Lebanese academic and journalist of Armenian descent specializing in comparative conflict analysis, post-Soviet transitions, and the weaponization of historical memory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Donald Tusk:</strong> Focuses on his career as the Prime Minister of Poland and President of the European Council. It catalogs his extensive and firm public positioning on Ukrainian sovereignty and international aid from 2014 through early 2026.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Radek Sikorski:</strong> The current Foreign Minister and Deputy PM of Poland (and husband to Anne Applebaum). It tracks his historical achievements—such as co-architecting the EU\'s Eastern Partnership—and his push for increased European defense rearmament.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Natalia Polyanskaya:</strong> An official under international sanctions who served on the \"People\'s Council\" for the illegal, self-declared separatist Donetsk People\'s Republic (DPR).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Alexander Zakharchenko:</strong> The late pro-Russian separatist leader and Head of the DPR from 2014 until his assassination via an IED explosion at a Donetsk café in August 2018.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. WordPress Blog Data (<em>\"Ongoing Stories of My Soul\"</em>)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The latter half of the document transitions into a meta-log of a WordPress site authored by a user named Deborah Hall<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. It includes titles, dates, metadata, and brief snippets of chronological blog posts written between 2016 and May 21, 2026<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. Notable post topics include:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fact-Checking &amp; Research Notes (2026):</strong> Brief essay write-ups covering data breaches (National Public Data breach and Florida real estate leaks) , clarifying claims surrounding Arsen Avakov\'s resignation letter , military voting statutes , and historical spotlights on figures like Lieutenant John L. Bullis or Black literacy in post-Civil War Louisiana.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Personal Essays &amp; Eulogies (2023–2024):</strong> Moving pieces tracking her transition from Blogger to WordPress , answering curious questions from her grandson , and writing a tribute for the late Professor Raj Ayyar.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Historic Commentary (2016–2017):</strong> Older entries documenting a 2017 satirical or open open letter to Donald Trump, an analysis of school testing metrics (<em>\"If Dr. Seuss Took ISTEP\"</em>), and an emotional reflection written by Hall as an educator coping with burying students or remembering September 11th.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please let me know if you would like me to unpack a specific profile, verify a timeline, or extract any particular piece of data found within this text!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Geopolitical Biographies &amp; Profile Entries','','trash','open','open','','geopolitical-biographies-profile-entries__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=156',0,'post','',0),
(157,1,'2026-05-21 10:57:31','2026-05-21 10:57:31','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The uploaded document, titled <strong>\"05.20.2026-Ukraine.1.odt\"</strong>, is an export or backup containing a collection of encyclopedic entries, analytical profiles, and personal blog posts<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. It maps out highly detailed timelines, official documentation, and political profiles centered around geopolitical conflicts in Eastern Europe, interspersed with personal reflections from a blog called <em>\"Ongoing Stories of My Soul\"</em><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A structural breakdown of the file reveals the following contents:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. Geopolitical Biographies &amp; Profile Entries</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The core of the document consists of a series of comprehensive, referenced profiles detailing figures who represent opposing lines of thought, diplomacy, or physical engagement in Eastern Europe and Ukraine<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Kurt Volker:</strong> Examines his tenure as the U.S. Special Representative for Ukraine Negotiations (2017–2019), detailing his public policy work with the Minsk agreements, the context of his resignation on September 27, 2019, and his subsequent congressional depositions regarding the Trump-Ukraine scandal.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Arkady Babchenko:</strong> A Russian print/television war correspondent and vocal Putin critic who fled to Kyiv. It outlines his military service in Chechnya, his book <em>\"One Soldier\'s War\"</em>, and his collaboration with the SBU to stage his own assassination in May 2018 to expose Russian agents.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Anne Applebaum:</strong> An American-Polish Pulitzer Prize-winning historian and <em>The Atlantic</em> staff writer. The entry lists her major literary works exploring communist and Soviet history, specifically highlighting <em>\"Red Famine: Stalin\'s War on Ukraine\"</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Oleg Sentsov:</strong> A Ukrainian film director and activist from Crimea who was illegally detained by the Russian FSB in 2014 on fabricated terrorism charges. It chronicles his 5-year imprisonment, his grueling 145-day hunger strike, his 2019 release via a prisoner swap, and his active combat role in the Armed Forces of Ukraine following the 2022 invasion.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Dr. Vicken Cheterian: A Swiss-based Lebanese academic and journalist of Armenian descent specializing in comparative conflict analysis, post-Soviet transitions, and the weaponization of historical memory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Donald Tusk:</strong> Focuses on his career as the Prime Minister of Poland and President of the European Council. It catalogs his extensive and firm public positioning on Ukrainian sovereignty and international aid from 2014 through early 2026.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Radek Sikorski:</strong> The current Foreign Minister and Deputy PM of Poland (and husband to Anne Applebaum). It tracks his historical achievements—such as co-architecting the EU\'s Eastern Partnership—and his push for increased European defense rearmament.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Natalia Polyanskaya:</strong> An official under international sanctions who served on the \"People\'s Council\" for the illegal, self-declared separatist Donetsk People\'s Republic (DPR).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Alexander Zakharchenko:</strong> The late pro-Russian separatist leader and Head of the DPR from 2014 until his assassination via an IED explosion at a Donetsk café in August 2018.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. WordPress Blog Data (<em>\"Ongoing Stories of My Soul\"</em>)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The latter half of the document transitions into a meta-log of a WordPress site authored by a user named Deborah Hall<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. It includes titles, dates, metadata, and brief snippets of chronological blog posts written between 2016 and May 21, 2026<sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup><sup></sup>. Notable post topics include:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fact-Checking &amp; Research Notes (2026):</strong> Brief essay write-ups covering data breaches (National Public Data breach and Florida real estate leaks) , clarifying claims surrounding Arsen Avakov\'s resignation letter , military voting statutes , and historical spotlights on figures like Lieutenant John L. Bullis or Black literacy in post-Civil War Louisiana.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Personal Essays &amp; Eulogies (2023–2024):</strong> Moving pieces tracking her transition from Blogger to WordPress , answering curious questions from her grandson , and writing a tribute for the late Professor Raj Ayyar.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Historic Commentary (2016–2017):</strong> Older entries documenting a 2017 satirical or open open letter to Donald Trump, an analysis of school testing metrics (<em>\"If Dr. Seuss Took ISTEP\"</em>), and an emotional reflection written by Hall as an educator coping with burying students or remembering September 11th.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please let me know if you would like me to unpack a specific profile, verify a timeline, or extract any particular piece of data found within this text!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Geopolitical Biographies &amp; Profile Entries','','inherit','closed','closed','','156-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 10:57:31','2026-05-21 10:57:31','',156,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=157',0,'revision','',0),
(158,1,'2026-05-21 11:01:35','2026-05-21 11:01:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://img5tv.cdnvideo.ru/webp/shared/files/202605/1_2576585.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov on Putin\'s visit to China</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov Calls Putin\'s Visit to the PRC \"Packed\" and \"Extremely Productive\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Russian President Vladimir Putin\'s official visit to the People\'s Republic of China proved to be extremely packed and yielded concrete results. Kremlin Press Secretary Dmitry Peskov stated this on May 21 during a briefing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The visit to China proceeded—as is typically the case with our strategic, privileged partner—in a packed, substantive, and extremely productive manner,\" said Dmitry Peskov.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Peskov, the Declaration on Building a Multipolar World and International Relations of a New Type, signed by Russia and China, holds particular significance. As the Kremlin spokesman noted, this document will provide additional impetus for the further strengthening of the strategic partnership and allied ties between Moscow and Beijing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Putin\'s two-day official visit concluded on May 20. During the trip, the Russian leader held talks with PRC Chairman Xi Jinping, while representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Peskov on Putin\'s Visit to China','','trash','open','open','','peskov-on-putins-visit-to-china__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=158',0,'post','',0),
(159,1,'2026-05-21 11:01:35','2026-05-21 11:01:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov on Putin\'s visit to China</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov Calls Putin\'s Visit to the PRC \"Packed\" and \"Extremely Productive\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Russian President Vladimir Putin\'s official visit to the People\'s Republic of China proved to be extremely packed and yielded concrete results. Kremlin Press Secretary Dmitry Peskov stated this on May 21 during a briefing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The visit to China proceeded—as is typically the case with our strategic, privileged partner—in a packed, substantive, and extremely productive manner,\" said Dmitry Peskov.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Peskov, the Declaration on Building a Multipolar World and International Relations of a New Type, signed by Russia and China, holds particular significance. As the Kremlin spokesman noted, this document will provide additional impetus for the further strengthening of the strategic partnership and allied ties between Moscow and Beijing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Putin\'s two-day official visit concluded on May 20. During the trip, the Russian leader held talks with PRC Chairman Xi Jinping, while representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Peskov on Putin\'s Visit to China','','inherit','closed','closed','','158-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 11:01:35','2026-05-21 11:01:35','',158,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=159',0,'revision','',0),
(160,1,'2026-05-21 11:04:29','2026-05-21 11:04:29','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://img5tv.cdnvideo.ru/webp/shared/files/202605/1_2576585.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov on Putin\'s visit to China</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peskov Calls Putin\'s Visit to the PRC \"Packed\" and \"Extremely Productive\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Russian President Vladimir Putin\'s official visit to the People\'s Republic of China proved to be extremely packed and yielded concrete results. Kremlin Press Secretary Dmitry Peskov stated this on May 21 during a briefing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The visit to China proceeded—as is typically the case with our strategic, privileged partner—in a packed, substantive, and extremely productive manner,\" said Dmitry Peskov.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Peskov, the Declaration on Building a Multipolar World and International Relations of a New Type, signed by Russia and China, holds particular significance. As the Kremlin spokesman noted, this document will provide additional impetus for the further strengthening of the strategic partnership and allied ties between Moscow and Beijing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Putin\'s two-day official visit concluded on May 20. During the trip, the Russian leader held talks with PRC Chairman Xi Jinping, while representatives of the Russian and Chinese delegations signed 21 joint documents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Peskov on Putin\'s Visit to China','','inherit','closed','closed','','158-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 11:04:29','2026-05-21 11:04:29','',158,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=160',0,'revision','',0),
(161,1,'2026-05-21 11:26:06','2026-05-21 11:26:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for this comprehensive and well-organized breakdown. I\'ve verified your summary against the actual World Socialist Web Site homepage content from mid-May 2026, and your categorization accurately reflects the major stories and editorial perspective featured on the site [[1]][[3]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown correctly captures several key thematic threads running through WSWS coverage during this period:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Verified Major Headlines:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The US-Israeli war on Iran and the Strait of Hormuz blockade disrupting global energy markets [[13]][[15]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Trump administration\'s $1.776 billion \"Anti-Weaponization Fund\" controversy [[26]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Nexteer Automotive workers forcing a UAW strike vote after rejecting contracts [[2]][[3]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Germany\'s €10 billion civil defense initiative framed as wartime preparation [[14]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Ebola public health emergency amid US withdrawal from WHO and aid cuts [[16]][[17]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Türkiye\'s ICBM unveiling and global militarization trends [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Notable Editorial Framing:</strong><br>The WSWS consistently analyzes these events through a Marxist lens, emphasizing:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The role of imperialist competition in driving global conflict</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Rank-and-file worker struggles against both corporate management and union bureaucracies</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The connection between war abroad and austerity/domestic repression at home</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The necessity of independent working-class political organization</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>One clarification:</strong> While your summary is largely accurate, the WSWS homepage shows the Ebola death toll cited as \"at least 118 dead in the DRC and Uganda\" rather than a confirmed global total [[31]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Is there a particular aspect of these developments you\'d like to explore further? For example:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analysis of specific labor struggles (Nexteer, UC workers, LIRR)?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The geopolitical implications of the Iran conflict?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The public health dimensions of the Ebola/hantavirus coverage?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The WSWS\'s political perspective on building anti-war movements?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m happy to help dig deeper into any of these topics or search for additional context on specific events.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','World Socialist Web Site...','','trash','open','open','','world-socialist-web-site__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=161',0,'post','',0),
(162,1,'2026-05-21 11:26:06','2026-05-21 11:26:06','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you for this comprehensive and well-organized breakdown. I\'ve verified your summary against the actual World Socialist Web Site homepage content from mid-May 2026, and your categorization accurately reflects the major stories and editorial perspective featured on the site [[1]][[3]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your breakdown correctly captures several key thematic threads running through WSWS coverage during this period:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Verified Major Headlines:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The US-Israeli war on Iran and the Strait of Hormuz blockade disrupting global energy markets [[13]][[15]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Trump administration\'s $1.776 billion \"Anti-Weaponization Fund\" controversy [[26]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Nexteer Automotive workers forcing a UAW strike vote after rejecting contracts [[2]][[3]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Germany\'s €10 billion civil defense initiative framed as wartime preparation [[14]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Ebola public health emergency amid US withdrawal from WHO and aid cuts [[16]][[17]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Türkiye\'s ICBM unveiling and global militarization trends [[30]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Notable Editorial Framing:</strong><br>The WSWS consistently analyzes these events through a Marxist lens, emphasizing:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The role of imperialist competition in driving global conflict</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Rank-and-file worker struggles against both corporate management and union bureaucracies</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The connection between war abroad and austerity/domestic repression at home</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The necessity of independent working-class political organization</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>One clarification:</strong> While your summary is largely accurate, the WSWS homepage shows the Ebola death toll cited as \"at least 118 dead in the DRC and Uganda\" rather than a confirmed global total [[31]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Is there a particular aspect of these developments you\'d like to explore further? For example:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analysis of specific labor struggles (Nexteer, UC workers, LIRR)?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The geopolitical implications of the Iran conflict?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The public health dimensions of the Ebola/hantavirus coverage?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The WSWS\'s political perspective on building anti-war movements?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'m happy to help dig deeper into any of these topics or search for additional context on specific events.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','World Socialist Web Site...','','inherit','closed','closed','','161-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 11:26:06','2026-05-21 11:26:06','',161,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=162',0,'revision','',0),
(163,1,'2026-05-21 11:41:35','2026-05-21 11:41:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes, there is substantial evidence of DPR/LPR influence operations in Italy. Here\'s what has been documented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>DPR/LPR Representation Offices in Italy</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since 2016, the DPR and LPR have operated unofficial representation offices in <strong>Turin, Verona, and Messina</strong>, though these are not recognized by Italian authorities [[58]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Turin</strong>: Led by Eliseo Bertolasi and Maurizio Marrone, who launched a \"representational office of the Donetsk People\'s Republic\" in December 2016 [[59]][[64]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Verona</strong>: Headed by Palmarino Zoccatelli [[59]][[61]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Messina</strong>: Led by Professor Daniele Makris, president of the \"Messina Per il Donbass\" organization [[59]][[60]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ukraine has repeatedly protested these offices. In 2020, President Zelensky called on Italy\'s Prime Minister to close these illegal offices [[67]], and Ukraine sent formal protest notes to Italy\'s Foreign Ministry [[65]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Italian Propagandists Operating from Occupied Donetsk</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Andrea Lucidi and Vincenzo Lorusso</strong> are two Italians living in Russian-occupied Donetsk who actively promote Kremlin narratives:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They organize RT-branded propaganda film screenings across Italy, despite EU sanctions on RT [[50]][[51]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Lorusso founded the <strong>Donbass Italia</strong> channel and organized unofficial distribution of Russian propaganda content [[52]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Lucidi obtained Russian citizenship in 2025 and has been living in Russia since 2022 [[55]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They promote films like \"Voci dal Donbass\" (Voices from Donbas), \"Bambini del Donbass\" (Children of Donbas), and \"Maidan, la strada verso la guerra\" [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Vittorio Nicola Rangeloni</strong> is another key figure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Started his propaganda career in 2015 in occupied Donetsk and Luhansk territories, then moved to Mariupol [[41]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Described as a \"reporter and foreign fighter in the Donbas\" who manages pro-Russian influence operations [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Published a book titled \"Donbass: Le mie cronache di guerra\" (Donbass: My War Chronicles) [[45]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>\"Cultural Organizations\" as Propaganda Platforms</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Organizations like <strong>Russia Emilia Romagna</strong> and <strong>Vento dell\'Est</strong> present themselves as cultural groups promoting Russian culture, but actually serve as platforms for Kremlin propaganda [[29]]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Russia Emilia Romagna</strong> attempted to hold a conference titled \"Mariupol: Revival After the War\" in January 2025, but local authorities banned it [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They use typical Russian propaganda rhetoric including \"fascist occupation regime of Kyiv\" and justify Stalin\'s policies [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Vento dell\'Est</strong> organized a photo exhibition titled \"10 Years of War in Donbas\" and events about the so-called \"persecution\" of the Ukrainian Orthodox Church of the Moscow Patriarchate [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Coordinated Influence Campaign</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These operations are part of a broader Russian influence effort in Italy:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Over a 60-day period (January 1-March 1, 2025), content from these networks reached an estimated <strong>1.84 million users</strong> with <strong>4.03 million impressions</strong> on social media [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They coordinate with Telegram groups like <strong>Verona per la Libertà</strong> (which pivoted from anti-lockdown protests to pro-Kremlin content) and receive support from Italian politicians like Stefano Valdegamberi [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In February 2025, Lorusso presented a petition with 23,000 signatures to Russian Foreign Ministry spokesperson Maria Zakharova, who described it as a \"historic\" expression of solidarity [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The campaign aims to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Undermine European support for Ukraine by portraying Russia as a liberator rather than an aggressor</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Legitimize Russian occupation of Ukrainian territories</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Erode trust in Western media [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This represents a sophisticated, multi-layered influence operation combining offline events, social media campaigns, and direct coordination with Russian officials.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','DPR/LPR Representation Offices in Italy','','trash','open','open','','dpr-lpr-representation-offices-in-italy__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=163',0,'post','',0),
(164,1,'2026-05-21 11:41:35','2026-05-21 11:41:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes, there is substantial evidence of DPR/LPR influence operations in Italy. Here\'s what has been documented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>DPR/LPR Representation Offices in Italy</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since 2016, the DPR and LPR have operated unofficial representation offices in <strong>Turin, Verona, and Messina</strong>, though these are not recognized by Italian authorities [[58]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Turin</strong>: Led by Eliseo Bertolasi and Maurizio Marrone, who launched a \"representational office of the Donetsk People\'s Republic\" in December 2016 [[59]][[64]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Verona</strong>: Headed by Palmarino Zoccatelli [[59]][[61]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Messina</strong>: Led by Professor Daniele Makris, president of the \"Messina Per il Donbass\" organization [[59]][[60]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ukraine has repeatedly protested these offices. In 2020, President Zelensky called on Italy\'s Prime Minister to close these illegal offices [[67]], and Ukraine sent formal protest notes to Italy\'s Foreign Ministry [[65]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Italian Propagandists Operating from Occupied Donetsk</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Andrea Lucidi and Vincenzo Lorusso</strong> are two Italians living in Russian-occupied Donetsk who actively promote Kremlin narratives:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They organize RT-branded propaganda film screenings across Italy, despite EU sanctions on RT [[50]][[51]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Lorusso founded the <strong>Donbass Italia</strong> channel and organized unofficial distribution of Russian propaganda content [[52]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Lucidi obtained Russian citizenship in 2025 and has been living in Russia since 2022 [[55]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They promote films like \"Voci dal Donbass\" (Voices from Donbas), \"Bambini del Donbass\" (Children of Donbas), and \"Maidan, la strada verso la guerra\" [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Vittorio Nicola Rangeloni</strong> is another key figure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Started his propaganda career in 2015 in occupied Donetsk and Luhansk territories, then moved to Mariupol [[41]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Described as a \"reporter and foreign fighter in the Donbas\" who manages pro-Russian influence operations [[43]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Published a book titled \"Donbass: Le mie cronache di guerra\" (Donbass: My War Chronicles) [[45]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>\"Cultural Organizations\" as Propaganda Platforms</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Organizations like <strong>Russia Emilia Romagna</strong> and <strong>Vento dell\'Est</strong> present themselves as cultural groups promoting Russian culture, but actually serve as platforms for Kremlin propaganda [[29]]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Russia Emilia Romagna</strong> attempted to hold a conference titled \"Mariupol: Revival After the War\" in January 2025, but local authorities banned it [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They use typical Russian propaganda rhetoric including \"fascist occupation regime of Kyiv\" and justify Stalin\'s policies [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Vento dell\'Est</strong> organized a photo exhibition titled \"10 Years of War in Donbas\" and events about the so-called \"persecution\" of the Ukrainian Orthodox Church of the Moscow Patriarchate [[29]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Coordinated Influence Campaign</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These operations are part of a broader Russian influence effort in Italy:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Over a 60-day period (January 1-March 1, 2025), content from these networks reached an estimated <strong>1.84 million users</strong> with <strong>4.03 million impressions</strong> on social media [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>They coordinate with Telegram groups like <strong>Verona per la Libertà</strong> (which pivoted from anti-lockdown protests to pro-Kremlin content) and receive support from Italian politicians like Stefano Valdegamberi [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In February 2025, Lorusso presented a petition with 23,000 signatures to Russian Foreign Ministry spokesperson Maria Zakharova, who described it as a \"historic\" expression of solidarity [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The campaign aims to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Undermine European support for Ukraine by portraying Russia as a liberator rather than an aggressor</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Legitimize Russian occupation of Ukrainian territories</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Erode trust in Western media [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This represents a sophisticated, multi-layered influence operation combining offline events, social media campaigns, and direct coordination with Russian officials.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','DPR/LPR Representation Offices in Italy','','inherit','closed','closed','','163-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 11:41:35','2026-05-21 11:41:35','',163,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=164',0,'revision','',0),
(165,1,'2026-05-21 12:03:26','2026-05-21 12:03:26','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes, there is substantial evidence of foreign influence operations specifically targeting U.S. active-duty military personnel. Here\'s what has been documented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Russia: Social Media Targeting of U.S. Troops</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Methods and Objectives</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Reflexive Control Strategy</strong>: Russian influence operations aim to seed U.S. troops with targeted disinformation to predispose them to make decisions favorable to Moscow [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Focus</strong>: Operations leverage Twitter, Facebook, and closed groups where military affinity networks congregate [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fake Accounts</strong>: Russian operatives have created accounts using military-themed language (\"Proud AMERICAN, wife, mother, conservative, served my country in USMC\") to gain credibility within military communities [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Documented Tactics</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Affinity Group Targeting</strong>: Russia identifies key voices within military communities and amplifies divisive messaging through them [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Exploiting Isolation</strong>: Officials have noted the U.S. military\'s growing separation from civilian society may increase vulnerability to targeted messaging [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Election-Adjacent Messaging</strong>: During 2016 and beyond, Russian accounts amplified themes like \"America First\" that resonated with rank-and-file service members [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>U.S. Response</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Department of Defense has \"amped up\" training and education to help troops identify disinformation [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>U.S. Cyber Command issues regular guidance on identifying adversarial propaganda [[6]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The DoD released social media policies specifically designed to protect against disinformation and fake accounts [[13]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Iran: \"Not Our War\" Campaign</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>The Operation</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Website</strong>: An Iran-backed site called \"Not Our War\" (notourwar.com) specifically targets U.S. veterans and active-duty personnel [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Network</strong>: Part of a larger ecosystem of ~20 Iran-controlled websites masquerading as legitimate U.S. news outlets [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Content Strategy</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Criticizes both major U.S. political parties to foster disillusionment with American democracy</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Promotes pro-Iran narratives, including claims of Iran\'s \"geopolitical supremacy\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Embeds links to explicitly anti-American content, some in Arabic [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Technical Indicators</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Shared web hosting infrastructure with other known Iranian-influenced sites</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Registered through proxy services to obscure origin (Public Domain Registry, India)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses AI-generated profile images on associated social media accounts [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Scope</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Microsoft and Mandiant (Google) have issued alerts about this broader Iranian influence ecosystem targeting the 2024 U.S. election [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Foundation for Defense of Democracies identified over 2,000 Iran-backed social media accounts on X (formerly Twitter) posting election-related content [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>China: Emerging Concerns</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While less publicly documented than Russian or Iranian efforts, U.S. officials have expressed concern about:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Pentagon AI Vulnerability</strong>: Large language models used by the Defense Department have proven susceptible to foreign state propaganda injection [[18]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Academic/Research Penetration</strong>: The Pentagon has published lists of foreign entities engaged in \"problematic activity\" targeting defense-related higher education and R&amp;D [[17]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Long-Term Influence</strong>: Chinese operations often focus on co-opting diaspora communities and shaping elite opinion rather than direct military targeting [[31]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Military Personnel Are Targeted</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Vulnerability</th><th>Exploitation Method</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Trust in Authority</strong></td><td>Disinformation framed as \"insider\" military perspective</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Closed Communities</strong></td><td>Infiltration of private Facebook groups, military forums</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deployment Stress</strong></td><td>Messaging that amplifies doubts about mission legitimacy</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Political Diversity</strong></td><td>Content designed to widen existing ideological divides within ranks</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Family Networks</strong></td><td>Targeting spouses and families who influence service member morale</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>U.S. Countermeasures</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Media Literacy Training</strong>: Pre-deployment and ongoing instruction on identifying misinformation [[6]][[13]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Partnerships</strong>: Coordination with social media companies to remove inauthentic accounts [[9]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Intelligence Sharing</strong>: The proposed Malign Foreign Influence Response Center (authorized in 2020 NDAA) aims to coordinate cross-agency responses [[10]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Force Protection Framing</strong>: Senior leaders now treat information threats as a \"force protection\" issue equivalent to physical threats [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>RAND Research</strong>: Studies explore using \"military influencers\" to build resilience against enemy disinformation [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Key Challenges</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Attribution Difficulty</strong>: Adversaries use deniable proxies, making retaliation complex [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Free Speech Balance</strong>: Countering disinformation without infringing on legitimate expression remains legally and ethically challenging [[7]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Evolution</strong>: As social media shifts to visual/short-form content (TikTok, etc.), detection methods must adapt [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Internal Divisions</strong>: Pre-existing political fissures within the military can be exploited to amplify discord [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Sources: Small Wars Journal analysis of Russian operations [[1]], Stars and Stripes reporting on Iran-backed campaigns [[11]], U.S. Cyber Command guidance [[6]], DoD social media policy releases [[13]], and Foundation for Defense of Democracies research [[11]].</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The targeting of U.S. military personnel represents a sophisticated evolution in foreign influence operations—moving beyond broad public messaging to precision targeting of a highly influential, disciplined, and politically diverse community whose perceptions can shape national security outcomes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','SocMedia Targeting of U.S. Troops','','trash','open','open','','socmedia-targeting-of-u-s-troops__trashed','','','2026-05-21 13:37:00','2026-05-21 13:37:00','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=165',0,'post','',0),
(166,1,'2026-05-21 12:03:26','2026-05-21 12:03:26','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes, there is substantial evidence of foreign influence operations specifically targeting U.S. active-duty military personnel. Here\'s what has been documented:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Russia: Social Media Targeting of U.S. Troops</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Methods and Objectives</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Reflexive Control Strategy</strong>: Russian influence operations aim to seed U.S. troops with targeted disinformation to predispose them to make decisions favorable to Moscow [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Focus</strong>: Operations leverage Twitter, Facebook, and closed groups where military affinity networks congregate [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Fake Accounts</strong>: Russian operatives have created accounts using military-themed language (\"Proud AMERICAN, wife, mother, conservative, served my country in USMC\") to gain credibility within military communities [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Documented Tactics</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Affinity Group Targeting</strong>: Russia identifies key voices within military communities and amplifies divisive messaging through them [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Exploiting Isolation</strong>: Officials have noted the U.S. military\'s growing separation from civilian society may increase vulnerability to targeted messaging [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Election-Adjacent Messaging</strong>: During 2016 and beyond, Russian accounts amplified themes like \"America First\" that resonated with rank-and-file service members [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>U.S. Response</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Department of Defense has \"amped up\" training and education to help troops identify disinformation [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>U.S. Cyber Command issues regular guidance on identifying adversarial propaganda [[6]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The DoD released social media policies specifically designed to protect against disinformation and fake accounts [[13]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Iran: \"Not Our War\" Campaign</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>The Operation</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Website</strong>: An Iran-backed site called \"Not Our War\" (notourwar.com) specifically targets U.S. veterans and active-duty personnel [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Network</strong>: Part of a larger ecosystem of ~20 Iran-controlled websites masquerading as legitimate U.S. news outlets [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Content Strategy</strong>:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Criticizes both major U.S. political parties to foster disillusionment with American democracy</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Promotes pro-Iran narratives, including claims of Iran\'s \"geopolitical supremacy\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Embeds links to explicitly anti-American content, some in Arabic [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Technical Indicators</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Shared web hosting infrastructure with other known Iranian-influenced sites</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Registered through proxy services to obscure origin (Public Domain Registry, India)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses AI-generated profile images on associated social media accounts [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Scope</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Microsoft and Mandiant (Google) have issued alerts about this broader Iranian influence ecosystem targeting the 2024 U.S. election [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The Foundation for Defense of Democracies identified over 2,000 Iran-backed social media accounts on X (formerly Twitter) posting election-related content [[11]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>China: Emerging Concerns</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While less publicly documented than Russian or Iranian efforts, U.S. officials have expressed concern about:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Pentagon AI Vulnerability</strong>: Large language models used by the Defense Department have proven susceptible to foreign state propaganda injection [[18]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Academic/Research Penetration</strong>: The Pentagon has published lists of foreign entities engaged in \"problematic activity\" targeting defense-related higher education and R&amp;D [[17]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Long-Term Influence</strong>: Chinese operations often focus on co-opting diaspora communities and shaping elite opinion rather than direct military targeting [[31]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Military Personnel Are Targeted</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><thead><tr><th>Vulnerability</th><th>Exploitation Method</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Trust in Authority</strong></td><td>Disinformation framed as \"insider\" military perspective</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Closed Communities</strong></td><td>Infiltration of private Facebook groups, military forums</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deployment Stress</strong></td><td>Messaging that amplifies doubts about mission legitimacy</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Political Diversity</strong></td><td>Content designed to widen existing ideological divides within ranks</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Family Networks</strong></td><td>Targeting spouses and families who influence service member morale</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>U.S. Countermeasures</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Media Literacy Training</strong>: Pre-deployment and ongoing instruction on identifying misinformation [[6]][[13]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Partnerships</strong>: Coordination with social media companies to remove inauthentic accounts [[9]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Intelligence Sharing</strong>: The proposed Malign Foreign Influence Response Center (authorized in 2020 NDAA) aims to coordinate cross-agency responses [[10]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Force Protection Framing</strong>: Senior leaders now treat information threats as a \"force protection\" issue equivalent to physical threats [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>RAND Research</strong>: Studies explore using \"military influencers\" to build resilience against enemy disinformation [[4]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Key Challenges</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Attribution Difficulty</strong>: Adversaries use deniable proxies, making retaliation complex [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Free Speech Balance</strong>: Countering disinformation without infringing on legitimate expression remains legally and ethically challenging [[7]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform Evolution</strong>: As social media shifts to visual/short-form content (TikTok, etc.), detection methods must adapt [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Internal Divisions</strong>: Pre-existing political fissures within the military can be exploited to amplify discord [[1]]</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Sources: Small Wars Journal analysis of Russian operations [[1]], Stars and Stripes reporting on Iran-backed campaigns [[11]], U.S. Cyber Command guidance [[6]], DoD social media policy releases [[13]], and Foundation for Defense of Democracies research [[11]].</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The targeting of U.S. military personnel represents a sophisticated evolution in foreign influence operations—moving beyond broad public messaging to precision targeting of a highly influential, disciplined, and politically diverse community whose perceptions can shape national security outcomes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','SocMedia Targeting of U.S. Troops','','inherit','closed','closed','','165-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 12:03:26','2026-05-21 12:03:26','',165,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=166',0,'revision','',0),
(167,1,'2026-05-21 13:36:24','2026-05-21 13:36:24','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Who we are</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Our website address is: https://ajsbsd.net.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Comments</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor&#8217;s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Media</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Cookies</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select &quot;Remember Me&quot;, your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Embedded content from other websites</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Who we share your data with</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">How long we retain your data</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">What rights you have over your data</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Where your data is sent</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong class=\"privacy-policy-tutorial\">Suggested text: </strong>Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n','Privacy Policy','','inherit','closed','closed','','3-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 13:36:24','2026-05-21 13:36:24','',3,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=167',0,'revision','',0),
