(177,1,'2026-05-21 15:54:02','2026-05-21 15:54:02','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If my writing has brought you comfort or clarity, you can support this space directly:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Crypto Donations</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>TRX: <code>THVdx6YTu47WXndYHqYz7NcUE5QscMNfu5</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Thank you for keeping reflective writing alive.</em> ✦</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Support <a href=\"/\">ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org</a> with TRON (TRX). Help keep reflective writing alive — no ads, just soulful stories. Crypto donations welcome. ✦</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Support This Soul Work','','inherit','closed','closed','','169-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 15:54:02','2026-05-21 15:54:02','',169,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=177',0,'revision','',0),
(178,1,'2026-05-21 15:55:13','2026-05-21 15:55:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>In the Name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit. Amen.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beloved in Christ, we gather today in sorrow and in hope, to commend to the infinite mercy of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ, the souls of His faithful servants, Jo and Jackie, who have departed from this earthly life to enter into the eternal presence of our Heavenly Father. As the Psalmist declares, \"Precious in the sight of the Lord is the death of His saints\" [[16]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>I. THE OPENING PRAYER</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>O Lord our God, Master of life and death, Keeper of souls and bodies, we stand before Your holy altar today with heavy hearts yet steadfast faith, to pray for the repose of the souls of Your departed servants. You who numbered the days of each, who called them from the womb, who guided their steps through the valleys and over the mountains of this temporal life, we beseech You: receive them now into Your heavenly kingdom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the tradition of our Holy Armenian Apostolic Church, we lift our voices in prayer, knowing that our prayers for the departed are not in vain, but are expressions of our love and our hope in Your boundless mercy [[14]]. For death is not the end, O Lord, but a passage from corruption to incorruption, from toil to rest, from sorrow to joy eternal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>II. ON THE LIFE AND SERVICE OF JO</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We remember today, O Christ our God, Your servant Jo, whom You called to serve her people with courage and compassion. Born in the year of our Lord 1974, she walked this earth for forty-two years, a brief candle in the expanse of eternity, yet one that burned brightly with the fire of love for her fellow man [[3]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a Member of Parliament, she was called to bat for the voiceless, to stand for the oppressed, to be a light in the darkness of injustice. Like the Good Samaritan who stopped to tend to the wounded stranger, Jo saw in every face the image of Christ, in every cry for help the voice of her Master calling her to service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She was a woman of conviction, O Lord, who believed that we are more alike than un alike, that our common humanity transcends the boundaries of nation, of creed, of circumstance. These words, spoken in the fullness of her faith, now echo in the halls of heaven as her eternal testimony.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On that fateful day in June of 2016, when violence stole her from this earth in Birstall, she was but forty-one years of age, a rising star in the firmament of British politics, a mother, a wife, a daughter, a sister, a friend [[4]]. The manner of her departure was sudden, was violent, was incomprehensible to our有限 minds. Yet You, O Lord, who see the end from the beginning, who hold all times and seasons in Your hands, received her soul with the tenderness of a father welcoming home his beloved child.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We pray, O Merciful One, that You forgive her every sin committed in thought, word, or deed. Wash her in the blood of the Lamb that was slain from the foundation of the world. Clothe her in the white robes of the redeemed, and grant her a place at the marriage supper of the Lamb.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>III. ON THE LIFE AND SERVICE OF JACKIE</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And we remember also, O God of all comfort, Your faithful servant Jackie, born in the year 1963, who served as a Representative of her people in the Congress of the United States [[6]]. For nearly a decade, from 2013 until her departure in 2022, she stood as a voice for her constituents in Indiana, bearing their burdens, presenting their needs, laboring in the vineyard of public service [[6]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the third day of August in the year 2022, near the town of Nappanee, her earthly journey came to an abrupt end in a tragic accident that also claimed the lives of two of her devoted staffers and another driver [[14]]. In an instant, O Lord, the temporal was exchanged for the eternal, the seen for the unseen, the mortal for the immortal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fifty-nine years she sojourned in this valley of tears, fifty-nine years of service, of faith, of dedication to the calling You had placed upon her life. Like the wise virgins who kept their lamps trimmed and burning, she was about her Father\'s business when You called her home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We lift to You, O Christ, our prayers for her soul. Forgive her trespasses, O Lord, as she forgave those who trespassed against her. Grant her rest in the bosom of Abraham, where pain and sorrow and sighing have fled away. Number her among the righteous who shine forth as the sun in the kingdom of their Father.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>IV. ON THE NATURE OF OUR MORTALITY</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What are we, O Lord, but dust and ashes? What is our life but a vapor that appears for a little time and then vanishes away? The flower of the field, in all its glory, is cut down by the scythe of death. The grass withers, the flower fades, but the word of our God stands forever.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These two women, Jo and Jackie, were taken from us in the prime of their service, in the fullness of their dedication. To our human eyes, it seems untimely, seems cruel, seems incomprehensible. Yet Your ways are not our ways, O Lord, nor are Your thoughts our thoughts. As the heavens are higher than the earth, so are Your ways higher than our ways.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Armenian tradition, we observe periods of mourning—seven days, forty days, six months, a year—for these fixed times remind us that grief has its season, but hope is eternal [[21]]. The fortieth day holds special significance, for it is believed that on this day, the soul completes its journey to the presence of God [[25]]. Today, we stand in that sacred space between sorrow and hope, between loss and gain, between the grave and the resurrection.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>V. BIBLICAL REFLECTIONS ON SERVICE AND SACRIFICE</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our Lord Jesus Christ said, \"Greater love has no one than this, than to lay down one\'s life for his friends.\" Both Jo and Jackie, in their own ways, laid down their lives in service to others. They did not live for themselves alone, but for the communities they served, for the principles they held dear, for the vision of a better world that burned in their hearts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like Moses, who led his people though he would not enter the Promised Land himself, they labored for a future they might not see. Like Deborah, they stood as leaders in times that required courage and conviction. Like Dorcas, they were full of good works and alms which they did.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Apostle Paul reminds us, \"We are confident, yes, well pleased rather to be absent from the body and to be present with the Lord.\" Though we mourn their absence from us, we rejoice in their presence with Christ. Though our eyes are dimmed with tears, the eyes of faith see them clothed in glory, crowned with righteousness, standing before the throne of God.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>VI. PRAYERS FOR THE DEPARTED</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Armenian Apostolic tradition, we pray for the departed, not because we doubt Your mercy, O Lord, but because we believe in the communion of saints, the bond of love that transcends the grave [[16]]. Every service in our Holy Church includes supplications for the departed, for we are one body in Christ, and when one member suffers, all suffer together; when one member is honored, all rejoice together [[12]].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>We pray for Jo:</em><br>Eternal rest grant unto her, O Lord, and let perpetual light shine upon her. May her soul and the souls of all the faithful departed, through the mercy of God, rest in peace. Amen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Forgive her, O Christ, every sin she committed in this life, whether knowingly or unknowingly, whether in youth or in maturity, whether in word or in deed or in thought. You alone are without sin; all others have transgressed Your commandments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Receive her into the kingdom of heaven, where the saints and martyrs, the prophets and apostles, the righteous of all ages, dwell in unending joy. Grant her the reward of her labors, the crown of righteousness which You have promised to all who love Your appearing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>We pray for Jackie:</em><br>Eternal rest grant unto her, O Lord, and let perpetual light shine upon her. May her soul and the souls of all the faithful departed, through the mercy of God, rest in peace. Amen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Have mercy upon her, O God, according to Your great mercy. According to the multitude of Your compassions, blot out her transgressions. Wash her thoroughly from her iniquity, and cleanse her from her sin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Grant her rest in the land of the living, in the mansions You have prepared for those who love You. Number her among the wise virgins who entered in with the bridegroom to the marriage feast. Let her hear those blessed words: \"Well done, good and faithful servant; you were faithful over a few things, I will make you ruler over many things. Enter into the joy of your lord.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>VII. COMFORT FOR THE BEREAVED</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To the families of Jo and Jackie—to the husbands who lost their wives, to the children who lost their mothers, to the parents who lost their daughters, to the siblings who lost their sisters, to the friends who lost their companions—we offer the comfort of the Gospel.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Blessed are those who mourn, for they shall be comforted. This is not the comfort of empty words, nor the solace of mere platitudes, but the comfort of the Holy Spirit, the Paraclete, the Helper who intercedes for us with groanings too deep for words.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your loss is real, your grief is valid, your tears are seen by the Father who counts each one. Yet we do not grieve as those who have no hope. For if we believe that Jesus died and rose again, even so God will bring with Him those who sleep in Jesus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the Armenian tradition, families gather after the funeral to share a meal, to break bread together, to remember the departed with love [[25]]. This is not mere custom, but a profound theology: that even in death, there is communion; even in loss, there is sharing; even in sorrow, there is the breaking of bread that points to the heavenly banquet where all tears shall be wiped away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>VIII. THE HOPE OF RESURRECTION</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We believe, O Lord, in the resurrection of the dead. We believe that as Christ was raised from the dead, never to die again, so too shall all who are in Him be raised to life eternal. The grave is not the end; the tomb is not the final word; death is not the victor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Christ is risen from the dead, trampling down death by death, and upon those in the tombs bestowing life!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is our hope, this is our faith, this is the anchor of our souls. That we shall see our departed ones again, not as they were in their frailty and mortality, but transformed, glorified, perfected in Christ. That the last enemy, death, shall be destroyed. That God shall be all in all.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jo and Jackie are not gone; they have gone before. They are not lost; they have been found in Christ. They are not dead; they sleep in Jesus, awaiting the trumpet call of the archangel, the voice of God, the resurrection morning.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>IX. FINAL BLESSING AND COMMENDATION</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And now, O Lord, we commit to Your keeping the souls of Jo and Jackie. Into Your hands, O Father, we commend their spirits. Receive them, we pray, into the eternal habitations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>May the angels lead them into paradise; may the martyrs come to welcome them and take them to the holy city, the new Jerusalem. May choirs of angels welcome them and lead them to the bosom of Abraham, and where Lazarus is poor no longer, may they find eternal rest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Eternal rest grant unto them, O Lord, and let perpetual light shine upon them. May they rest in peace, and may their memory be eternal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit, be glory, honor, worship, and adoration, now and forever, and unto the ages of ages. Amen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>X. THE FINAL PRAYER</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>O God of the living and the dead, who appeared to our fathers and to all the saints who have pleased You from the beginning of the world, look upon us, Your unworthy servants, who pray before You. Receive the souls of Jo and Jackie into Your kingdom, into the land of the living, into the bosom of Abraham.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Forgive them every offense, every transgression, every sin. You alone are holy, You alone are righteous, You alone are without blemish. All others have sinned and fall short of Your glory. Yet You sent Your only-begotten Son to be the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only, but for the sins of the whole world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Grant them, O Lord, the reward of the righteous. Grant them the crown of life that does not fade away. Grant them to stand at Your right hand on the day of judgment, to hear the blessed words: \"Come, you blessed of My Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And to us who remain, grant strength to bear our grief, grace to fulfill our days, faith to trust in Your promises, and hope to look beyond the grave to the resurrection and the life. May we so live that when our end comes, we may depart in peace, having kept the faith, having finished our course, having fought the good fight.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For Yours is the kingdom, and the power, and the glory, of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, now and forever, and unto the ages of ages. Amen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>ALLELUIA, ALLELUIA, ALLELUIA.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Rest in peace, Jo. Rest in peace, Jackie. Your labor is ended, your warfare is accomplished, your race is run. Enter into the joy of your Lord.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>May your memory be eternal, and may your souls rest in the paradise of delight, where the voices of those who keep the festival are unceasing, and the joy of those who behold the ineffable beauty of the Lord is everlasting.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Amen. Amen. Amen.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center; margin:2rem 0;\">\n  If these words resonated, you can <a href=\"/support/\" style=\"color:#00D4AA; font-weight:600;\">support this space with TRON</a>. ✦\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','A EULOGY FOR TWO ANGELS','','inherit','closed','closed','','58-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 15:55:13','2026-05-21 15:55:13','',58,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=178',0,'revision','',0),
(179,1,'2026-05-21 15:56:28','2026-05-21 15:56:28','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\"></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Everything wonderful starts on paper. It begins as a faint thought, a half-formed question, a quiet observation about the world. Then, someone picks up a pen, opens a notebook, or steps into a classroom and gives that thought a voice. For nearly half a century, Professor Raj Ayyar did exactly that. He did not merely teach philosophy; he lived it. He did not just share ideas; he invited others to think, feel, and grow alongside him. His story, like the best of human narratives, does not end with a final chapter. It continues in the minds he shaped, the conversations he sparked, and the quiet dignity he brought to every room he entered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born in India, Raj Ayyar’s intellectual journey began at St. Stephen’s College in Delhi, an institution long celebrated for nurturing independent thought and moral courage. There, he discovered that education is not about memorizing answers, but about learning how to ask better questions. This curiosity carried him across the Atlantic to the United States, where he found his true calling in the American classroom. From 1981 to 2000, he served as a professor at East Florida State College, teaching Philosophy, Humanities, and World Religions to a diverse array of students. He approached each lesson not as a transmission of facts, but as an invitation to wonder. Whether discussing ancient texts, ethical dilemmas, or the nature of human belief, he encouraged his students to think critically, speak honestly, and listen deeply.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beyond the lecture hall, Prof. Ayyar shared his voice with the broader public through radio broadcasting. In an era when media was still largely analog, his programs offered listeners thoughtful reflections, literary insights, and musical discoveries. Later, he continued his teaching journey part-time at several colleges in the San Francisco Bay Area, staying engaged with evolving academic conversations while maintaining his signature blend of warmth and intellectual rigor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 2000s, drawn by family ties and a renewed sense of purpose, he returned to India. Between 2008 and 2013, he taught at St. Joseph’s College and Christ University in Bangalore, where he became known for his approachable demeanor and his insistence that learning must serve life, not just career. In 2014, he joined IIIT-Delhi as a Visiting Professor, a role that allowed him to bridge the humanities with emerging technology. He taught courses such as Critical and Creative Thinking, Perspectives on Knowledge, Philosophy of Religion, and Theory and Practice of Engineering Ethics. In an institution focused on innovation, he reminded students that progress without moral reflection is incomplete, and that technology must always serve human dignity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Those who studied under him often described him as a “truant in philosophy.” The phrase was never meant as criticism. Rather, it captured his gentle refusal to be confined by academic orthodoxy. He drew deeply from the works of Henri Bergson, whose ideas about time, intuition, and creative evolution resonated with his own belief in the fluid, unpredictable nature of human experience. He also engaged with A.N. Whitehead’s process philosophy, which views reality not as static objects, but as dynamic relationships. Through these lenses, Prof. Ayyar practiced what a tribute later called a “Bergsonian critique of ignorance”: a lifelong commitment to questioning assumptions, embracing uncertainty, and choosing understanding over dogma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His personal life reflected the same integrity he taught in the classroom. He was remembered as a true egalitarian, someone who “never cared for high and low.” He treated janitors and deans, freshmen and visiting scholars, with the same quiet respect. As a gay man in a world that has not always been welcoming to those who live differently, he knew intimately “what it meant to be kept apart.” Yet he never allowed exclusion to breed bitterness. Instead, he transformed that experience into empathy, using his classroom as a sanctuary where diverse voices were honored, and where every student could feel seen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the global pandemic arrived in 2020, Prof. Ayyar made a deeply personal choice. He moved to Bangalore to care for his aging father, stepping away from formal teaching to fulfill a quiet duty of love. It was a season that reflected his lifelong belief that human connection matters more than professional titles. He continued to read, write, and reflect, maintaining his blog under the banner <em>Ongoing Stories of My Soul</em>. The title was no accident. He understood that a life well-lived leaves behind more than credentials or publications. It leaves behind ways of seeing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Professor Raj Ayyar passed away in early June 2023. The announcement from IIIT-Delhi was simple: “With a heavy heart we bid adieu to Prof. Raj Ayyar today.” But those who knew him understood that farewells are never truly final for those who teach us how to think. His legacy lives in every student who chooses curiosity over cynicism, compassion over indifference, and dialogue over division. It lives in the quiet moments when someone pauses to ask, “What if I’m wrong?” or “How can I understand this better?” It lives in the belief that education is not about filling minds, but about lighting fires.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The phrase that opens his blog—<em>Everything wonderful starts on paper</em>—is more than a tagline. It is a philosophy. Ideas begin as sketches. Conversations start as drafts. Change is born when someone dares to write down a thought, share it, and invite others to build upon it. Prof. Ayyar understood this deeply. He knew that teaching, at its best, is an act of trust: the trust that a single question can ripple outward, that a single conversation can shift a perspective, that a single life lived with integrity can quietly reshape the world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We do not honor such teachers by placing them on pedestals. We honor them by continuing the work they began. By reading widely. By listening carefully. By treating every person with dignity. By refusing to let fear replace wonder. By keeping our souls open to new stories, new questions, and new beginnings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The paper may eventually yellow. The pens may run dry. But the stories they carried? Those endure. And as long as we keep turning the page, his story remains very much alive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center; margin:2rem 0;\">\n  If these words resonated, you can <a href=\"/support/\" style=\"color:#00D4AA; font-weight:600;\">support this space with TRON</a>. ✦\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','The Life and Legacy of Professor Raj Ayyar','','inherit','closed','closed','','56-revision-v1','','','2026-05-21 15:56:28','2026-05-21 15:56:28','',56,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=179',0,'revision','',0);
