. It was a premier facility for the construction, nuclear refueling, and heavy maintenance of the U.S. Navy\'s submarine fleet. Its closure consolidated Pacific submarine operations primarily to Puget Sound.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. Alameda Naval Air Station &amp; Shipyard (California)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Targeted in 1993 and officially shuttered in 1997.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Situated directly on the San Francisco Bay, Alameda was a massive homeport for Pacific Fleet aircraft carriers, engineering laboratories, and deep-water berthing. Closing Alameda structurally moved the Navy\'s major California presence entirely south to San Diego.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. Charleston Naval Shipyard (South Carolina)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Recommended for closure in 1993 and deactivated in 1996.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> This was one of the largest employers in South Carolina and a critical Atlantic hub. It specialized in repairing and modernizing nuclear submarines and surface vessels. Its closure stripped a massive amount of dry-dock capacity from the East Coast.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. Homestead Air Force Base (Florida)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Realigned and heavily drawn down following 1993.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Located just south of Miami, the base was devastated by Hurricane Andrew in 1992. Rather than fully rebuilding it to its massive Cold War-era operational capacity, the Clinton administration utilized the 1993 BRAC round to officially close its major active-duty operations and realign it into a much smaller Air Reserve Station, removing a primary frontline fighter base near the Caribbean.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">5. K.I. Sawyer Air Force Base (Michigan)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Scheduled for closure in the 1993 round and shut down in 1995.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Located in Michigan\'s Upper Peninsula, K.I. Sawyer was an essential Strategic Air Command (SAC) base during the Cold War. It housed B-52 nuclear bombers and KC-135 tankers designed to fly over the Arctic Circle in the event of a conflict with the Soviet Union. Its closure dismantled an essential northern-tier aerial defense runway.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">6. Plattsburgh Air Force Base (New York)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Closed during the 1993 BRAC round and officially shuttered in 1995.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Similar to K.I. Sawyer, Plattsburgh was another major northern-tier Strategic Air Command base located near the Canadian border. It hosted FB-111 bombers and refueling tankers. Its closure completely eliminated the active-duty Air Force bomber presence in the northeastern United States.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">7. Fort Ord (California)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Originally flagged at the end of the Bush administration, the formal decommissioning and massive land-transfer process took place under Clinton in 1994.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Located on the Monterey Bay coastline, Fort Ord was one of the largest expanses of U.S. Army training grounds in the country and the primary home of the 7th Infantry Division (Light).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">8. Naval Air Station Barbers Point (Hawaii)</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Closure:</strong> Recommended for closure in the 1993 BRAC round and officially closed in 1999.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Strategic Impact:</strong> Known as the \"Crossroads of the Pacific,\" Barbers Point was the primary base for land-based maritime surveillance, anti-submarine warfare aircraft, and long-range Pacific reconnaissance flights. Operations were consolidated into the nearby Marine Corps Base Hawaii (Kaneohe Bay), reducing the standalone naval aviation footprint in the archipelago.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Analytical Perspective:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the strategic community, these closures are viewed through two very different lenses:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Official View:</strong> The Clinton administration and Congress defended these actions as a necessary \"Peace Dividend.\" With the Soviet Union collapsed, maintaining massive, redundant Cold War infrastructure was deemed an unnecessary drain on taxpayers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Alternative/Sovereign View:</strong> Analysts like Skousen argue that the rapid downsizing of these major bases—especially major shipyards, bomber facilities, and repair depots—permanently damaged America\'s domestic military surge capacity, leaving the homeland more vulnerable to long-term foreign threats by centralizing military assets into fewer, highly targeted regional hubs.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC)','','inherit','closed','closed','','230-revision-v1','','','2026-05-23 01:30:18','2026-05-23 01:30:18','',230,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=238',0,'revision','',0),
(239,1,'2026-05-23 04:35:43','2026-05-23 04:35:43','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The lethal maritime campaign in the Caribbean—known militarily as <strong>Operation Southern Spear</strong>—is the starkest real-world example of how this \"undeclared grey-zone warfare\" operates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since September 2025, the U.S. military has bypassed traditional maritime law-enforcement protocols (like stopping, boarding, and arresting suspects) and has instead used drone and naval airstrikes to directly blow up speedboats and vessels transiting the Caribbean and Eastern Pacific.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This operation highlights how the lines between crime, war, and international borders are being blurred.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. The Legal Ruse: \"Narcoterrorism\" as a State of War</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under standard international law, the U.S. Coast Guard or Navy cannot simply open fire on a suspected drug-smuggling vessel in international waters. They are bound by strict law-enforcement frameworks: they must track the boat, demand to board it, search it, and bring the suspects to a port to face a trial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To bypass this legal hurdle, the Trump administration designated Latin American drug cartels and criminal networks (such as the Venezuelan gang <em>Tren de Aragua</em>) as <strong>narcoterrorists</strong>.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By applying the label of \"terrorism,\" the U.S. executive branch argued that the United States is in a state of <strong>active armed conflict</strong> with these cartels.<sup></sup> This rhetorical shift attempts to swap out domestic law enforcement rules for the <strong>Laws of Armed Conflict (LOAC)</strong>.<sup></sup> Under the laws of war, an enemy target does not need to be read their rights or arrested—they can simply be destroyed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. What is Happening on the Ground (and Water)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The reality of Operation Southern Spear has triggered immense international backlash, congressional scrutiny, and a formal Pentagon Inspector General investigation due to the exact issue you pointed out: the identity of the people on the boats.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Scale:</strong> Over 50 airstrikes have been carried out, resulting in the deaths of nearly 200 people.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The \"Double-Tap\" Controversy:</strong> In several instances—most notably the initial strike in September 2025 and an incident in October—crew members who survived the initial missile blast were filmed clinging to the capsized wreckage. U.S. forces subsequently struck the wreckage a second time to ensure total destruction, justifying it under the umbrella of \"military self-defense\" and eliminating the target.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Are They Cartel Bosses or Fishermen?</strong> The administration has rarely provided public evidence of drugs on the destroyed boats, relying instead on intelligence that the vessels were \"transiting known smuggling routes.\" Independent journalistic investigations have identified several of the deceased as impoverished day-laborers and fishermen from coastal villages in Venezuela and Trinidad and Tobago. Local families maintain that these men were hired out of desperation to transport cargo or fish, with no knowledge or meaningful connection to international drug syndicates.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. The Geopolitical Undercurrent</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While framed publicly as a harsh escalation in the \"War on Drugs\" to stop fentanyl and cocaine supply lines, the timing and location of the Caribbean strikes are deeply geopolitical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The maritime campaign ramped up alongside heavy military pressure against Venezuela, culminating in the high-profile U.S. raid and capture of Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By utilizing deniable or fast-moving airstrikes against vessels departing the region, the U.S. has effectively maintained a hot military blockade in the southern Caribbean without ever having to go to Congress to formally declare war on a sovereign neighbor. It is the modern textbook definition of using kinetic, wartime force under a different semantic name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Operation Southern Spear','','publish','closed','closed','','operation-southern-spear','','','2026-05-23 04:35:44','2026-05-23 04:35:44','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?page_id=239',0,'page','',0),
(240,1,'2026-05-23 04:35:43','2026-05-23 04:35:43','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The lethal maritime campaign in the Caribbean—known militarily as <strong>Operation Southern Spear</strong>—is the starkest real-world example of how this \"undeclared grey-zone warfare\" operates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since September 2025, the U.S. military has bypassed traditional maritime law-enforcement protocols (like stopping, boarding, and arresting suspects) and has instead used drone and naval airstrikes to directly blow up speedboats and vessels transiting the Caribbean and Eastern Pacific.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This operation highlights how the lines between crime, war, and international borders are being blurred.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. The Legal Ruse: \"Narcoterrorism\" as a State of War</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under standard international law, the U.S. Coast Guard or Navy cannot simply open fire on a suspected drug-smuggling vessel in international waters. They are bound by strict law-enforcement frameworks: they must track the boat, demand to board it, search it, and bring the suspects to a port to face a trial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To bypass this legal hurdle, the Trump administration designated Latin American drug cartels and criminal networks (such as the Venezuelan gang <em>Tren de Aragua</em>) as <strong>narcoterrorists</strong>.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By applying the label of \"terrorism,\" the U.S. executive branch argued that the United States is in a state of <strong>active armed conflict</strong> with these cartels.<sup></sup> This rhetorical shift attempts to swap out domestic law enforcement rules for the <strong>Laws of Armed Conflict (LOAC)</strong>.<sup></sup> Under the laws of war, an enemy target does not need to be read their rights or arrested—they can simply be destroyed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. What is Happening on the Ground (and Water)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The reality of Operation Southern Spear has triggered immense international backlash, congressional scrutiny, and a formal Pentagon Inspector General investigation due to the exact issue you pointed out: the identity of the people on the boats.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The Scale:</strong> Over 50 airstrikes have been carried out, resulting in the deaths of nearly 200 people.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>The \"Double-Tap\" Controversy:</strong> In several instances—most notably the initial strike in September 2025 and an incident in October—crew members who survived the initial missile blast were filmed clinging to the capsized wreckage. U.S. forces subsequently struck the wreckage a second time to ensure total destruction, justifying it under the umbrella of \"military self-defense\" and eliminating the target.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Are They Cartel Bosses or Fishermen?</strong> The administration has rarely provided public evidence of drugs on the destroyed boats, relying instead on intelligence that the vessels were \"transiting known smuggling routes.\" Independent journalistic investigations have identified several of the deceased as impoverished day-laborers and fishermen from coastal villages in Venezuela and Trinidad and Tobago. Local families maintain that these men were hired out of desperation to transport cargo or fish, with no knowledge or meaningful connection to international drug syndicates.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. The Geopolitical Undercurrent</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While framed publicly as a harsh escalation in the \"War on Drugs\" to stop fentanyl and cocaine supply lines, the timing and location of the Caribbean strikes are deeply geopolitical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The maritime campaign ramped up alongside heavy military pressure against Venezuela, culminating in the high-profile U.S. raid and capture of Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro.<sup></sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By utilizing deniable or fast-moving airstrikes against vessels departing the region, the U.S. has effectively maintained a hot military blockade in the southern Caribbean without ever having to go to Congress to formally declare war on a sovereign neighbor. It is the modern textbook definition of using kinetic, wartime force under a different semantic name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Operation Southern Spear','','inherit','closed','closed','','239-revision-v1','','','2026-05-23 04:35:43','2026-05-23 04:35:43','',239,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?p=240',0,'revision','',0),
(241,1,'2026-05-23 11:32:16','2026-05-23 11:32:16','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Will Lehman\'s Appeal to Nexteer Workers</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Analysis from the World Socialist Web Site (Marxist/Internationalist viewpoint)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔑 Core Argument</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The article frames the Nexteer contract fight not as an isolated labor dispute, but as a <strong>microcosm of the global class struggle</strong>: workers vs. a union bureaucracy aligned with management and the capitalist state.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>\"This struggle is about more than one contract. It is about who controls the workplace, the union and ultimately society itself.\"</em> — Will Lehman</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🎯 Key Themes (WSWS Lens)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1️⃣ Rank-and-File Power vs. Bureaucratic Betrayal</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The UAW apparatus is portrayed as <strong>actively obstructing</strong> worker militancy: blocking strike votes, extending contracts without consent, threatening workers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Lehman\'s solution: <strong>elected, accountable strike committees</strong> controlled by shop-floor workers—not appointed officials.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>WSWS sees this as essential to rebuilding working-class power independent of the Democratic Party and corporate unionism.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2️⃣ Concessions as Class Warfare</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The article historicizes wage erosion: parts workers once earned near Big Three parity; today\'s <code>19.50–19.50–</code>27/hr tier system equals <strong>real wages from 20+ years ago</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adjusted for inflation, workers \"would be making more than $45/hour today\"—framing current offers as <strong>systematic wealth transfer from labor to capital</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3️⃣ Internationalism Over Nationalism</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Rejects company threats to move jobs to Mexico/Poland as divide-and-rule tactics.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Calls for <strong>cross-border rank-and-file solidarity</strong> via the <em>International Workers Alliance of Rank-and-File Committees (IWA-RFC)</em>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Explicitly anti-imperialist: links rising living costs to US war spending (e.g., conflict with Iran).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4️⃣ Strike Readiness as Strategic Imperative</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Warns against letting the union treat the 86% strike authorization as a \"pressure valve\" while production continues.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Demands <strong>$1,000/week strike pay</strong> (not $500) to sustain a real fight.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Urges Big Three workers to honor picket lines—building <strong>sector-wide leverage</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🧭 Political Orientation</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table class=\"has-fixed-layout\"><tbody><tr><td>Element</td><td>WSWS Position</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Union bureaucracy</strong></td><td>A layer integrated into management; obstacle to struggle</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Democratic Party</strong></td><td>Instrument of capital; workers need independent political organization</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Strategy</strong></td><td>Rank-and-file committees → strike action → broader class confrontation</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Goal</strong></td><td>Socialist transformation: workers\' control of production and society</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">🔗 Broader Context (Per WSWS)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This fight is linked to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>🚗 Contract battles at American Axle, Dana, Magna, Bridgewater</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>🏭 Rank-and-file slates at Ford Rouge, CNH Industrial</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>🎓 Student/academic worker strikes (Harvard, UMass Boston)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>🌍 Global inflation, war, and capitalist crisis</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The publication sees Lehman\'s campaign as part of a <strong>renewed international workers\' movement</strong> challenging both corporate power and the traditional labor leadership that accommodates it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">⚠️ Critical Note</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The WSWS represents the <strong>Socialist Equality Party (Fourth International)</strong>, a Trotskyist organization. Its analysis is explicitly revolutionary socialist: it does not seek to \"reform\" the UAW or capitalism, but to build independent working-class power aimed at overthrowing the capitalist system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Readers seeking alternative perspectives may also consult coverage from:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Mainstream labor media (<em>Labor Notes</em>, <em>In These Times</em>)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Business press (<em>Reuters</em>, <em>Bloomberg</em>)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Other leftist outlets (<em>Jacobin</em>, <em>Dissent</em>)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Want help finding primary sources, union statements, or contrasting analyses on the Nexteer struggle? I can assist with that.</em> 🛠️</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','📰 WSWS Perspective','','publish','closed','closed','','%f0%9f%93%b0-wsws-perspective','','','2026-05-23 11:32:16','2026-05-23 11:32:16','',0,'https://ongoingstoriesofmysoul.org/?page_id=241',0,'page','',0),
